(verb
  :name "time/delta"
  :library "time"
  :kind "null"
  :signature "(time/delta unit) -> number"
  :summary "Returns the elapsed time since the last frame in the specified unit (ms, s, m, h, d)."
  :explanation "This verb measures the time delta (difference) between the current frame and the previous frame, returning the interval in a named unit: milliseconds (ms), seconds (s), minutes (m), hours (h), or days (d). It is useful for frame-rate-independent animation and simulation: instead of assuming fixed frame duration, multiply velocity or acceleration by the delta to ensure consistent motion regardless of frame rate. The unit parameter is a symbol (or string) that specifies the output unit."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(on-tick (lambda ()\n  (let ((dt (time/delta 's)))\n    (entity/move! 'ball (list (* 100 dt) 0)))))" :note "Ball moves 100 units per second, regardless of frame rate.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(on-tick (lambda ()\n  (let* ((dt (time/delta 'ms))\n         (acceleration 200)\n         (new-vel (+ (entity/vel 'player) (* acceleration dt 0.001))))\n    (entity/set-vel! 'player new-vel))))" :note "Physics simulation: acceleration applied over milliseconds, scaled to per-frame impulse.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (tick-simulation ctx)\n  (let* ((dt (time/delta 's))\n         (vel (ctx-get 'velocity ctx))\n         (friction 0.99)\n         (new-vel (* vel (expt friction dt)))\n         (pos (+ (ctx-get 'position ctx) (* vel dt))))\n    (next 'tick-simulation (ctx-set 'velocity new-vel (ctx-set 'position pos ctx)))))\n\n(on-tick tick-simulation)" :note "Simulation state machine: delta drives position and velocity decay, independent of frame rate.")
  )
  :caveats ("Unit must be one of: 'ms, 's, 'm, 'h, 'd (or equivalent string symbols)." "Unknown unit may cause an error or 'nan; always validate unit spelling." "First frame may report a large delta if no prior frame time is recorded; initialize timing carefully." "Very slow or paused execution (e.g., debugging breakpoints) may return a large delta; clamp if needed.")
  :drawbacks ("Relies on accurate clock synchronization; system clock skew or manual timing manipulation breaks assumptions." "Conversion between units is fixed; custom units are not supported." "If frame rate varies dramatically, large deltas may cause instability (overshooting). Apply max-delta clamping: (min dt max-dt)." "Not suitable for real-time hard constraints; elapsed time is measured after computation.")
  :usecases ("Frame-rate-independent physics and animation." "Velocity and acceleration simulation." "Adaptive timing loops (slow on low-end devices, fast on high-end)." "Measuring elapsed time in user-friendly units.")
  :related ("time/when" "time/during" "time/every-ms" "on-tick" "frame")
  :learn (:concept "Frame-rate-independent delta time: multiply rates and accelerations by dt to decouple simulation from frame rate." :prerequisites ("on-tick") :progression "Master time/delta for physics; then learn time/every-ms (fixed intervals) and time/when (event timing) for higher-level temporal control."))

(verb
  :name "time/during"
  :library "time"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(time/during predicate clause) → clause"
  :summary "Create a clause that runs its body only while a condition remains true."
  :explanation "time/during wraps a predicate and a clause together, gating execution: the clause fires each frame only as long as the predicate evaluates to truthy. Once the predicate becomes false, the clause stops running. This is useful for time-boxed animations, conditional behaviors, or guarded state machines. It composes with big-bang and other loop forms."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(define (start ctx)\n  (big-bang\n    (list (time/during (lambda () (< (game/frame (ctx-get 'game-id ctx)) 60))\n                       (to-draw (lambda (s) '(render)))))))" :note "Run the render clause only for the first 60 frames.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define (start ctx)\n  (big-bang\n    (list (time/during (lambda () (ctx-get 'is-active? ctx))\n                       (to-draw (lambda (s) '(render))))\n          (on-key (lambda (k s) s)))))" :note "Render while is-active? is true in state; other clauses run unconditionally.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (start ctx)\n  (let ((game-id (big-bang\n                   (list (time/during\n                          (lambda () (and (ctx-get 'running? ctx)\n                                         (> (ctx-get 'health ctx) 0)))\n                          (to-draw (lambda (s) (paint-grid s))))\n                        (time/until (lambda () (= (ctx-get 'health ctx) 0))\n                                    (to-draw (lambda (s) '(game-over))))))))\n    game-id))" :note "Nest time/during and time/until to model a two-phase loop: active gameplay, then game-over screen.")
  )
  :caveats ("The predicate is re-evaluated every frame; side-effects in the predicate will run each frame." "If the predicate is false on the first frame, the clause never runs." "Once false, the clause remains dormant for the rest of the loop; there is no re-activation.")
  :drawbacks ("For one-time delayed actions, time/until or time/when may be clearer." "Predicates that depend on mutable state must be careful about state consistency.")
  :usecases ("Conditional animations that stop when a flag becomes false." "Guarding a rendering phase while an entity is alive." "Time-boxing a behavior: run input handling only during active gameplay.")
  :related ("time/until" "time/when" "time/every-ms" "big-bang" "to-draw" "on-key")
  :learn (:concept "Conditional gate on a clause: predicate-driven activation." :prerequisites ("big-bang" "to-draw") :progression "Learn time/until next (the inverse — run until a condition), then time/when (one-shot trigger)."))

(verb
  :name "time/every-ms"
  :library "time"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(time/every-ms milliseconds clause) → clause"
  :summary "Wrap a clause so it fires at most once per N milliseconds."
  :explanation "time/every-ms throttles a clause's execution to a fixed wall-clock interval. The clause is allowed to run at most once every N milliseconds, regardless of frame rate. This decouples behavior from frame rate and is essential for audio polling, network requests, or expensive computations that should not run every frame. The internal timer tracks elapsed wall time, not game frames."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(define (start ctx)\n  (big-bang\n    (list (time/every-ms 100\n                         (to-draw (lambda (s) (audio-play 'click)))))))" :note "Play a click sound at most once per 100 milliseconds, decoupled from frame rate.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define (start ctx)\n  (big-bang\n    (list (time/every-ms 500\n                         (to-draw (lambda (s)\n                                   (let ((count (ctx-get 'poll-count ctx)))\n                                     (ctx-set 'poll-count (+ count 1) s)))))\n          (on-key (lambda (k s) s)))))" :note "Increment a counter every 500ms, while input handling runs every frame.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (start ctx)\n  (big-bang\n    (list (time/every-ms 1000\n                         (to-draw (lambda (s)\n                                   (let ((health (ctx-get 'health s)))\n                                     (if (> health 0)\n                                         (ctx-set 'health (- health 1) s)\n                                         s)))))\n          (time/during (lambda () (ctx-get 'is-active? ctx))\n                       (on-key (lambda (k s) s))))))" :note "Poison damage ticks every second; input handling only while active. Orthogonal time scales.")
  )
  :caveats ("The threshold is wall-clock time, not game frames, so it is immune to frame-rate stutters." "If the loop is paused or suspended, wall time keeps advancing; the clause may fire unexpectedly on resume." "Very small intervals (< 16ms) may appear to fire every frame on 60 Hz displays.")
  :drawbacks ("Cannot be frame-locked; use time/across or on-tick if you need frame-exact timing." "Interval is approximate — actual elapsed time may vary by a few milliseconds.")
  :usecases ("Polling external state at a fixed cadence (e.g., reading a sensor every 200ms)." "Damage or regeneration ticks decoupled from frame rate." "Rate-limiting expensive computations (physics solve, pathfinding) to 30 Hz while rendering at 60 Hz." "Audio-driven behavior (e.g., emit a visual pulse every beat of a song).")
  :related ("time/during" "time/across" "time/when" "on-tick" "audio-beat?")
  :learn (:concept "Wall-clock throttling: decouple behavior from frame rate." :prerequisites ("big-bang" "to-draw" "ctx-get" "ctx-set") :progression "Learn time/across next (frame-locked intervals), then compose with audio verbs like audio-beat?"))

(verb
  :name "time/then"
  :library "time"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(time/then clause-a clause-b) → clause"
  :summary "Sequentially compose two clauses: run clause-a, then when it completes, run clause-b."
  :explanation "time/then chains two clauses in sequence, like a promise chain or a state transition. The first clause runs until it returns a 'done' signal (or is consumed); then the second clause takes over. This is a fundamental tool for choreography: multi-step animations, narratives, or state machines where each phase must complete before the next begins. It is composable: (time/then a (time/then b c)) chains three clauses."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(define (start ctx)\n  (big-bang\n    (list (time/then (to-draw (lambda (s) (paint-grid s)))\n                     (to-draw (lambda (s) '(game-over)))))))" :note "Render the grid, then render game-over. In practice, done signals control the switch.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define (start ctx)\n  (big-bang\n    (list (time/then (time/every-ms 500\n                                     (to-draw (lambda (s) (audio-play 'tick))))\n                     (to-draw (lambda (s) (card-emit 'event-finished))))\n          (on-key (lambda (k s) s)))))" :note "Emit a tick every 500ms, then emit an event when the first clause finishes.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (start ctx)\n  (big-bang\n    (list (time/then\n            (time/during (lambda () (< (game/frame (ctx-get 'game-id ctx)) 120))\n                        (to-draw (lambda (s) (paint-grid s))))\n            (time/then\n              (time/every-ms 300 (to-draw (lambda (s) (audio-play 'win))))\n              (to-draw (lambda (s) (card-emit 'game-complete)))))\n          (on-key (lambda (k s) s)))))" :note "Choreograph: play grid for 120 frames, then emit victory sound every 300ms, then emit completion event.")
  )
  :caveats ("The done signal is typically generated by time/until or explicitly returned from a clause." "If neither clause ever produces done, the second clause will never run." "Nesting time/then deeply can become hard to read; consider extracted helper predicates.")
  :drawbacks ("Strict sequencing: both clauses cannot run concurrently. Use a list of clauses for parallel behaviors." "Debugging long chains can be tedious; add logging or breakpoints in the transition predicates.")
  :usecases ("Cutscene choreography: intro animation → dialogue → action sequence." "State machines with multi-step behaviors: idle → attack-startup → attack → recovery." "Tutorial sequences: show instruction → wait for confirmation → advance." "Loading screens: splash → progress bar → ready.")
  :related ("time/during" "time/until" "time/when" "big-bang" "done")
  :learn (:concept "Sequential composition of clauses: pipeline choreography." :prerequisites ("big-bang" "to-draw" "time/during") :progression "Combine with time/until and time/when to build expressive timelines."))

(verb
  :name "time/until"
  :library "time"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(time/until predicate clause) → clause"
  :summary "Run a clause, and signal done once a condition becomes true."
  :explanation "time/until is the complement of time/during: the clause runs freely until the predicate flips true, at which point the clause signals completion. Use this to gate a behavior until an end condition is met (e.g., \"run this animation until the health reaches zero\"). Unlike time/during, which keeps a clause dormant while the predicate is false, time/until keeps the clause active and checks for an end condition. It pairs naturally with time/then to chain behaviors."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(define (start ctx)\n  (big-bang\n    (list (time/until (lambda () (= (ctx-get 'health ctx) 0))\n                      (to-draw (lambda (s) (paint-grid s)))))))" :note "Render the grid until health reaches zero, then stop.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define (start ctx)\n  (big-bang\n    (list (time/until (lambda () (> (game/frame (ctx-get 'game-id ctx)) 300))\n                      (to-draw (lambda (s) (card-emit 'frame s))))\n          (on-key (lambda (k s) s)))))" :note "Emit a frame event every frame, until we've run for 300 frames.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (start ctx)\n  (big-bang\n    (list (time/then\n            (time/until (lambda () (>= (ctx-get 'score ctx) 100))\n                       (to-draw (lambda (s) (paint-grid s))))\n            (time/every-ms 100\n                          (to-draw (lambda (s) (audio-play 'victory)))))\n          (on-key (lambda (k s) s)))))" :note "Play the grid until score hits 100, then play victory sound every 100ms.")
  )
  :caveats ("The predicate is checked after the clause executes, so the clause runs at least once even if the predicate is true on frame 0." "Once the condition is true, the clause is done and does not re-activate." "The state must be updated externally (via ctx-set or other mutations) for the predicate to change.")
  :drawbacks ("For conditions that should prevent the clause from running at all, use time/during instead." "Predicates that depend on external state (e.g., a flag set by another system) can be fragile.")
  :usecases ("Play an animation until a timer expires." "Render a scene until the player health reaches zero." "Accumulate score or resources until a threshold is met." "Run a loop body until an invariant is violated or a goal is reached.")
  :related ("time/during" "time/when" "time/then" "big-bang" "stop-when")
  :learn (:concept "End-condition gating: run until a flag, then hand off." :prerequisites ("big-bang" "to-draw" "ctx-get" "ctx-set") :progression "Combine with time/then to build multi-phase loops; compare with time/during for the dual pattern."))

(verb
  :name "time/when"
  :library "time"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(time/when predicate clause) → clause"
  :summary "Create a one-shot clause that fires once, the first time a condition becomes true."
  :explanation "time/when is a one-time trigger: the wrapped clause runs exactly once, the first frame the predicate evaluates to true. On all other frames, it is inert. This is distinct from time/during (which keeps running while true) and time/until (which runs until true). Use time/when for single-fire events: a doorway opening when the player arrives, a sound cue on a specific beat, or a transition at the exact moment a condition flips."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(define (start ctx)\n  (big-bang\n    (list (time/when (lambda () (> (ctx-get 'health ctx) 50))\n                     (to-draw (lambda (s) (audio-play 'alarm)))))))" :note "Play the alarm sound once, the first frame health exceeds 50.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define (start ctx)\n  (big-bang\n    (list (time/when (lambda () (audio-beat? (ctx-get 'beat-id ctx)))\n                     (to-draw (lambda (s) (sprite-address 'pulse))))\n          (on-key (lambda (k s) s)))))" :note "Trigger a visual pulse exactly once when the audio beat arrives.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (start ctx)\n  (big-bang\n    (list (time/when (lambda () (= (ctx-get 'phase ctx) 'boss-enter))\n                     (to-draw (lambda (s) (card-emit 'boss-dialogue))))\n          (time/during (lambda () (ctx-get 'is-running? ctx))\n                       (on-key (lambda (k s) s))))))" :note "Emit a dialogue event exactly once when the boss-enter phase begins, while input runs continuously.")
  )
  :caveats ("The clause fires on the first frame the predicate is true, not on the frame it becomes true (if the predicate is already true at loop start, it fires immediately)." "Once fired, the clause never runs again, even if the predicate becomes false and then true again." "The predicate is re-evaluated every frame, so side-effects in the predicate will run until it is true.")
  :drawbacks ("Cannot be re-triggered; for repeating events on a condition, use time/during." "If the condition is false for the entire loop, the clause never runs (which is silent — no error).")
  :usecases ("Play a doorway-open sound the first time the player enters a region." "Emit a tutorial hint the moment the player's score hits a milestone." "Trigger a cutscene the first time a boss is encountered." "Sync a visual effect to the first beat of a song.")
  :related ("time/during" "time/until" "time/every-ms" "big-bang" "audio-beat?")
  :learn (:concept "One-shot trigger: fire once when a condition becomes true, then lock." :prerequisites ("big-bang" "to-draw" "time/during") :progression "Understand the trio (time/during, time/until, time/when) as orthogonal gating strategies; combine with time/then for orchestration."))

; ─── library: topo (27 verbs) ───

(verb
  :name "topo/ball"
  :library "topo"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(topo/ball center radius metric-space) -> set"
  :summary "Compute the closed metric ball {j : d(center,j)≤radius} in a metric space."
  :explanation "topo/ball constructs the closed ball centered at a point, containing all points within a given distance (including the boundary). It is a fundamental topological object: neighborhoods, open covers, and filtrations all build on metric balls. The operation takes a center point, a radius, and a metric space object, and returns the set of all points satisfying the distance constraint. This is deterministic within a given device/precision context. Balls form the basis for Vietoris–Rips complexes and persistent homology computations."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(let ((ms (topo/metric-space '((0 0) (1 0) (0 1) (1 1)))))\n  (topo/ball '(0 0) 1.5 ms))" :note "Find all points within distance 1.5 of the origin in a 2×2 grid.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(let ((pts (list '(0 0) '(1 0) '(2 0) '(3 0))))\n  (let ((ms (topo/metric-space pts)))\n    (length (topo/ball '(1.5 0) 1.0 ms))))" :note "Count points in a 1D line segment within distance 1 of x=1.5.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(let ((evolve-cover (lambda (ms scales)\n                      (map (lambda (eps)\n                            (topo/ball (car (topo/metric-space->points ms))\n                                      eps\n                                      ms))\n                          scales))))\n  (let ((ms (topo/metric-space (list '(0 0) '(1 1) '(2 0)))))\n    (map length (evolve-cover ms '(0 1.0 2.0)))))" :note "Track how the ball size grows over a sequence of scales, showing nested filtration structure.")
  )
  :caveats ("The result includes the boundary (≤, not <); this is the closed ball." "Distance is computed according to the metric in the space object; changing the metric changes the ball." "Computation time grows with the number of points in the metric space.")
  :drawbacks ("topo/ball is a local operation; computing many balls (as in topo/vietoris-rips) may be expensive." "No caching of distances; repeated ball computations recompute all distances." "Limited to finite metric spaces; infinite or continuous spaces require discretization.")
  :usecases ("Building neighborhoods in topology or differential geometry." "Constructing Vietoris–Rips complexes for persistent homology." "Studying how topological features persist as a scale parameter varies.")
  :related ("topo/vietoris-rips" "topo/rips-filtration" "topo/metric-space" "topo/persistence")
  :learn (:concept "Metric balls as the fundamental building block of topology; filtrations parameterized by radius." :prerequisites ("topo/metric-space") :progression "After topo/ball, learn topo/vietoris-rips to build complexes, then topo/persistence for barcode analysis."))

(verb
  :name "topo/betti"
  :library "topo"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(topo/betti complex) -> vector"
  :summary "Compute the Betti vector (β₀, β₁, β₂, …) of a simplicial complex over GF(2)."
  :explanation "topo/betti computes the complete Betti sequence of a complex using homology over the field GF(2) (integers modulo 2). The k-th Betti number β_k counts the number of independent k-dimensional holes: β₀ is the number of connected components, β₁ counts loops (1-dimensional holes), β₂ counts voids (2-dimensional holes), and so on. The Betti vector is a topological signature that is invariant under continuous deformations. This is the summary form of topo/betti-k; it returns the entire sequence in one call."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(let ((tri (topo/complex (list '(0) '(1) '(2) '(0 1) '(1 2) '(0 1 2)))))\n  (topo/betti tri))" :note "Compute Betti vector of a filled triangle: β₀=1 (one component), β₁=0 (no holes).")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(let ((circle (topo/vietoris-rips (list '(1 0) '(0 1) '(-1 0) '(0 -1)) 1.5)))\n  (let ((b (topo/betti circle)))\n    (list (car b) (if (> (length b) 1) (cadr b) 0))))" :note "Build a Vietoris–Rips complex from a circle, extract β₀ and β₁ to verify one component and one loop.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(let ((compare-betti (lambda (complexes)\n                       (map (lambda (c)\n                             (let ((b (topo/betti c)))\n                               (list (length b) (apply + b))))\n                           complexes))))\n  (let ((disk (topo/complex (list '(0) '(1) '(2) '(0 1) '(1 2) '(0 2) '(0 1 2))))\n        (annulus '(\"dummy\")))\n    (compare-betti (list disk annulus))))" :note "Compare topological signatures of multiple complexes; the length and sum of Betti vectors encode different aspects of shape.")
  )
  :caveats ("Computation uses GF(2) (mod 2 arithmetic); torsion information is not captured." "The Betti vector is dimension-capped at 8; asking for β_k with k>8 escalates 'dimension-cap (see topo/betti-k)." "Trailing zero Betti numbers are trimmed from the output; a sphere has [1, 0, 1], not [1, 0, 1, 0, 0, ...].")
  :drawbacks ("Computing Betti requires full homology computation; large complexes may be slow or exhaust memory." "The Euler–Poincaré check is informational; failure indicates a bug in the complex, not in the algorithm." "topo/betti loses information about grading and generators; use topo/homology-gf2 for structural detail.")
  :usecases ("Rapid topological classification of shapes." "Validating simplicial complex construction (via χ check)." "Summarizing persistent homology by extracting Betti at a single scale.")
  :related ("topo/betti-k" "topo/homology-gf2" "topo/euler-char" "topo/persistence" "topo/vietoris-rips")
  :learn (:concept "Homology and Betti numbers as topological invariants; the cycle space and boundary space decomposition." :prerequisites ("topo/complex" "topo/boundary-matrix") :progression "After topo/betti, explore topo/betti-k for single dimensions, then topo/persistence for multi-scale analysis."))

(verb
  :name "topo/betti-curve"
  :library "topo"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(topo/betti-curve filtration dimension) -> list-of-values"
  :summary "Compute β_dimension as a function of scale across a filtration."
  :explanation "topo/betti-curve tracks how a single Betti number β_k evolves as the filtration parameter (usually a radius or distance threshold) increases. It takes a filtration (a sequence of complexes at increasing scales), picks a specific dimension k, and returns the sequence of β_k values at each scale. This is the core of persistent homology visualization: watching β_k birth and death across scales reveals topological features that persist vs. those that are noise. The curve is deterministic within device precision."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(let ((filt (topo/rips-filtration (list '(0 0) '(1 0) '(2 0)) (list 0.5 1.0 1.5))))\n  (topo/betti-curve filt 0))" :note "Track β₀ (components) as a 1D point set is connected by increasing scales.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(let ((pts (list '(0 0) '(1 1) '(-1 1) '(0 -1))))\n  (let ((filt (topo/rips-filtration pts (list 0 1.0 1.5 2.0))))\n    (list (topo/betti-curve filt 0) (topo/betti-curve filt 1))))" :note "Compute β₀ and β₁ curves separately; watch components merge and loops appear.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(let ((detect-feature (lambda (curve min-persistence)\n                        (let loop ((c curve) (i 0) (last-val 0))\n                          (if (null? c) null\n                            (let ((val (car c))\n                                  (delta (abs (- (car c) last-val))))\n                              (if (> delta 0)\n                                (cons (list 'scale i 'change delta) (loop (cdr c) (+ i 1) val))\n                                (loop (cdr c) (+ i 1) val))))))))\n  (let ((filt (topo/rips-filtration (list '(0 0) '(1 0) '(0.5 1)) (list 0 0.5 1.0 1.5))))\n    (detect-feature (topo/betti-curve filt 0) 0)))" :note "Scan a Betti curve for births and deaths to extract persistent features.")
  )
  :caveats ("The filtration must be provided in order of increasing scale; disorder yields meaningless results." "The dimension parameter must be ≤ 8; topo/betti-k enforces this." "A dimension not present in the complex yields β_k = 0 silently; no error is raised.")
  :drawbacks ("topo/betti-curve is a 1D readout; it loses 2D persistence diagram structure (use topo/persistence for diagrams)." "Computing many scales can be expensive; the filtration size directly affects runtime." "No smoothing or interpolation is applied; Betti curves are step functions and can be visually noisy.")
  :usecases ("Visualizing topological birth-death events across a single dimension." "Detecting persistent features in multi-scale point cloud data." "Debugging persistent homology computations by inspecting intermediate Betti values.")
  :related ("topo/rips-filtration" "topo/persistence" "topo/betti" "topo/betti-k")
  :learn (:concept "Persistence parameterization and single-dimensional tracking; the foundation for barcode visualization." :prerequisites ("topo/rips-filtration" "topo/betti-k") :progression "After topo/betti-curve, move to topo/persistence for full 2D diagrams and topo/persistence-entropy for shape statistics."))

(verb
  :name "topo/betti-k"
  :library "topo"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(topo/betti-k complex dimension) -> number"
  :summary "Compute the k-th Betti number β_k over GF(2); dimension >8 → 'dimension-cap."
  :explanation "topo/betti-k computes a single Betti number β_k for a given simplicial complex, where k is the dimension of the topological feature being counted. β₀ is the number of connected components, β₁ counts independent loops, β₂ counts voids, etc. The computation is over GF(2) (the field with two elements), which simplifies linear algebra. This is the scalar version of topo/betti; use it when you need only one dimension. If dimension exceeds 8, the verb escalates 'dimension-cap as a safety limit."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(let ((tri (topo/complex (list '(0) '(1) '(2) '(0 1) '(1 2) '(0 1 2)))))\n  (topo/betti-k tri 0))" :note "Count connected components (β₀) in a filled triangle: result is 1.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(let ((torus-faces (list '(0) '(1) '(2) '(3) '(0 1) '(1 2) '(0 2) '(0 3) '(1 3) '(2 3)\n                          '(0 1 2) '(1 2 3))))\n  (list (topo/betti-k (topo/complex torus-faces) 0)\n        (topo/betti-k (topo/complex torus-faces) 1)\n        (topo/betti-k (topo/complex torus-faces) 2)))" :note "Compute β₀, β₁, β₂ of a torus-like complex manually; should be [1, 2, 1].")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(let ((scan-persistent-feature (lambda (filt dim)\n                                (let ((betti-seq\n                                       (map (lambda (c) (topo/betti-k c dim))\n                                            filt)))\n                                  (let loop ((b betti-seq) (i 0) (prev 0))\n                                    (if (null? b) null\n                                      (let ((delta (- (car b) prev)))\n                                        (if (> delta 0)\n                                          (cons (list 'scale i 'birth) (loop (cdr b) (+ i 1) (car b)))\n                                          (loop (cdr b) (+ i 1) (car b)))))))))\n  (let ((filt (topo/rips-filtration (list '(0 0) '(1 1) '(0 1)) (list 0 1.0 1.5))))\n    (scan-persistent-feature filt 1)))" :note "Track when a 1-dimensional feature (loop) is born across a filtration by monitoring β₁.")
  )
  :caveats ("Dimension >8 escalates 'dimension-cap immediately; no partial computation is attempted." "Computing GF(2) homology loses torsion information; use rational or ℤ homology for that (not implemented in this library)." "If the dimension is absent in the complex (e.g., dimension 2 in a 1-dimensional graph), β_k is 0.")
  :drawbacks ("topo/betti-k computes only one dimension; for the full Betti vector use topo/betti." "Large complexes require full matrix computation, which can be slow." "The dimension cap (8) is hard-coded; no way to exceed it.")
  :usecases ("Querying a single topological feature in a complex." "Iterating over dimensions to build the full Betti vector (as topo/betti does)." "Monitoring a specific feature in a filtration sequence (e.g., tracking loop count).")
  :related ("topo/betti" "topo/boundary-matrix" "topo/homology-gf2" "topo/betti-curve")
  :learn (:concept "Homology in a single dimension; the rank-nullity decomposition of boundary maps." :prerequisites ("topo/complex" "topo/boundary-matrix") :progression "Start with topo/betti-k for one dimension, then topo/betti for all dimensions, then topo/betti-curve for tracking across scales."))

(verb
  :name "topo/bottleneck"
  :library "topo"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(topo/bottleneck barcode-1 barcode-2) -> number"
  :summary "Compute the bottleneck distance between two persistence barcodes (small-diagram approximation)."
  :explanation "The bottleneck distance is a metric on persistence diagrams (or barcodes): it measures the maximum cost of matching one diagram to another under the constraint that unmatched points must map to the diagonal y=x. It is the ℓ∞ (Chebyshev) distance between optimal matchings. This is useful for comparing topological signatures of different point clouds or testing stability under perturbation. The implementation uses a small-diagram approximation suitable for moderate-sized inputs; very large diagrams may need a backend solver."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(let ((b1 (list '(0 1) '(1 2)))\n      (b2 (list '(0 1) '(1 2))))\n  (topo/bottleneck b1 b2))" :note "Two identical barcodes have bottleneck distance 0.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(let ((b1 (list '(0 1) '(2 3)))\n      (b2 (list '(0 1.1) '(2.1 3))))\n  (topo/bottleneck b1 b2))" :note "Small perturbations of births and deaths yield small bottleneck distance (≈0.1).")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(let ((compute-stability (lambda (point-sets epsilon)\n                          (let ((generate-barcodes\n                                 (lambda (pts)\n                                   (let ((filt (topo/rips-filtration pts (list 0 epsilon (* 2 epsilon)))))\n                                     (topo/persistence filt 1)))))\n                            (let ((bc1 (generate-barcodes (car point-sets)))\n                                  (bc2 (generate-barcodes (cadr point-sets))))\n                              (topo/bottleneck bc1 bc2))))))\n  (compute-stability (list (list '(0 0) '(1 0) '(0 1))\n                            (list '(0 0) '(1.01 0) '(0 1)))\n                      1.5))" :note "Measure topological stability: how much do barcodes change under small perturbations of the input point set?")
  )
  :caveats ("Bottleneck distance is symmetric but not translation-invariant in the (birth, death) plane; diagram location matters." "The small-diagram approximation assumes <100 points per barcode; larger inputs escalate 'use-backend." "Near-diagonal noise is handled with a small tolerance; the exact threshold is implementation-defined.")
  :drawbacks ("Bottleneck is ℓ∞, not ℓ²; it is sensitive to a single outlier. For more robust comparison, use Wasserstein distance (not in this library)." "Computing bottleneck for many diagram pairs is expensive; consider batching or sampling for large datasets." "The result is a single number; it does not indicate which features differ or how.")
  :usecases ("Comparing topological signatures of similar point clouds." "Testing stability of persistent homology under noise or perturbation." "Clustering or classifying shapes by their persistence diagrams.")
  :related ("topo/persistence" "topo/rips-filtration" "topo/betti-curve")
  :learn (:concept "Metric on persistence diagrams; optimal matching under Chebyshev distance." :prerequisites ("topo/persistence" "topo/rips-filtration") :progression "After topo/bottleneck, explore topo/total-persistence and topo/persistence-entropy for other barcode statistics."))

(verb
  :name "topo/boundary-matrix"
  :library "topo"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(topo/boundary-matrix complex) -> matrix"
  :summary "Compute the ∂_k boundary matrix over GF(2) for a simplicial complex."
  :explanation "The boundary matrix encodes how simplices of dimension k relate to simplices of dimension k−1 via their faces. Over GF(2) (binary field), each entry is 0 or 1, indicating presence or absence of an incidence. This matrix is the foundation of homology computation: its rank and nullity yield the Betti numbers that measure topological features like connected components, holes, and voids. The boundary operator satisfies ∂∂=0, a key algebraic constraint that makes homology well-defined."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code ";; A triangle (2-simplex) has three edges (1-simplices) as boundaries\n(let ((tri (topo/complex '((0 1 2)))))\n  (topo/boundary-matrix tri))" :note "Smallest example: the 2D boundary matrix of a single triangle, showing which edges bound it.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code ";; Build a complex from two triangles sharing an edge\n(let* ((c (topo/close (topo/complex '((0 1 2) (1 2 3)))))\n       (b (topo/boundary-matrix c))\n       (h (topo/homology-gf2 c)))\n  (list b h))" :note "The boundary matrix encodes shared edges; homology derives Betti numbers from its rank.")
    (:tier "expert" :code ";; Analyze a Rips filtration at one scale to extract homology persistence\n(let* ((rips (topo/vietoris-rips '((0 0) (1 0) (1 1) (0 1)) 1.5))\n       (closed (topo/close rips))\n       (bmat (topo/boundary-matrix closed))\n       (betti (topo/betti closed)))\n  (list 'betti betti 'rank-via-boundary (length bmat)))" :note "In TDA workflows, boundary matrices drive persistence computations; here we inspect structure before computing barcodes.")
  )
  :caveats ("Operates in GF(2), so all arithmetic is mod 2; orientations collapse to presence/absence." "Fuel consumption grows with simplex count; exceeding bitwise capacity returns 'too-many-simplices." "Input complex should be properly closed via topo/close for homology correctness; unclosed complexes may yield spurious Betti numbers." "Returns a sparse bitwise matrix; dense matrix operations on large complexes will be slow.")
  :drawbacks ("GF(2) homology loses information compared to rational or integer coefficients (e.g., torsion becomes invisible)." "Not suitable for real-coefficient homology or cohomology; use linalg or symbolic libraries for finer analysis." "Bitwise representation limits dimension cap to ~8; for higher dimensions, use persistent homology or external tools.")
  :usecases ("Computing Betti numbers (topological invariants) for finite simplicial complexes." "Verifying the Euler–Poincaré formula χ = Σ(−1)ᵏβₖ as a sanity check." "Building persistent homology barcodes by tracking rank changes across a filtration." "Analyzing 2D/3D mesh topology in mesh processing or geometric modeling.")
  :related ("topo/homology-gf2" "topo/betti" "topo/betti-k" "topo/close" "topo/complex" "topo/f-vector" "topo/euler-char")
  :learn (:concept "The boundary operator ∂_k as a linear map, and how its rank determines homology groups." :prerequisites ("topo/complex" "topo/close") :progression "Understand boundary matrices, then move to topo/homology-gf2 for full homology, then topo/persistence for topological features across scales."))

(verb
  :name "topo/close"
  :library "topo"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(topo/close simplices) -> closed-complex"
  :summary "Return the downward closure (all faces) of a set of simplices."
  :explanation "A simplicial complex requires that if a simplex is included, all of its lower-dimensional faces must also be included. The closure operation adds all missing faces to ensure this property. For example, if you include a triangle (3 vertices), closure automatically adds its three edges and three vertices. This is essential before computing homology, since the boundary operator needs the full face lattice to be well-defined. Without closure, Betti number computations become meaningless."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code ";; A single triangle: closure adds its 3 edges and 3 vertices\n(topo/close '((0 1 2)))" :note "One 2-simplex becomes 1 triangle + 3 edges + 3 vertices = 7 simplices total.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code ";; Two triangles sharing an edge; closure deduplicates shared faces\n(let ((t1 '((0 1 2)))\n      (t2 '((1 2 3))))\n  (topo/close (append t1 t2)))" :note "The shared edge (1 2) appears once in the closure, even though it borders both triangles.")
    (:tier "expert" :code ";; Closure as a preprocessing step before building a boundary matrix\n(let* ((raw-simplices '((0 1 2) (1 2 3) (2 3 4)))\n       (closed (topo/close raw-simplices))\n       (f-vec (topo/f-vector closed))\n       (chi (topo/euler-char closed)))\n  (list 'face-counts f-vec 'euler-characteristic chi))" :note "After closure, the complex is ready for topological analysis; f-vector and Euler characteristic are computed on the closed complex.")
  )
  :caveats ("Closure is idempotent: calling topo/close on an already-closed complex returns the same complex." "Does not validate simplex membership; malformed indices are passed through and may cause errors downstream." "Fuel cost scales with total face count; for large or high-dimensional complexes, closure can exceed bitwise capacity." "Order of input simplices is irrelevant; output is always a set (no duplicates).")
  :drawbacks ("Can dramatically increase complex size; a single high-dimensional simplex explodes into exponentially many faces." "For visualization or storage, closure may not be necessary; use it only when algebraic operations (homology, boundary) are needed." "No validation of input simplices; garbage in, garbage out (via downstream errors).")
  :usecases ("Preparing a user-specified set of simplices for homology computation." "Building a well-defined simplicial complex from a face list that may omit lower-dimensional faces." "Verifying that a complex satisfies the closure property before passing to topological algorithms." "Combining multiple simplices or geometric objects that may share faces.")
  :related ("topo/complex" "topo/boundary-matrix" "topo/homology-gf2" "topo/f-vector" "topo/euler-char")
  :learn (:concept "What a simplicial complex is (a set of simplices closed under taking faces), and why closure is a structural requirement." :prerequisites ("topo/complex") :progression "After understanding closure, move to topo/f-vector to count faces by dimension, then topo/euler-char to compute invariants."))

(verb
  :name "topo/complex"
  :library "topo"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(topo/complex simplex-list) -> complex"
  :summary "Build a simplicial complex from a list of simplices without automatic closure."
  :explanation "A simplicial complex is the foundation of algebraic topology: a collection of simplices (vertices, edges, triangles, tetrahedra, …) that is closed under taking faces. This verb takes a bare simplex list and packages it into a complex object that other topological verbs can query and analyze. Unlike topo/close, this does not automatically add missing faces; it returns the complex as specified. If you need a proper closed complex for homology, call topo/close on the result. This separation allows you to construct partial complexes for visualization or incremental algorithms."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code ";; Three vertices form a triangle\n(topo/complex '((0 1 2)))" :note "Single 2-simplex; edges and vertices are not automatically added.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code ";; Explicitly list vertices, edges, and a triangle\n(let ((verts '((0) (1) (2)))\n      (edges '((0 1) (1 2) (0 2)))\n      (tri '((0 1 2))))\n  (topo/complex (append verts edges tri)))" :note "A closed complex built by hand; topo/complex accepts the full list and deduplicates.")
    (:tier "expert" :code ";; Build a complex from a filtration (Rips at different scales)\n(let* ((pts '((0 0) (1 0) (1 1) (0 1)))\n       (rips1 (topo/vietoris-rips pts 0.5))\n       (rips2 (topo/vietoris-rips pts 1.5))\n       (c1 (topo/complex (topo/close rips1)))\n       (c2 (topo/complex (topo/close rips2))))\n  (list 'scale-0.5 (topo/f-vector c1) 'scale-1.5 (topo/f-vector c2)))" :note "Build multiple closed complexes at different scales for persistent homology analysis.")
  )
  :caveats ("Does not enforce closure: if you omit a face of a simplex, the complex remains incomplete." "For homology computation, you must call topo/close first; otherwise boundary matrices will be malformed." "Input list may contain duplicates; topo/complex deduplicates automatically." "Simplex indices must be non-negative integers; out-of-order indices are sorted internally.")
  :drawbacks ("Requires manual face management; for complex polyhedra, closure is much more convenient." "No automatic validation; a syntactically valid complex may be topologically incoherent (e.g., an edge without its vertices)." "For large simplex lists, deduplication cost is linear in the total count.")
  :usecases ("Constructing custom simplicial complexes from explicit face lists." "Building partial complexes for incremental or streaming algorithms." "Combining output from external geometry libraries (e.g., mesh generators) with the topology toolkit." "Testing or analyzing subsets of a larger complex (e.g., lower-dimensional skeleton).")
  :related ("topo/close" "topo/f-vector" "topo/boundary-matrix" "topo/homology-gf2" "topo/vietoris-rips")
  :learn (:concept "What a simplicial complex is, and the difference between a bare simplex list and a well-formed closed complex." :prerequisites () :progression "Build a complex with topo/complex, then close it with topo/close, then analyze with topo/f-vector and topo/boundary-matrix."))

(verb
  :name "topo/components"
  :library "topo"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(topo/components complex) -> list-of-component-sets"
  :summary "Partition the vertices of a complex into connected components."
  :explanation "Two vertices are in the same connected component if a path of edges links them. This verb computes all such components as separate sets. For a single connected graph, there is one component; for a graph with isolated vertices, each isolated vertex is its own component. The Betti number β₀ (the first Betti number) equals the number of connected components, a fundamental topological invariant. Components partition the vertex set and are useful for understanding the large-scale structure of networks, meshes, and point clouds."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code ";; A single triangle is one component\n(let ((c (topo/close (topo/complex '((0 1 2))))))\n  (topo/components c))" :note "Three connected vertices; one component: {0, 1, 2}.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code ";; Two disconnected triangles\n(let ((c (topo/close (topo/complex '((0 1 2) (3 4 5))))))\n  (list (topo/components c)\n        (topo/connected? c)))" :note "Two components: {0,1,2} and {3,4,5}; the complex is not connected.")
    (:tier "expert" :code ";; Count components and verify via Euler characteristic\n(let* ((c (topo/close (topo/complex '((0 1) (2 3) (4 5)))))\n       (comps (topo/components c))\n       (beta0 (length comps))\n       (betti (topo/betti c))\n       (chi (topo/euler-char c)))\n  (list 'num-components beta0 'betti betti 'euler chi))" :note "β₀ = (number of components) is the first Betti number; verify with topo/euler-char.")
  )
  :caveats ("Operates only on the 1-skeleton (edges); higher-dimensional simplices are ignored for connectivity." "An isolated vertex (degree 0) forms its own component." "The order of components in the output list is not guaranteed; treat the result as an unordered partition." "For non-empty complex, at least one component is always returned.")
  :drawbacks ("Does not count components in quotient spaces or with boundary conditions; purely intrinsic connectivity." "For very large complexes, union-find is efficient, but the output itself is large if there are many components." "Does not preserve or compute component properties (size, diameter, etc.); use topo/f-vector or external analysis for that.")
  :usecases ("Determining if a complex is connected (single component)." "Finding isolated regions in a mesh or point cloud." "Computing the first Betti number β₀ (number of connected components)." "Preprocessing for algorithms that require connected input, or analyzing each component separately.")
  :related ("topo/connected?" "topo/betti" "topo/betti-k" "topo/euler-char" "topo/homology-gf2")
  :learn (:concept "Connected components as a partition of the vertex set; the relationship between connectivity and the first Betti number." :prerequisites ("topo/complex" "topo/close") :progression "Compute components, then learn topo/betti to see β₀ in context; relate to topo/euler-char for the full Euler–Poincaré formula."))

(verb
  :name "topo/connected?"
  :library "topo"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(topo/connected? complex) -> #t|#f"
  :summary "Test whether a complex is connected (all vertices reachable via edges)."
  :explanation "A complex is connected if its 1-skeleton (vertices and edges) forms a single connected component; equivalently, there is a path of edges between any two vertices. This is a basic structural test used in mesh processing, network analysis, and topology. A connected complex has exactly one connected component. The result is either #t (connected) or #f (disconnected). This predicate is fast compared to computing all components explicitly, since it can return #f as soon as a disconnection is found."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code ";; A single triangle is connected\n(let ((c (topo/close (topo/complex '((0 1 2))))))\n  (topo/connected? c))" :note "Result: #t (all vertices reachable).")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code ";; Two separate edges are not connected\n(let ((c (topo/close (topo/complex '((0 1) (2 3))))))\n  (topo/connected? c))" :note "Result: #f (vertices 0,1 are disconnected from 2,3).")
    (:tier "expert" :code ";; Use connectivity as a precondition for further analysis\n(let* ((c (topo/close (topo/complex '((0 1 2) (1 2 3) (2 3 4))))))\n  (if (topo/connected? c)\n      (list 'status 'connected 'euler (topo/euler-char c))\n      (list 'status 'disconnected 'components (length (topo/components c)))))" :note "Branch logic: only compute Euler characteristic if connected; otherwise list components.")
  )
  :caveats ("Tests only the 1-skeleton; a complex with vertices and faces but no edges is disconnected." "An empty complex (no vertices) is vacuously #t." "A complex with isolated vertices is #f." "The result depends only on the graph structure, not on higher-dimensional simplices.")
  :drawbacks ("Does not provide details (e.g., which vertices form each component); use topo/components for that." "For disconnected complexes, you may want to analyze each component separately; this predicate does not help with that directly." "No heuristic or approximate connectivity for weighted or metric spaces; this is purely combinatorial.")
  :usecases ("Quickly checking if a mesh or network is in one piece." "Guarding against algorithms that assume connectedness (e.g., certain Euler characteristic formulas)." "Filtering or validating input complexes before expensive homology computations." "Preprocessing for algorithms that require connected domains (e.g., some flow or diffusion solvers).")
  :related ("topo/components" "topo/betti" "topo/betti-k" "topo/euler-char" "topo/homology-gf2")
  :learn (:concept "Graph connectivity: a property of the 1-skeleton; relationship to the first Betti number and the Euler characteristic." :prerequisites ("topo/complex" "topo/close") :progression "Test connectivity with topo/connected?, then explore topo/components for details, and topo/betti for the topological interpretation."))

(verb
  :name "topo/crossing-number"
  :library "topo"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(topo/crossing-number knot-diagram) -> int"
  :summary "Count the number of crossings in a knot diagram."
  :explanation "A knot diagram is a 2D projection of a knot with over/under crossing information. The crossing number is the minimum number of such crossings needed to represent the knot; it is a fundamental knot invariant. Lower crossing numbers are easier to work with, and the unknot (trivial knot) has crossing number 0. This count is the raw crossing tally; for algebraic invariants like the writhe (signed sum of crossings), use topo/writhe. The crossing number helps classify and distinguish knots: for example, the trefoil knot has crossing number 3."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code ";; The unknot has 0 crossings\n(let ((unknot (topo/knot '())))\n  (topo/crossing-number unknot))" :note "Result: 0 (no crossings).")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code ";; A simple trefoil knot (3 crossings)\n(let ((trefoil (topo/knot '((1 5 2 3) (3 1 4 5) (5 3 6 4))))))\n  (list 'crossings (topo/crossing-number trefoil)\n        'writhe (topo/writhe trefoil)))" :note "3 crossings; writhe is the signed sum (−1, 0, or +1 per crossing).")
    (:tier "expert" :code ";; Classify a knot by its crossing number and other invariants\n(let ((k (topo/knot '((1 5 2 3) (3 1 4 5) (5 3 6 4))))))\n  (let ((c-num (topo/crossing-number k))\n        (g (topo/euler-genus k)))\n    (list 'crossing-num c-num 'genus g 'is-unknot (topo/unknot? k))))" :note "Crossing number is one of several knot invariants; used together for classification.")
  )
  :caveats ("Operates on a PD code diagram, not on the knot itself; the same knot can have multiple diagrams with different crossing numbers." "The crossing number returned is that of the *given* diagram, not the minimal crossing number (which requires exhaustive search)." "Malformed PD codes may return errors; use topo/knot to validate and encode first." "Crossing number alone does not uniquely identify a knot; other invariants (writhe, genus) are also needed.")
  :drawbacks ("Does not compute the minimal crossing number; only the crossing count of the provided diagram." "No distinction between knot and link; works for any diagram but semantic meaning depends on context." "For comparison with the unknot, also check topo/unknot? or topo/writhe for independent validation.")
  :usecases ("Classifying knots by complexity (crossing number)." "Comparing knot diagrams to see if they might represent the same knot." "Computing other invariants that depend on crossing count (e.g., bounds on genus or Thurston-Bennequin number)." "Analyzing knot data from external sources (databases, simulations) for statistical properties.")
  :related ("topo/knot" "topo/writhe" "topo/unknot?" "topo/euler-genus")
  :learn (:concept "The crossing number as a knot diagram property and its role in knot classification." :prerequisites ("topo/knot") :progression "Count crossings, compute writhe, and test unknot; then explore higher invariants like genus for full knot classification."))

(verb
  :name "topo/euler-char"
  :library "topo"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(topo/euler-char complex) -> int"
  :summary "Compute the Euler characteristic χ = Σ(−1)ᵏf_k (or V−E for a graph)."
  :explanation "The Euler characteristic is a fundamental topological invariant: the alternating sum of face counts by dimension. For a 2D graph, χ = V − E (vertices minus edges). For a 2D surface, χ = V − E + F (vertices minus edges plus faces). This single number encodes topological structure: a sphere has χ=2, a torus has χ=0, and a projective plane has χ=1. The Euler–Poincaré formula relates χ to Betti numbers: χ = Σ(−1)ᵏβₖ, giving a strong consistency check. The Euler characteristic is invariant under continuous deformations (homeomorphisms), making it a robust topological fingerprint."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code ";; A single edge has χ = 2 − 1 = 1\n(let ((c (topo/close (topo/complex '((0 1))))))\n  (topo/euler-char c))" :note "f_0 = 2 (vertices 0,1), f_1 = 1 (edge); χ = 2−1 = 1.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code ";; A triangle has χ = 3 − 3 + 1 = 1\n(let ((c (topo/close (topo/complex '((0 1 2))))))\n  (list 'face-vector (topo/f-vector c)\n        'euler (topo/euler-char c)))" :note "f_0=3 vertices, f_1=3 edges, f_2=1 triangle; χ = 3−3+1 = 1.")
    (:tier "expert" :code ";; Verify Euler–Poincaré: χ = Σ(−1)ᵏβₖ\n(let* ((c (topo/close (topo/complex '((0 1 2) (1 2 3)))))\n       (h (topo/homology-gf2 c))\n       (chi-direct (topo/euler-char c))\n       (betti (topo/betti c))\n       (chi-from-betti (- (car betti) (cadr betti) (if (> (length betti) 2) (caddr betti) 0))))\n  (list 'euler-direct chi-direct 'euler-from-betti chi-from-betti 'match (= chi-direct chi-from-betti)))" :note "The Euler characteristic computed from f-vector equals that derived from Betti numbers; a consistency sanity-check.")
  )
  :caveats ("Eulerian characteristic is defined for closed (downward-closed) complexes; run topo/close first." "For disconnected complexes, χ sums over all components; a complex with k components has χ ≥ k." "χ is invariant under dimension: a 2D manifold and a 3D manifold with the same topology have the same χ." "For non-orientable surfaces, χ is still well-defined but the geometric interpretation differs (e.g., real projective plane has χ=1, not χ=2).")
  :drawbacks ("χ alone does not uniquely determine a surface: both torus and Klein bottle have χ=0 despite being topologically distinct." "Does not distinguish between manifolds and non-manifolds; a \"bad\" complex may have χ that doesn't correspond to any standard surface." "For higher homological invariants, use topo/betti or topo/homology-gf2 directly.")
  :usecases ("Quick topological fingerprint of a mesh or complex." "Consistency checking: computing χ in two different ways (f-vector vs. Betti numbers) and verifying they agree." "Classifying surfaces by χ (spheres, tori, projective planes, …)." "Analyzing the impact of mesh refinement or simplification on topology.")
  :related ("topo/f-vector" "topo/betti" "topo/betti-k" "topo/homology-gf2" "topo/components" "topo/boundary-matrix")
  :learn (:concept "The Euler characteristic as an alternating sum of face counts, and its role in the Euler–Poincaré formula." :prerequisites ("topo/complex" "topo/close" "topo/f-vector") :progression "Compute Euler characteristic, then verify via topo/betti and topo/homology-gf2; understand the topological classification of surfaces."))

(verb
  :name "topo/euler-genus"
  :library "topo"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(topo/euler-genus knot) -> int"
  :summary "Return the genus of a knot diagram, or an informational lower bound if the genus is not computable."
  :explanation "The genus is a measure of topological complexity: the minimum genus of any orientable surface the knot can bound as a spanning surface. A knot of genus 0 is the unknot; higher genera indicate more complex knots. For many knot diagrams, the genus can be computed exactly via Seifert's algorithm; for others, only a lower bound is available. The genus is a powerful knot invariant that distinguishes many knots that the crossing number alone cannot separate. This verb returns either an exact genus (for diagrams where computation succeeds) or a lower bound (e.g., via 4-ball genus or other bounding techniques)."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code ";; The unknot has genus 0\n(let ((unknot (topo/knot '())))\n  (topo/euler-genus unknot))" :note "Result: 0 (unknot spans a disk, genus 0).")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code ";; A trefoil knot has genus 1\n(let ((trefoil (topo/knot '((1 5 2 3) (3 1 4 5) (5 3 6 4))))))\n  (list 'knot-diagram trefoil\n        'genus (topo/euler-genus trefoil)\n        'crossing-num (topo/crossing-number trefoil)))" :note "Trefoil: genus 1, crossing number 3; genus is a finer invariant.")
    (:tier "expert" :code ";; Use genus to distinguish knots; check consistency with other invariants\n(let* ((k1 (topo/knot '((1 5 2 3) (3 1 4 5) (5 3 6 4))))); trefoil\n       (k2 (topo/knot '((1 5 2 3) (3 1 4 5) (5 3 6 4) (7 9 8 10) (9 7 10 8)))); composite\n       (g1 (topo/euler-genus k1))\n       (g2 (topo/euler-genus k2))\n       (w1 (topo/writhe k1))\n       (w2 (topo/writhe k2)))\n  (list 'knot-1 (list 'genus g1 'writhe w1)\n        'knot-2 (list 'genus g2 'writhe w2)))" :note "Compare genera and writhe; genus is invariant under orientation, writhe depends on chosen orientation.")
  )
  :caveats ("The returned genus is an informational property of the knot, not always an exact value; some diagrams return only lower bounds." "Genus computation is expensive for complex diagrams; the verb may take longer than crossing-number or writhe." "Genus depends on the topological type of the knot, not its diagram; different diagrams of the same knot have the same genus." "For links (multiple components), the genus may be defined differently; this verb assumes a single knot.")
  :drawbacks ("Genus alone does not uniquely classify knots; two distinct knots can have the same genus." "Seifert surface algorithms are computationally intensive; for large diagrams or exhaustive searches, external libraries may be needed." "If computation fails, the verb returns a conservatively low bound; this may not be the true genus.")
  :usecases ("Comparing knot invariants (crossing number, genus, writhe) for classification." "Studying the topology of knots that bound minimal-genus surfaces." "Verifying computational results from other knot invariant calculators." "Analyzing knot complexity: genus often correlates with other complexity measures.")
  :related ("topo/knot" "topo/crossing-number" "topo/writhe" "topo/unknot?" "topo/euler-char")
  :learn (:concept "Knot genus as a measure of spanning surface complexity, and its role in knot invariant hierarchies." :prerequisites ("topo/knot" "topo/crossing-number") :progression "Compute genus, compare with crossing number and writhe, and use together for robust knot classification."))

(verb
  :name "topo/f-vector"
  :library "topo"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(topo/f-vector complex) -> list"
  :summary "Returns the face-count vector (f₀, f₁, …) enumerating vertices, edges, facets, etc. of a simplicial complex."
  :explanation "The f-vector is a foundational invariant in combinatorial topology. For a simplicial complex, f_k counts the number of k-dimensional faces (0-faces are vertices, 1-faces are edges, etc.). This vector encodes the shape's combinatorial structure and feeds directly into homology calculations and the Euler characteristic. Understanding f-vectors is essential for visualizing what a complex actually contains."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(let ((tri (topo/complex (list (list 0 1) (list 1 2) (list 2 0) (list 0 1 2)))))\n  (topo/f-vector tri))" :note "A triangle complex: f-vector is (3 3 1) meaning 3 vertices, 3 edges, 1 face.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(let* ((g (topo/graph 4 (list (list 0 1) (list 1 2) (list 2 3))))\n       (c (topo/close g))\n       (fv (topo/f-vector c)))\n  (list 'f-vector fv 'euler (topo/euler-char c)))" :note "Builds a path graph, closes it to include all faces, computes f-vector and verifies Euler χ.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(let* ((points (list (list 0 0) (list 1 0) (list 0 1) (list 1 1)))\n       (ms (topo/metric-space points (lambda (p q) (apply + (map (lambda (a b) (abs (- a b))) p q)))))\n       (vrips (topo/vietoris-rips ms 1.5))\n       (fv (topo/f-vector vrips))\n       (betti (topo/betti vrips)))\n  (list 'f-vector fv 'betti betti 'match (equal? (topo/euler-char vrips) (fold-left + 0 (map (lambda (i fi) (* (if (even? i) 1 -1) fi)) (list-range (length fv)) fv)))))" :note "Builds a Vietoris–Rips complex from a metric space, checks f-vector against Betti numbers via Euler–Poincaré formula.")
  )
  :caveats ("f-vector is indexed by dimension: (f₀ f₁ f₂ …); don't confuse position with dimension." "Requires a closed simplicial complex; use topo/close to ensure all faces are included." "Empty complex yields the empty list.")
  :drawbacks ("Alone, f-vector does not distinguish topologically different spaces (e.g., a sphere and a torus can share f-vectors for certain subdivisions)." "For very large complexes, storing and computing the full vector can be expensive; use topo/betti or topo/euler-char if only a summary is needed.")
  :usecases ("Validating the structure of a simplicial complex before homology computation." "Debugging face counts in Vietoris–Rips or other automatic complex builders." "Teaching or visualization: f-vector is an intuitive first look at combinatorial shape.")
  :related ("topo/euler-char" "topo/betti" "topo/complex" "topo/close" "topo/boundary-matrix")
  :learn (:concept "The f-vector encodes the raw count of faces at each dimension; it is the input to homology." :prerequisites ("topo/complex" "topo/close") :progression "After f-vector, learn topo/euler-char (a linear invariant) and topo/betti (homological content)."))

(verb
  :name "topo/graph"
  :library "topo"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(topo/graph num-vertices edge-list) -> graph"
  :summary "Builds a simple graph on vertices {0, 1, …, n-1} from an edge list; rejects self-loops and duplicate edges."
  :explanation "A graph is the foundation of discrete topology. This verb constructs one from a vertex count and an explicit list of edges (each edge a 2-element list). It validates that the graph is simple: no vertex connects to itself, and no edge appears twice (in either direction). A validated graph is a clean object for connectivity analysis, component detection, and Vietoris–Rips complex construction. Use this when you need a rigorous starting point."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(topo/graph 4 (list (list 0 1) (list 1 2) (list 2 3)))" :note "A path graph with 4 vertices and 3 edges: 0–1–2–3.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(let* ((g (topo/graph 5 (list (list 0 1) (list 1 2) (list 2 3) (list 3 4) (list 4 0))))\n       (c (topo/connected? g)))\n  (list 'graph g 'connected c))" :note "A 5-cycle: all vertices in one connected component.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(let* ((g (topo/graph 6 (list (list 0 1) (list 1 2) (list 3 4) (list 4 5))))\n       (comps (topo/components g)))\n  (map (lambda (comp) (length comp)) comps))" :note "A disconnected graph with two components; topo/components lists vertex sets in each.")
  )
  :caveats ("Edges are undirected: (list 0 1) and (list 1 0) are the same edge; duplicates are rejected." "Vertices must be integers in [0, num-vertices); out-of-range edges cause validation error." "Self-loops (e.g., (list 0 0)) are explicitly forbidden.")
  :drawbacks ("topo/graph constructs only the 1-skeleton; to build a full simplicial complex with higher-dimensional faces, use topo/complex or topo/close." "No weighted edges; for metric distances, use topo/metric-space instead." "Large graphs (>10000 vertices) may be slow to validate; consider using a backend for industrial problems.")
  :usecases ("Building a connectivity skeleton before computing homology." "Checking planarity with topo/planar?." "Feeding into topo/vietoris-rips to build a full simplicial complex from points." "Analyzing network topology: connected components, planarity, Euler characteristic.")
  :related ("topo/complex" "topo/metric-space" "topo/connected?" "topo/components" "topo/vietoris-rips" "topo/f-vector" "topo/euler-char")
  :learn (:concept "A graph is a set of vertices and edges; topo/graph validates and stores it for downstream topology." :prerequisites ("(core)") :progression "After topo/graph, learn topo/components and topo/connected? (reachability), then topo/complex and topo/close (higher-dimensional topology)."))

(verb
  :name "topo/homology-gf2"
  :library "topo"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(topo/homology-gf2 complex) -> dict"
  :summary "Computes homology groups over GF(2) (the field with two elements) and returns a summary including Betti numbers and verification of the Euler–Poincaré formula χ = Σ(−1)ᵏβₖ."
  :explanation "Homology is a deep invariant that counts topological \"holes\" at each dimension: β₀ is the number of connected components, β₁ counts tunnels, β₂ counts voids, etc. This verb computes homology over GF(2) (coefficients 0 and 1), which is simpler and sufficient for many applications. It returns a dictionary with Betti numbers and automatically verifies that the Euler–Poincaré formula holds—a self-consistency check. If the computation is correct, χ should equal the alternating sum of Betti numbers."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(let ((tri (topo/complex (list (list 0 1) (list 1 2) (list 2 0) (list 0 1 2)))))\n  (topo/homology-gf2 tri))" :note "A filled triangle: β₀=1 (one component), β₁=0 (no tunnels), β₂=1 (one filled region).")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(let* ((c (topo/close (topo/graph 4 (list (list 0 1) (list 1 2) (list 2 3) (list 3 0)))))\n       (h (topo/homology-gf2 c))\n       (chi (topo/euler-char c)))\n  (list 'homology h 'euler chi 'consistent (equal? chi (list-ref h 'euler-poincare))))" :note "A 4-cycle closed: Euler formula should match.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(let* ((pts (list (list 0 0) (list 1 0) (list 0.5 0.866)))\n       (ms (topo/metric-space pts (lambda (p q) (apply + (map (lambda (a b) (abs (- a b))) p q)))))\n       (vr (topo/vietoris-rips ms 1.5))\n       (h (topo/homology-gf2 vr))\n       (betti (list-ref h 'betti)))\n  (let ((b0 (list-ref betti 0)) (b1 (list-ref betti 1)))\n    (list 'components b0 'tunnels b1 'genus (/ (- 2 (topo/euler-char vr)) 2))))" :note "Vietoris–Rips complex from metric points; homology reveals topology, genus derived from Euler.")
  )
  :caveats ("Works over GF(2); for integer or rational coefficients, different torsion may appear (not detected here)." "Dimension cap at k > 8; higher Betti numbers return '*[verify]*' if the source does not handle them." "The Euler–Poincaré verification is an internal consistency check; a mismatch signals a bug in the complex or boundary matrix.")
  :drawbacks ("Over GF(2), 2-torsion (e.g., in real projective plane) is invisible; use a backend for integer coefficients." "Computation scales cubically with boundary matrix size; large complexes may be slow." "Does not return explicit cycle/boundary representatives, only their ranks and counts.")
  :usecases ("Validating a complex's topology before deeper analysis." "Teaching homology: Betti numbers are concrete and intuitive." "Checking planarity via Betti: a tree has β₁=0; a single cycle has β₁=1." "Detecting connected components: β₀ equals the number of components.")
  :related ("topo/betti" "topo/betti-k" "topo/f-vector" "topo/euler-char" "topo/boundary-matrix" "topo/persistence" "topo/complex" "topo/close")
  :learn (:concept "Homology measures topological holes; Betti numbers are the ranks of these hole spaces. The Euler–Poincaré formula ties them together." :prerequisites ("topo/f-vector" "topo/euler-char" "topo/boundary-matrix") :progression "After topo/homology-gf2, explore topo/persistence for how Betti numbers change across a filtration."))

(verb
  :name "topo/knot"
  :library "topo"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(topo/knot pd-code) -> knot"
  :summary "Parses and validates a knot from a planar diagram (PD) code; rejects malformed input."
  :explanation "A PD code is a compact way to specify a knot diagram: a list of crossing records, each specifying how four strands meet. This verb reads a PD code, validates that it forms a closed knot (strands connect consistently, no dangling ends), and returns a knot object. A valid knot can then be analyzed for crossing number, writhe, and unknottedness. Use this when your knot arrives as diagram data and you need to ensure it is well-formed before topology computation."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(topo/knot (list))" :note "The empty (0-crossing) unknot: a trivial knot, always valid.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(let ((unknot (topo/knot (list))))\n  (list 'knot unknot 'is-unknot (topo/unknot? unknot)))" :note "Validate and test the unknot.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(let* ((k (topo/knot (list (list 1 2 3 4) (list 3 4 1 2))))\n       (cn (topo/crossing-number k))\n       (w (topo/writhe k)))\n  (list 'knot k 'crossings cn 'writhe w))" :note "A minimal knot with crossing record; compute writhe and crossing number.")
  )
  :caveats ("PD codes must be well-formed: each crossing references four strands, and strands must close into a loop." "The knot must be connected; disconnected diagrams (links) are rejected by topo/knot." "Reidemeister equivalence is NOT checked; two different PD codes may represent the same knot.")
  :drawbacks ("PD code format is technical; beginners should use documented examples or interactive tools to generate valid codes." "topo/knot alone does not determine knot type (e.g., trefoil vs. figure-eight); use other invariants." "Large PD codes (many crossings) may be slow; the unknot problem is NP-hard in general.")
  :usecases ("Parsing knot diagrams from external sources (SnapPy, KnotInfo, etc.)." "Validating hand-drawn or manually specified knot data." "Computing invariants (crossing number, writhe, unknottedness) for knot classification." "Knot theory visualization and education.")
  :related ("topo/crossing-number" "topo/unknot?" "topo/writhe")
  :learn (:concept "A knot is a closed loop in 3D space, encoded as a planar diagram (PD code). Validation ensures consistency before analysis." :prerequisites ("(core)") :progression "After topo/knot, compute invariants with topo/crossing-number, topo/writhe, and topo/unknot?."))

(verb
  :name "topo/metric-space"
  :library "topo"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(topo/metric-space points distance-fn) -> metric-space"
  :summary "Builds a finite metric space from a list of points and a distance function; validates that the distance function satisfies the metric axioms (non-negativity, symmetry, triangle inequality)."
  :explanation "A metric space is a set of points with a well-defined distance satisfying four axioms: d(x,x)=0, d(x,y)≥0, d(x,y)=d(y,x), and d(x,z)≤d(x,y)+d(y,z). This verb takes points (e.g., coordinates or arbitrary objects) and a distance function (a binary operator), validates all pairs, and returns a metric-space object. Once validated, the metric space feeds into complex builders like topo/vietoris-rips. Validation is essential to prevent silent nonsense downstream."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(topo/metric-space (list (list 0 0) (list 1 0) (list 0 1))\n  (lambda (p q) (apply + (map (lambda (a b) (abs (- a b))) p q))))" :note "Three points in Manhattan distance; validation passes.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(let* ((pts (list (list 0 0) (list 1 0) (list 1 1) (list 0 1)))\n       (ms (topo/metric-space pts\n             (lambda (p q) (sqrt (apply + (map (lambda (a b) (expt (- a b) 2)) p q)))))))\n  (list 'points (length pts) 'metric-space ms))" :note "Four corners of a unit square; Euclidean distance.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(let* ((pts (list 'a 'b 'c 'd))\n       (dist (lambda (x y)\n               (let ((p (list x y)))\n                 (cond ((equal? p (list 'a 'b)) 1.0)\n                       ((equal? p (list 'b 'a)) 1.0)\n                       ((equal? p (list 'b 'c)) 2.0)\n                       ((equal? p (list 'c 'b)) 2.0)\n                       ((equal? p (list 'a 'c)) 3.0)\n                       ((equal? p (list 'c 'a)) 3.0)\n                       ((equal? p (list 'c 'd)) 1.5)\n                       ((equal? p (list 'd 'c)) 1.5)\n                       ((equal? p (list 'a 'd)) (sqrt 13))\n                       ((equal? p (list 'd 'a)) (sqrt 13))\n                       ((equal? x y) 0.0)\n                       (else 999.0)))))\n       (ms (topo/metric-space pts dist)))\n  (list 'discrete-metric-space ms))" :note "A custom metric on symbolic points; all axioms must hold or validation fails.")
  )
  :caveats ("Distance function must be symmetric: d(x,y) = d(y,x); the validator checks this explicitly." "Triangle inequality d(x,z) ≤ d(x,y) + d(y,z) is validated for all triples; violations are caught." "Self-distance d(x,x) must equal 0 exactly; numerical errors can cause silent failures." "Large point sets (>1000 points) incur O(n²) validation cost.")
  :drawbacks ("Validation is strict; even small numerical errors (e.g., floating-point rounding) can fail the metric axioms." "Once built, the metric space is immutable; to change the distance, rebuild it." "For very large point sets, consider pre-validating a subset, then assuming the distance is metric.")
  :usecases ("Building Vietoris–Rips complexes: topo/vietoris-rips requires a validated metric space." "Defining neighborhoods and balls for point-set topology: topo/ball uses a metric." "Ensuring distance functions are truly metric before topology computation." "Comparing algorithms on well-defined metric spaces.")
  :related ("topo/vietoris-rips" "topo/ball" "topo/graph" "topo/complex" "topo/homology-gf2")
  :learn (:concept "A metric space pairs points with a distance that obeys four axioms; validation ensures consistency before topology." :prerequisites ("(core)") :progression "After topo/metric-space, build complexes with topo/vietoris-rips and analyze them with topo/homology-gf2."))

(verb
  :name "topo/orientable?"
  :library "topo"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(topo/orientable? moebius-flag) -> boolean"
  :summary "Returns #t if a surface is orientable, #f if it contains a Möbius band; the decision is based on the Möbius flag passed in."
  :explanation "A surface is orientable if you can consistently choose a normal direction at every point; if it contains a Möbius band (a non-orientable twist), then no such global choice exists. This verb takes a flag indicating Möbius character and returns whether the surface is orientable. This is a query on metadata rather than a computation; it clarifies the global structure of a surface. Use this when you need to decide whether a surface is one-sided or two-sided."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(topo/orientable? #f)" :note "A surface with no Möbius band is orientable; returns #t.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(let ((orientable (topo/orientable? #f))\n      (nonorientable (topo/orientable? #t)))\n  (list 'sphere-like orientable 'projective-plane-like nonorientable))" :note "Compare orientable and non-orientable surfaces.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(let* ((genus 2)\n       (moebius-count 0)\n       (is-orientable (topo/orientable? (= moebius-count 0))))\n  (if is-orientable\n    (list 'surface 'orientable-genus genus)\n    (list 'surface 'non-orientable-genus moebius-count)))" :note "Classify a surface by orientability and genus.")
  )
  :caveats ("This verb is a property query, not a computation; it assumes the Möbius flag is already known (e.g., from Euler genus or manual specification)." "If the Möbius flag is incorrect, the answer is meaningless; validate the input independently." "Returns a boolean; does not distinguish between different non-orientable surfaces (e.g., projective plane vs. Klein bottle).")
  :drawbacks ("Provides only a yes/no answer; does not compute genus or other fine details." "Requires the Möbius flag as input; if you do not have it, compute it separately (e.g., from topo/euler-genus)." "Does not work on arbitrary complexes without explicit Möbius metadata.")
  :usecases ("Quickly checking whether a surface is one-sided or two-sided." "Conditional logic in geometry code: different algorithms for orientable vs. non-orientable surfaces." "Classification of compact surfaces: combining orientability and genus gives a complete topological type." "Teaching surface topology: orientability is a key concept.")
  :related ("topo/euler-genus" "topo/planar?" "topo/f-vector" "topo/euler-char")
  :learn (:concept "Orientability is a global property: a surface is one-sided (non-orientable, contains Möbius) or two-sided (orientable). The flag encodes this." :prerequisites ("topo/euler-char" "topo/euler-genus") :progression "Combine topo/orientable? with genus to fully classify compact surfaces."))

(verb
  :name "topo/persistence"
  :library "topo"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(topo/persistence filtration dimension) -> barcode"
  :summary "Computes the persistent β_dimension homology barcode over a filtration (a sequence of complexes at increasing scales), showing when each homological feature is born and dies."
  :explanation "Persistent homology tracks how topology evolves as you build a complex scale by scale. A filtration is a sequence of complexes C₀ ⊆ C₁ ⊆ … ⊆ Cₙ; each feature (connected component, tunnel, void) appears (is born) at some scale and vanishes (dies) at a later scale. The barcode is a list of intervals [birth, death], with infinite bars for features that never die. This verb is central to topological data analysis: it reveals the structure of data at all scales. Use it when you want to understand which features are real (persistent) vs. noise (short-lived)."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(let ((filt (topo/rips-filtration (topo/metric-space (list (list 0 0) (list 1 0) (list 0 1)) (lambda (p q) (apply + (map (lambda (a b) (abs (- a b))) p q)))) 0 2.0 0.5)))\n  (topo/persistence filt 0))" :note "Persistence barcode in dimension 0 (connected components) for a Rips filtration.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(let* ((pts (list (list 0 0) (list 1 0) (list 1 1) (list 0 1)))\n       (ms (topo/metric-space pts (lambda (p q) (sqrt (apply + (map (lambda (a b) (expt (- a b) 2)) p q))))))\n       (filt (topo/rips-filtration ms 0 2.5 0.25))\n       (b0 (topo/persistence filt 0))\n       (b1 (topo/persistence filt 1)))\n  (list 'h0 b0 'h1 b1))" :note "Compare persistence in dimensions 0 and 1 for a square point cloud.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(let* ((pts (list (list 0 0) (list 1 0) (list 0.5 0.866) (list 0.5 0.3)))\n       (ms (topo/metric-space pts (lambda (p q) (sqrt (apply + (map (lambda (a b) (expt (- a b) 2)) p q))))))\n       (filt (topo/rips-filtration ms 0 3.0 0.1))\n       (b1 (topo/persistence filt 1))\n       (total-pers (topo/total-persistence b1))\n       (entropy (topo/persistence-entropy b1)))\n  (list 'dimension 1 'barcode b1 'total-persistence total-pers 'entropy entropy))" :note "Full persistent homology analysis: barcode, total persistence, and entropy.")
  )
  :caveats ("The dimension parameter selects which homology to track; dimension > ambient will likely yield empty barcodes." "Requires a pre-built filtration (typically from topo/rips-filtration); generating one is expensive for large point clouds." "Infinite bars (features never killed) are real; but distinguish them from numerical artifacts." "Scale (ε) in the filtration must be chosen carefully; too small → noise, too large → oversimplification.")
  :drawbacks ("Computing persistent homology scales as O(n³) for n points (worst case); use a backend for >5000 points." "Interpreting barcodes requires domain knowledge; visual inspection is key." "Two data sets with similar barcodes are topologically similar, but not necessarily equivalent." "Persistent homology erases some information (e.g., actual coordinates); it is a projection onto a 1D timeline.")
  :usecases ("Topological data analysis: detect clusters and holes in point clouds." "Denoising: short-lived features are noise; persistent features are real." "Clustering: high persistence in H₀ indicates strong cluster structure." "Feature detection: loops and voids revealed by H₁, H₂ persistence." "Comparing datasets: use topo/bottleneck to measure barcode distance.")
  :related ("topo/rips-filtration" "topo/betti-curve" "topo/total-persistence" "topo/persistence-entropy" "topo/bottleneck" "topo/homology-gf2" "topo/metric-space")
  :learn (:concept "Persistent homology tracks when topological features appear and disappear across a filtration; the barcode is a 1D summary of the lifetime of each feature." :prerequisites ("topo/homology-gf2" "topo/metric-space" "topo/vietoris-rips") :progression "After topo/persistence, analyze the barcode with topo/total-persistence, topo/persistence-entropy, and topo/bottleneck for distance."))

(verb
  :name "topo/persistence-entropy"
  :library "topo"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(topo/persistence-entropy barcode) -> number"
  :summary "Computes the Shannon entropy of the finite persistence bar lengths in a barcode, measuring the disorder or spread of feature lifetimes."
  :explanation "In a persistent homology barcode, each bar has a length (death − birth); entropy quantifies how spread out these lengths are. High entropy means bar lengths vary widely (diverse features); low entropy means most bars have similar lengths (homogeneous structure). Entropy is a single-number summary useful for comparing datasets. A barcode with one very long bar and many short ones has low entropy; a barcode with evenly distributed bar lengths has high entropy. Use this when you want a scalar measure of topological diversity."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(let ((barcode (list (list 0 1.0) (list 0 1.0) (list 0 1.0))))\n  (topo/persistence-entropy barcode))" :note "Three bars of equal length (1.0): entropy is maximal (≈1.58 for 3 equal bars in bits).")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(let ((barcode1 (list (list 0 1.0) (list 0 0.1) (list 0 0.05)))\n      (barcode2 (list (list 0 0.5) (list 0 0.5))))\n  (list 'barcode1-entropy (topo/persistence-entropy barcode1)\n        'barcode2-entropy (topo/persistence-entropy barcode2)))" :note "Compare entropy of a heterogeneous barcode vs. a homogeneous one.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(let* ((pts (list (list 0 0) (list 1 0) (list 1 1) (list 0 1) (list 0.5 0.5)))\n       (ms (topo/metric-space pts (lambda (p q) (sqrt (apply + (map (lambda (a b) (expt (- a b) 2)) p q))))))\n       (filt (topo/rips-filtration ms 0 2.5 0.1))\n       (b1 (topo/persistence filt 1))\n       (ent (topo/persistence-entropy b1))\n       (total (topo/total-persistence b1)))\n  (list 'topology 'barcode b1 'total-persistence total 'entropy ent 'ratio (/ total (+ 0.001 (log ent)))))" :note "Full analysis: barcode, total persistence, and entropy; ratio indicates structure diversity.")
  )
  :caveats ("Entropy is defined only for non-empty barcodes with at least one finite bar; empty or all-infinite barcodes return 0 or undefined." "The logarithm base matters: using log₂ (bits) vs. natural log (nats) changes the scale; both are valid." "Bars of length 0 (birth = death, birth point) are degenerate; filter them out before computing entropy." "Small numerical errors in bar lengths can distort entropy; use rounded or binned lengths if needed.")
  :drawbacks ("Entropy alone does not characterize a barcode: two different barcodes can have the same entropy." "Cannot distinguish between noise and signal; low entropy may indicate either homogeneous structure or data collapse." "Requires a complete barcode; missing or truncated data will skew the result." "Not a universal distance metric; use topo/bottleneck for principled barcode comparison.")
  :usecases ("Summarizing barcode complexity in a single scalar for ranking or filtering datasets." "Distinguishing organized structures (low entropy) from chaotic point clouds (high entropy)." "Quality control: comparing experiment-to-experiment or algorithm-to-algorithm entropy for consistency." "Teaching persistent homology: entropy is an intuitive measure of topological diversity.")
  :related ("topo/persistence" "topo/total-persistence" "topo/bottleneck" "topo/betti-curve" "topo/homology-gf2")
  :learn (:concept "Persistence entropy is a single-number summary of how spread out the lifetimes of topological features are; it captures topological diversity." :prerequisites ("topo/persistence" "topo/total-persistence") :progression "After topo/persistence-entropy, use topo/bottleneck to compare barcodes from different datasets."))

(verb
  :name "topo/planar?"
  :library "topo"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(topo/planar? graph) -> boolean"
  :summary "Tests whether a graph is planar using Euler's bound and K₅ detection."
  :explanation "A planar graph can be drawn on a surface without edge crossings. This verb uses two fast filters: first checking Euler's bound (e ≤ 3v − 6 for simple graphs), then screening for a K₅ (complete 5-vertex) subgraph. For very dense graphs, returns the symbol 'use-backend to signal that a heavier algorithm would be needed. Useful in topology and circuit-board routing."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(let ((g (topo/graph '((a b) (b c) (c a)))))\n  (topo/planar? g))" :note "A simple triangle is planar; returns #t.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(let ((k5 (topo/graph '((a b) (a c) (a d) (a e)\n                         (b c) (b d) (b e)\n                         (c d) (c e)\n                         (d e)))))\n  (topo/planar? k5))" :note "K₅ (complete 5-vertex) is not planar; returns #f.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(let ((g (topo/graph (map (lambda (i)\n                         (list i (modulo (+ i 1) 20)))\n                       (range 0 20)))))\n  (if (eq? (topo/planar? g) 'use-backend)\n      (display \"Graph too large; use external backend\")\n      (display (if (topo/planar? g) \"Planar\" \"Non-planar\"))))" :note "Large graphs may return 'use-backend; check for it before assuming boolean result.")
  )
  :caveats ("Euler's bound is necessary but not sufficient; passing it does not guarantee planarity." "For graphs with > ~100 edges, may return 'use-backend instead of a boolean." "Self-loops and multi-edges are not handled; assume simple graphs." "'use-backend is a third-case value; always check for it with eq? rather than assuming #t/#f.")
  :drawbacks ("Fast heuristics are not complete; false negatives are possible for some non-planar graphs." "If you need certainty, integrate a full planarity algorithm (Hopcroft–Tarjan) via the backend." "Does not return a planar embedding; only answers yes/no.")
  :usecases ("Checking circuit-board layouts (PCB routing constraints)." "Graph visualization: deciding whether to use a planar layout." "Topology puzzles and graph-theory education." "Quick filtering before expensive layout or rendering.")
  :related ("topo/euler-genus" "topo/graph" "topo/components")
  :learn (:concept "Euler's formula and forbidden minors as planarity witnesses" :prerequisites ("topo/graph") :progression "After understanding planar?, study topo/euler-genus to compute genus (0 for planar), then topo/orientable? for surface topology."))

(verb
  :name "topo/rips-filtration"
  :library "topo"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(topo/rips-filtration point-set epsilon-max [step-count]) -> filtration"
  :summary "Builds a Vietoris–Rips filtration: a nested sequence of simplicial complexes at increasing scales."
  :explanation "A filtration is a family of complexes C(ε₀) ⊆ C(ε₁) ⊆ C(ε₂) … indexed by scale (radius). The Rips complex at scale ε includes all vertices and edges connecting points within distance ε, plus all higher-dimensional faces implied by edge inclusion. This is the input to persistent homology: by tracking when features (connected components, holes, voids) appear and disappear across scales, you extract topological structure without committing to a single scale. Central to topological data analysis (TDA)."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(let ((pts '((0 0) (1 0) (0.5 0.866))))\n  (topo/rips-filtration pts 2.0))" :note "Three points forming a triangle; produces a filtration with scales from ε=0 up to 2.0.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(let* ((pts (map (lambda (t) (list (cos (* 2 3.14159 t)) (sin (* 2 3.14159 t))))\n                    (map (lambda (i) (/ i 10.0)) (range 0 10))))\n        (filt (topo/rips-filtration pts 1.5 20)))\n  (topo/persistence filt 1))" :note "10 points on a circle; the filtration captures the emergence and persistence of the 1-hole.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(let* ((pts '((0 0) (2 0) (1 1.732) (1 0.577)))\n        (filt (topo/rips-filtration pts 3.0 50))\n        (bars (topo/persistence filt 0))\n        (vitality (topo/total-persistence filt)))\n  (list 'persistence-bars bars\n        'total-vitality vitality))" :note "Compute both barcode and total persistence to measure topological feature strength.")
  )
  :caveats ("Step count (number of epsilon values sampled) controls resolution; too coarse may miss features." "Rips complexes grow exponentially with dimension; pre-check point count and epsilon range." "Points are assumed metric; use metric-space verbs if using non-Euclidean distances." "The filtration itself is an opaque object; extract persistence via topo/persistence.")
  :drawbacks ("Quadratic pairwise distance computation; slow for >1000 points without spatial indexing." "Higher dimensions grow in complexity; capped at dimension 8 for Betti computation." "Does not return individual complexes; must use topo/persistence to extract meaning.")
  :usecases ("Persistent homology: detecting clusters, loops, and voids across scales." "Point-cloud analysis: inferring hidden structure without choosing a single scale a priori." "Data-topology visualization: understanding high-dimensional manifolds." "Feature engineering: computing topological descriptors (persistence entropy, total persistence).")
  :related ("topo/persistence" "topo/vietoris-rips" "topo/total-persistence" "topo/persistence-entropy" "topo/betti-curve")
  :learn (:concept "Filtration as a path through scale space; persistent homology tracking births and deaths" :prerequisites ("topo/vietoris-rips" "topo/metric-space") :progression "Use topo/rips-filtration to create the filtration, then topo/persistence to read off barcodes, then topo/total-persistence to summarize."))

(verb
  :name "topo/total-persistence"
  :library "topo"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(topo/total-persistence filtration [dim]) -> number"
  :summary "Sums the lifetimes of all finite bars in a persistent homology barcode: Σ(death − birth)."
  :explanation "In a persistence barcode, each topological feature (connected component, hole, void) appears at one scale (birth) and disappears at another (death). The lifetime is death − birth. Total persistence is the sum of all finite lifetimes—a single number measuring how much topological structure is present and robust across scales. High total persistence indicates strong, long-lived features; low values suggest noise. It is a key TDA statistic for comparing filtrations."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(let ((filt (topo/rips-filtration '((0 0) (1 0) (0 1)) 2.0)))\n  (topo/total-persistence filt 0))" :note "Total persistence of connected components (dim 0) for three points; indicates how fragmented the union of balls is.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(let* ((circle-pts (map (lambda (t) (list (cos (* 2 3.14159 t)) (sin (* 2 3.14159 t))))\n                         (map (lambda (i) (/ i 20.0)) (range 0 20))))\n       (filt (topo/rips-filtration circle-pts 2.5 40))\n       (p0 (topo/total-persistence filt 0))\n       (p1 (topo/total-persistence filt 1)))\n  (list 'components p0 'holes p1))" :note "Compare persistence across dimensions; p1 (holes) should dominate for a circle.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(let* ((cloud (map (lambda (i)\n                    (list (random-range -2 2) (random-range -2 2) (random-range -2 2)))\n                  (range 0 50)))\n       (filt (topo/rips-filtration cloud 3.0 60))\n       (vitality (map (lambda (dim) (topo/total-persistence filt dim)) (range 0 3)))\n       (entropy (topo/persistence-entropy filt)))\n  (list 'vitality-by-dim vitality 'entropy entropy))" :note "Combine total-persistence across all dimensions to build a topological fingerprint of point-cloud structure.")
  )
  :caveats ("Infinite bars (e.g. the 0-dimensional component that never dies) are excluded; they represent the final connected structure, not transient noise." "The dimension must be specified; default may be 0 (components)." "Result is sensitive to scale range and step count of the filtration." "Requires a valid barcode; malformed input yields no error, but a nonsense sum.")
  :drawbacks ("Does not distinguish which features are persistent; only sums their lifetimes." "Sensitive to outliers if they create long-lived edges or holes." "Single number loses information about the distribution of lifetimes; use topo/persistence-entropy for dispersion.")
  :usecases ("Comparing two point clouds or datasets: the one with higher persistence has more robust structure." "Quality assurance in TDA: checking whether feature detection produced meaningful results." "Machine learning: using total persistence as a feature vector component." "Noise vs. signal discrimination: large persistence indicates real structure, small suggests noise.")
  :related ("topo/persistence" "topo/rips-filtration" "topo/persistence-entropy" "topo/betti-curve")
  :learn (:concept "Lifetime as a measure of topological robustness; summing to extract a single robust statistic" :prerequisites ("topo/persistence" "topo/rips-filtration") :progression "Compute total-persistence to get a 1D summary, then use topo/persistence-entropy to measure spread, then topo/bottleneck to compare two filtrations."))

(verb
  :name "topo/unknot?"
  :library "topo"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(topo/unknot? knot-diagram) -> boolean"
  :summary "Tests whether a knot diagram represents the unknot (the trivial knot with 0 crossings)."
  :explanation "A knot diagram is a projection of a knot onto a plane with over/under crossing information. The unknot is the simplest knot—topologically equivalent to a circle with no knots. This verb checks whether the diagram can be simplified to the unknot, typically using the crossing number: if the diagram has 0 crossings, it is the unknot. Diagrams with nonzero crossings may or may not unknot. The verb returns true only for the zero-crossing (trivial) case."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(let ((circle (topo/knot '())))\n  (topo/unknot? circle))" :note "An empty crossing list is the unknot; returns #t.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(let ((trefoil (topo/knot '((1 2 3 4 2 1 4 3)))))\n  (list (topo/unknot? trefoil)\n        (topo/crossing-number trefoil)))" :note "The trefoil knot has 3 crossings and is not the unknot; returns (#f 3).")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(let ((diagrams (list (topo/knot '())\n                       (topo/knot '((1 2 3 4 2 1 4 3)))\n                       (topo/knot '((1 2 3 4 5 6 2 3 1 4 5 6))))))\n  (map (lambda (d) (list (topo/unknot? d) (topo/crossing-number d)))\n       diagrams))" :note "Batch-check diagrams; only the first (empty) is the unknot.")
  )
  :caveats ("This is the simple zero-crossing test; diagrams with 1+ crossings always return #f, even if they unknot via Reidemeister moves." "A full unknot-decision algorithm is NP-hard; this verb does not perform sequence reduction." "Malformed knot diagrams may cause an error tagged 'diagram-invalid; use topo/knot to validate first.")
  :drawbacks ("Low expressive power: only identifies the trivial knot, not broader knot families." "Does not perform Reidemeister move reduction; cannot prove unknottedness of most diagrams." "For research-grade knot analysis, use external tools (SnapPea, KnotTheory) via the backend.")
  :usecases ("Quick sanity check: verifying that a computed diagram is trivial." "Filtering: eliminating the unknot from a list of knots to focus on nontrivial ones." "Education: teaching knot invariants in a pedagogical context.")
  :related ("topo/knot" "topo/crossing-number" "topo/writhe")
  :learn (:concept "The unknot as the trivial knot; the simple zero-crossing test as a first filter" :prerequisites ("topo/knot" "topo/crossing-number") :progression "Use topo/unknot? for quick checks, then study topo/crossing-number and topo/writhe for invariants, then move to external tools for full knot classification."))

(verb
  :name "topo/vietoris-rips"
  :library "topo"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(topo/vietoris-rips point-set epsilon [fuel]) -> complex"
  :summary "Constructs the Vietoris–Rips complex at scale ε: a simplicial complex with all cliques of points within pairwise distance ε."
  :explanation "The Vietoris–Rips complex is a fundamental construction in topological data analysis. At scale ε, include a vertex for each point, an edge between any two points within distance ε, and a k-simplex (face) for any (k+1)-clique of edges. Unlike the Čech complex, it does not require circumradius checks—only pairwise distances. This makes it fast and widely used. The result is a simplicial complex suitable for computing homology and Betti numbers. Fuel (computation budget) prevents runaway on dense point clouds."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(let ((pts '((0 0) (1 0) (0.5 0.866))))\n  (topo/vietoris-rips pts 1.5))" :note "Three points of a triangle; at ε=1.5, all edges form and the 2-simplex (triangle face) is included.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(let ((pts '((0 0) (1 0) (2 0) (1 1))))\n  (let ((cpx (topo/vietoris-rips pts 1.1)))\n    (list (topo/betti cpx)\n          (topo/euler-char cpx))))" :note "Four points in a rough square; compute Betti numbers and Euler characteristic of the resulting complex.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(let ((circle-pts (map (lambda (t) (list (cos (* 6.28 t)) (sin (* 6.28 t))))\n                        (map (lambda (i) (/ i 16.0)) (range 0 16)))))\n  (let ((cpx (topo/vietoris-rips circle-pts 0.8 10000)))\n    (cond ((eq? cpx 'too-many-simplices)\n           (display \"Fuel exceeded; reduce epsilon or point count\"))\n          (else\n           (list 'betti (topo/betti cpx)\n                 'homology (topo/homology-gf2 cpx))))))" :note "16 points on a circle; construct complex and check for robust 1-hole (β₁=1).")
  )
  :caveats ("Fuel (default or explicit cap) prevents infinite loops; exceeding it returns 'too-many-simplices, not a partial complex." "Simplices grow combinatorially; even moderate epsilon and point count can explode in high dimensions." "Pairwise distance computation is O(n²); use spatial indexing for >1000 points (not built in)." "For non-Euclidean metrics, use topo/metric-space to define distance; vietoris-rips assumes the metric is available.")
  :drawbacks ("Clique enumeration is NP-hard; computation time grows rapidly with epsilon and point density." "Unlike Čech, Rips over-approximates (includes simplices not in Čech); good for speed, less accurate topologically." "Betti computation is capped at dimension 8; higher-dimensional homology is not supported.")
  :usecases ("Building simplicial complexes for persistent homology (input to topo/rips-filtration)." "Computing Betti numbers and Euler characteristic of point clouds." "Testing topological hypotheses (e.g., does this cloud contain a loop?)." "Comparing complexes at different scales to track feature persistence.")
  :related ("topo/rips-filtration" "topo/betti" "topo/homology-gf2" "topo/boundary-matrix" "topo/metric-space")
  :learn (:concept "Simplicial complex from distance data; the Rips variant as a balance between speed and topological fidelity" :prerequisites ("topo/complex" "topo/metric-space") :progression "Construct a single complex with topo/vietoris-rips, compute its Betti numbers with topo/betti, then build a filtration with topo/rips-filtration to extract persistence."))

(verb
  :name "topo/writhe"
  :library "topo"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(topo/writhe knot-diagram) -> number"
  :summary "Computes the writhe: the algebraic sum of crossing signs in a knot diagram."
  :explanation "In a knot diagram, each crossing is labeled with a sign: +1 for a right-handed crossing (the over-strand goes right relative to the under-strand) and −1 for left-handed. The writhe is the sum of all crossing signs. It is an invariant under the first Reidemeister move (which changes writhe) and the second and third moves (which preserve it). Writhe is useful for knot analysis, classification, and as input to other invariants. Unlike the crossing number, writhe is signed and can be 0 even for knotted diagrams."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(let ((unknot (topo/knot '())))\n  (topo/writhe unknot))" :note "The unknot has no crossings; writhe is 0.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(let ((right-trefoil (topo/knot '((1 2 3 4 2 1 4 3))))\n      (left-trefoil (topo/knot '((1 4 3 2 4 1 2 3)))))\n  (list (topo/writhe right-trefoil)\n        (topo/writhe left-trefoil)))" :note "Right and left trefoils have opposite writhe (±3), reflecting chirality.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(let ((diagrams (map topo/knot\n                   '(() ((1 2 3 4 2 1 4 3)) ((1 2 3 4 5 6 2 3 1 4 5 6))))))\n  (map (lambda (d) (list (topo/writhe d)\n                        (topo/crossing-number d)))\n       diagrams))" :note "Compare writhe and crossing number; writhe is signed, crossing number is absolute.")
  )
  :caveats ("Writhe depends on the diagram orientation; reversing the knot's direction flips the sign of all crossings." "Writhe is not a complete knot invariant; two different knots can have the same writhe." "Changing a crossing via a Reidemeister I move changes writhe by ±2; moves II and III preserve it." "Malformed diagrams may cause 'diagram-invalid error; validate with topo/knot first.")
  :drawbacks ("Does not uniquely identify knots; useful in combination with other invariants (e.g., crossing number, Jones polynomial)." "Sensitive to diagram choice; different projections of the same knot can have different writhe." "For full knot classification, writhe alone is insufficient; use external tools (SnapPea, KnotTheory).")
  :usecases ("Detecting chirality: knots with opposite writhe are mirror images." "Analyzing Reidemeister moves: tracking writhe change under diagram manipulation." "Comparing diagram families: understanding how writhe varies across the same knot type." "Education: teaching knot invariants and their geometric meaning.")
  :related ("topo/knot" "topo/crossing-number" "topo/unknot?")
  :learn (:concept "Writhe as a signed sum of crossing orientations; an invariant under certain diagram moves" :prerequisites ("topo/knot" "topo/crossing-number") :progression "Understand writhe as an algebraic invariant, then study how it relates to crossing number, then combine with other invariants for knot classification."))

; ─── library: transport (1 verbs) ───

(verb
  :name "transport/tempo"
  :library "transport"
  :kind "null"
  :signature "(transport/tempo bpm) -> token"
  :summary "Set the shared transport BPM (beats per minute) across all synchronized playback."
  :explanation "The transport tempo is a global clock that coordinates audio playback, animation timing, and beat-aligned state transitions across the running surface. When you call transport/tempo with a numeric BPM, you return a control descriptor (not an immediate side effect) that the runtime interprets to resynchronize all beat-dependent verbs (audio/play, synth/play, on-frame, across-beats, etc.) to the new tempo. Use this when you need to lock multiple subsystems to a single rhythmic pulse."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(transport/tempo 120)" :note "Set the shared clock to 120 BPM; all beat-synchronized verbs will retune to this pulse.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define (tempo-shift ctx)\n  (let ((new-bpm (+ (audio-bpm) 10)))\n    (act 'transport/tempo (list new-bpm) 'tempo-set)))" :note "Read the current BPM, increment it, and issue a tempo shift; the act descriptor queues the change.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (sync-to-track ctx)\n  (let* ((track-meta (ctx-result ctx))\n         (track-bpm (ctx-get 'bpm track-meta)))\n    (next 'playing (act 'transport/tempo (list track-bpm) 'tempo-locked))))" :note "Extract BPM from a fetched track metadata object and lock the global tempo to it before transitioning to playback state.")
  )
  :caveats ("Tempo changes take effect on the next frame boundary; rapid consecutive calls may coalesce." "Does not affect already-scheduled notes or audio samples mid-playback; only applies to newly initiated playback." "The BPM must be a positive number; zero or negative values are rejected silently.")
  :drawbacks ("Global tempo changes affect all synchronized subsystems simultaneously—use with care in multi-track or multi-agent scenarios." "No gradual tempo ramp; transitions are instantaneous at frame boundary.")
  :usecases ("Synchronizing a multi-track composition to a master metronome." "Matching playback tempo to detected audio onset or live tap input." "Coordinating dance choreography, animation loops, and beat-locked state transitions.")
  :related ("audio/tempo" "audio/bpm" "on-beat" "synth/play" "audio/play")
  :learn (:concept "Global tempo as a control descriptor; the separation between descriptor (what to do) and effect (when it happens)." :prerequisites ("audio/bpm" "act") :progression "After understanding transport/tempo, learn audio/tempo for per-channel tempo control, then explore across-beats and on-beat for beat-aligned choreography."))

; ─── library: vec (13 verbs) ───

(verb
  :name "vec/+"
  :library "vec"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(vec/+ v1 v2 ...) -> vector"
  :summary "Element-wise addition of vectors; all must have the same dimension."
  :impl-status "wired"
  :impl-file "src/wired-verbs.js"
  :impl-notes "Variadic component-wise sum over an arbitrary number of vectors. Missing components are treated as 0, so vectors of different length are padded rather than raised — a design choice that lets 2D vectors freely embed into 3D contexts. Empty arg list returns ()."
  :explanation "Vector addition is the fundamental linear algebra operation: add corresponding components. If v1 = [a, b, c] and v2 = [d, e, f], then v1 + v2 = [a+d, b+e, c+f]. This is exact arithmetic (no floating-point error beyond Scheme's native number operations). Variadic: vec/+ can add 2 or more vectors in sequence, walking through them position by position."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(vec/+ '(1 2 3) '(4 5 6))" :note "3-dimensional vector addition. Returns (5 7 9) — each position summed independently.")
    (:tier "apprentice" :code "(define player-pos '(100 200))\n(define delta '(3 -1))\n(vec/+ player-pos delta)" :note "The classic 'move by a delta' pattern. New position (103 199). Move north-east by (3, -1) — the -1 means down one because screen Y grows downward.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(let ((v1 '(1 0 -1))\n      (v2 '(2 3 4))\n      (v3 '(-3 2 0)))\n  (vec/+ v1 v2 v3))" :note "Variadic: add three vectors in one call. Returns (0 5 3).")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(let* ((forces (list '(10 0) '(0 15) '(-5 3)))\n       (net-force (fold-left vec/+ '(0 0) forces)))\n  net-force)" :note "Sum a list of force vectors via fold. Net force = (5 18). This is the standard physics pattern for accumulating impulses in a frame.")
    (:tier "master" :code "(define (path->positions origin steps)\n  ;; Given a starting position and a list of step vectors,\n  ;; return the visited positions including the origin.\n  (let loop ((cur origin) (rest steps) (acc (list origin)))\n    (if (null? rest)\n        (reverse acc)\n        (let ((next (vec/+ cur (car rest))))\n          (loop next (cdr rest) (cons next acc))))))\n(path->positions '(0 0) '((1 0) (0 1) (1 0) (0 -1)))" :note "Cumulative fold builds a path from step-deltas. Returns ((0 0) (1 0) (1 1) (2 1) (2 0)) — a square-like walk that ends one right of the start.")
  )
  :caveats ("Component-count mismatch does not raise; shorter vectors are zero-padded up to the longest. Callers who need strict equality should validate first." "Exact arithmetic is preserved; 1/2 + 1/3 yields 5/6, not a float approximation." "vec/+ is variadic; (vec/+ v1 v2 v3) adds all three in one call, not sequential nesting.")
  :drawbacks ("No in-place operation; creates a new vector (functional programming style)." "Variadic unpacking may be slower than binary + for very long chains." "Exact rationals in each component can grow in numerator/denominator size; simplification is not automatic.")
  :usecases ("Physics: summing forces, velocities, or displacements." "Computer graphics: adding translation or offset vectors." "Linear algebra: assembling linear combinations (paired with vec/scale)." "Data science: element-wise merging of numerical features.")
  :related ("vec/-" "vec/scale" "vec/dot" "vec/norm")
  :learn (:concept "Vector addition as component-wise operation preserving exact arithmetic" :prerequisites ("vec/make") :progression "Master vec/+, then combine with vec/scale to build linear combinations, then use vec/dot for projections, then study matrix operations.")
  :math (:algebra ("associative" "commutative" "identity: zero-vector") :total #t :domain "n vectors of equal dimension d" :codomain "vector of dimension d")
  :cs (:complexity "time O(k·d), space O(d) for k vectors of dimension d" :effects (none) :pure #t)
  :ai (:deterministic #t :cacheable #t :cardinality one :common-mistakes "Assuming vec/+ raises on dim mismatch; it zero-pads instead. If you need strict dim checking, use (vec/dim v) yourself first.")
  :hacker (:primitive #f :kin ("R7RS: no built-in; Clojure: (mapv + v1 v2); NumPy: v1 + v2") :history "Standard linear algebra since Grassmann (1844). Our impl is a straightforward variadic component-wise fold."))

(verb
  :name "vec/-"
  :library "vec"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(vec/- v1 [v2 ...]) -> vector"
  :summary "Element-wise subtraction of vectors; single-arg negates, N-ary subtracts left-to-right."
  :impl-status "wired"
  :impl-file "src/wired-verbs.js"
  :impl-notes "Variadic component-wise subtraction. One arg negates. Two args = v1-v2. N-ary = (((v1-v2)-v3)-v4). Missing components zero-pad rather than raise — see vec/+ for the matching design."
  :explanation "Vector subtraction is addition of the negated vector: v1 − v2 = v1 + (−v2). If v1 = [a, b, c] and v2 = [d, e, f], then v1 − v2 = [a−d, b−e, c−f]. Exact arithmetic is preserved. With one argument, returns the negation. With 2+ arguments, subtracts left-to-right: vec/- v1 v2 v3 = (v1 − v2) − v3."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(vec/- '(5 7 9) '(1 2 3))" :note "3-D subtraction. Returns (4 5 6).")
    (:tier "apprentice" :code "(vec/- '(1 2 3))" :note "One-arg negates every component. Returns (-1 -2 -3) — cleaner than writing (vec/- '(0 0 0) v) for the same effect.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(let ((start '(3 4))\n      (end '(7 1)))\n  (vec/- end start))" :note "Displacement vector (end − start) from two positions. Returns (4 -3) — four right, three up in screen space where Y grows downward.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(vec/- '(10 10 10) '(1 2 3) '(1 1 1))" :note "N-ary left-to-right subtraction. (10-1-1, 10-2-1, 10-3-1) = (8 7 6). Handy for subtracting several offsets in one call.")
    (:tier "master" :code "(define (velocity from to dt)\n  ;; Given two positions and a time delta, return the average\n  ;; velocity vector: displacement / dt applied component-wise.\n  (map (lambda (x) (/ x dt)) (vec/- to from)))\n(velocity '(0 0) '(6 8) 2)" :note "Compose vec/- with map to compute a velocity. From (0,0) to (6,8) over 2 seconds: (3 4). Magnitude 5 — the 3-4-5 triangle appearing in kinematics.")
  )
  :caveats ("Component-count mismatch does not raise; shorter vectors are zero-padded." "Left-associative: vec/- a b c = (a − b) − c, not a − (b − c)." "Single-argument form returns negation." "Exact arithmetic is preserved; 1/2 − 1/3 yields 1/6 exactly.")
  :drawbacks ("Variadic left-associativity can be counterintuitive; use parentheses to clarify intent." "No in-place operation; creates a fresh vector each time." "Exact rationals can accumulate large numerators/denominators over many operations.")
  :usecases ("Physics: computing relative velocity or displacement between two points." "Graphics: computing edge vectors from vertex pairs." "Linear algebra: forming differences for numerical methods (e.g. gradient descent)." "Signal processing: computing deltas or differences in time series.")
  :related ("vec/+" "vec/scale" "vec/norm" "vec/dot")
  :learn (:concept "Vector subtraction as component-wise negation and addition; left-to-right evaluation" :prerequisites ("vec/+" "vec/make") :progression "Use vec/- to compute displacements, then combine with vec/norm to compute distances, then study vec/angle-between for relative orientation.")
  :math (:algebra ("not-commutative" "identity: zero-vector on the right") :total #t :domain "one or more vectors" :codomain "vector of the largest input dimension")
  :cs (:complexity "time O(k·d), space O(d)" :effects (none) :pure #t)
  :ai (:deterministic #t :cacheable #t :cardinality one :common-mistakes "Expecting right-associative evaluation. (vec/- a b c) subtracts BOTH b and c from a, not (a - (b-c)).")
  :hacker (:primitive #f :kin ("NumPy: v1 - v2 - v3; Clojure: (mapv - v1 v2 v3)") :history "Follows Grassmann's vector algebra; the negation-of-one-arg convention echoes Scheme's numeric (-)."))

(verb
  :name "vec/->string"
  :library "vec"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(vec/->string v) -> string"
  :summary "Convert a vector to a compact parenthesized string of components."
  :impl-status "wired"
  :impl-file "src/wired-verbs.js"
  :impl-notes "Formats as \"(c1 c2 c3)\" — s-expression style. NOT bracket notation. The impl uses parens so debug output round-trips through the reader with a leading quote or list."
  :explanation "Produces a compact string for logging, display, or REPL output. The format uses parentheses and space separators — the same shape the reader accepts, so debug output can be pasted back into code (with a leading quote or list) and it will round-trip. Non-numeric components render as their JS-default toString."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(vec/->string '(3 4))" :note "Bare list works. Returns the string \"(3 4)\".")
    (:tier "apprentice" :code "(vec/->string (vec/make (list 3 4)))" :note "Same result via vec/make: \"(3 4)\". The vector's underlying shape is a list, so vec/->string doesn't need to know the difference.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(vec/->string (vec/+ '(1 2 3) '(4 5 6)))" :note "Compose vec/+ with vec/->string for a one-liner debug print. Returns \"(5 7 9)\".")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (debug-vector-ops label v)\n  (string-append label \": \" (vec/->string v)))\n(list (debug-vector-ops \"Original\" '(1 2 3))\n      (debug-vector-ops \"Doubled\" (vec/+ '(1 2 3) '(1 2 3))))" :note "Named debug helper for annotated inspection. Composable — feeds directly into (display ...) or log lines.")
    (:tier "master" :code "(define (format-transcript ops)\n  ;; ops is a list of (label vec) pairs; render each as one line.\n  (define (fmt-pair p) (string-append (car p) \" = \" (vec/->string (cadr p))))\n  (let loop ((remaining ops) (acc '()))\n    (if (null? remaining)\n        (reverse acc)\n        (loop (cdr remaining)\n              (cons (fmt-pair (car remaining)) acc)))))\n(format-transcript (list (list \"a\" '(1 2))\n                         (list \"b\" '(3 4))\n                         (list \"sum\" (vec/+ '(1 2) '(3 4)))))" :note "Build a transcript of vector operations by pairing each with vec/->string. Three annotated lines — a common pattern when teaching or debugging a linear-algebra derivation.")
  )
  :caveats ("Format is parenthesized (\"(1 2 3)\"), not bracketed — the earlier summary said brackets but the impl uses s-expr style." "Not meant to be a serialization format; use it for humans, not for machine round-trips." "Non-numeric components render as their JS-side toString.")
  :drawbacks ("Produces a new string object per call — avoid in tight inner loops." "No control over precision; Scheme numbers render with JS defaults.")
  :usecases ("Debugging: examining intermediate vector values in a calculation." "REPL interaction: quick eyeball inspection of vec/+ or vec/scale outputs." "Logging: recording vector states during a simulation.")
  :related ("vec/make" "vec/ref" "vec/dim" "vec/=" "matrix/->string")
  :learn (:concept "Display and introspection of vector data without mutation." :prerequisites ("vec/make") :progression "After learning vec/->string, inspect results of vec/+, vec/-, and vec/scale to understand composition.")
  :cs (:complexity "time O(d), space O(d) for dimension d" :effects (none) :pure #t)
  :ai (:deterministic #t :cacheable #t :cardinality one)
  :hacker (:primitive #f :history "Sakura convention — parens over brackets to match the reader."))

(verb
  :name "vec/="
  :library "vec"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(vec/= a b) -> boolean"
  :summary "Test exact component-wise equality of two vectors."
  :impl-status "wired"
  :impl-file "src/wired-verbs.js"
  :impl-notes "Dim check first, then strict === per component. No tolerance."
  :explanation "Returns true if and only if two vectors have the same dimension and every corresponding component is exactly equal (using Scheme's = predicate on numbers). Dimension mismatch returns false. This is a strict equality test, not approximate; use it for validation and exact comparisons, not for floating-point tolerance checks."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(vec/= '(1 2 3) '(1 2 3))" :note "Two identical 3-vectors return #t.")
    (:tier "apprentice" :code "(vec/= '(1 2 3) '(1 2 4))" :note "One component differs — vec/= is all-or-nothing, so #f.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define orig '(2 3))\n(define scaled (vec/scale '(1 1.5) 2))\n(if (vec/= orig scaled) 'match 'differ)" :note "Round-trip: build the target directly, then via vec/scale, verify they agree. (vec/scale v k) returns v*k componentwise.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (all-equal? vecs)\n  (if (null? vecs) #t\n    (let ((v0 (car vecs)))\n      (let loop ((rest (cdr vecs)))\n        (cond ((null? rest) #t)\n              ((vec/= v0 (car rest)) (loop (cdr rest)))\n              (else #f))))))\n(all-equal? (list '(1 0) '(1 0) '(1 0)))" :note "Fold vec/= to check every vector equals the first. Manual short-circuit exits on first mismatch.")
    (:tier "master" :code "(define (find-index target vecs)\n  (let loop ((rest vecs) (i 0))\n    (cond ((null? rest) -1)\n          ((vec/= target (car rest)) i)\n          (else (loop (cdr rest) (+ i 1))))))\n(find-index '(2 3) (list '(1 0) '(0 1) '(2 3) '(5 5)))" :note "Linear search returns 0-based position of first match. Returns 2 — target is at index 2.")
  )
  :math (:algebra ("equivalence relation") :total #t :domain "two vectors" :codomain "boolean")
  :cs (:complexity "time O(d), space O(1)" :effects (none) :pure #t)
  :ai (:deterministic #t :cacheable #t :cardinality one)
  :caveats ("Exact equality: 0.3 ≠ (0.1 + 0.2) due to floating-point rounding." "Different dimensions always compare false; no automatic alignment or zero-padding." "Both arguments must be vectors; passing non-vectors yields false or error depending on implementation.")
  :drawbacks ("Too strict for many numerical applications; consider approximate comparison (e.g., checking vec/norm of difference)." "Does not short-circuit on dimension mismatch in all implementations; may be slower than a custom predicate." "Not idempotent with floating-point: (vec/= v1 v1) is always true, but (vec/= (vec/+ a b) (vec/+ a b)) may differ if intermediate rounding differs.")
  :usecases ("Unit tests: verifying that a transformation produces an expected exact result." "Discrete geometry: checking whether two lattice points coincide." "Symbolic computation: comparing vectors over exact rational or symbolic components.")
  :related ("vec/make" "vec/+" "vec/-" "vec/norm" "matrix/=")
  :learn (:concept "Exact comparison and equality testing in linear algebra." :prerequisites ("vec/make" "= (core form)") :progression "Master vec/= before attempting approximate comparisons or tolerance-based checks; understand floating-point limitations."))

(verb
  :name "vec/angle-between"
  :library "vec"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(vec/angle-between a b) -> number"
  :summary "Compute the angle (in radians) between two vectors via arccosine."
  :impl-status "wired"
  :impl-file "src/wired-verbs.js"
  :impl-notes "Direct dot/magnitude formula: acos(dot(a,b) / (|a|*|b|)). Clamps the cosine to [-1, 1] before acos so tiny floating-point overflows don't produce NaN. Zero-magnitude inputs return 0."
  :explanation "Returns the unsigned angle θ ∈ [0, π] between vectors a and b using θ = acos((a·b)/(‖a‖·‖b‖)). Parallel yields 0. Anti-parallel yields π. Perpendicular yields π/2."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(vec/angle-between '(1 0) '(0 1))" :note "Perpendicular 2-D unit vectors. Returns π/2 ≈ 1.5708.")
    (:tier "apprentice" :code "(vec/angle-between '(1 0) '(-1 0))" :note "Anti-parallel: same axis, opposite direction. Returns π ≈ 3.1416.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define theta (vec/angle-between '(1 1 1) '(1 0 0)))\n(list 'radians theta 'degrees (* theta (/ 180 3.141592653589793)))" :note "3-D angle between (1,1,1) and the x-axis. About 54.7° — the tetrahedral half-angle.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (closest-to target candidates)\n  (let loop ((rest candidates) (best (car candidates))\n              (best-a (vec/angle-between target (car candidates))))\n    (if (null? rest) best\n        (let ((a (vec/angle-between target (car rest))))\n          (if (< a best-a)\n              (loop (cdr rest) (car rest) a)\n              (loop (cdr rest) best best-a))))))\n(closest-to '(1 0 0) (list '(1 1 0) '(0 1 0) '(1 0 1)))" :note "Find the candidate with smallest angle to target — direction snapping. Returns the first one that ties (both (1 1 0) and (1 0 1) are 45° off).")
    (:tier "master" :code "(define (angle-classify a b)\n  (let ((theta (vec/angle-between a b)))\n    (cond ((< theta 0.001)                'parallel)\n          ((< (abs (- theta 1.5708)) 0.001) 'perpendicular)\n          ((< (abs (- theta 3.14159)) 0.001) 'anti-parallel)\n          ((< theta 1.5708)               'acute)\n          (else                            'obtuse))))\n(list (angle-classify '(1 0) '(1 0))\n      (angle-classify '(1 0) '(0 1))\n      (angle-classify '(1 0) '(-1 0))\n      (angle-classify '(1 0) '(1 1)))" :note "Named regions with epsilon tolerance. Returns (parallel perpendicular anti-parallel acute) — the four archetypal cases.")
  )
  :math (:total #t :domain "two vectors of matching dimension" :codomain "real in [0, π]")
  :cs (:complexity "time O(d), space O(1)" :effects (none) :pure #t)
  :ai (:deterministic #t :cacheable #t :cardinality one :common-mistakes "Passing zero vectors — the impl returns 0 rather than raising; a common source of silent bugs.")
  :caveats ("Dimension mismatch halts with 'dim-mismatch; ensure vectors have equal size." "Zero vectors cause division by zero, yielding NaN." "Floating-point rounding in dot product and norms can introduce small errors; angles near 0 or π are most sensitive." "The result is always in [0, π]; use vec/dot or geom/atan2 to distinguish opposite directions if needed.")
  :drawbacks ("Slower than direct dot-product tests (e.g., dot ≈ 0 for perpendicularity); use vec/dot first for filtering." "acos is computationally expensive; avoid calling repeatedly in tight loops without caching." "Returns NaN (not an error) for zero vectors, making silent bugs possible.")
  :usecases ("Robotics: measuring angular deviation between desired and actual heading vectors." "Computer vision: finding the closest-aligned feature vector in a set." "Geometry: classifying angle relationships (acute, right, obtuse) for constraints.")
  :related ("vec/dot" "vec/norm" "vec/normalize" "vec/cross" "geom/angle-between" "const/pi")
  :learn (:concept "Geometric angle measurement via the dot product and arccosine." :prerequisites ("vec/dot" "vec/norm" "geom/->radians") :progression "After vec/angle-between, learn vec/cross for 3-D orientation and geom/law-of-cosines-angle for triangle geometry."))

(verb
  :name "vec/cross"
  :library "vec"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(vec/cross a b) -> vector"
  :summary "Compute the 3-D cross product a × b."
  :explanation "Returns a new 3-D vector perpendicular to both input vectors, with magnitude equal to the area of the parallelogram they span. The direction follows the right-hand rule. Both inputs must be exactly 3-dimensional; other dimensions yield 'dim-3-required error. The result is exact for rational inputs but subject to floating-point rounding for reals."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(define x-axis (vec/make (list 1 0 0)))\n(define y-axis (vec/make (list 0 1 0)))\n(vec/cross x-axis y-axis)" :note "Standard basis vectors; result is (0, 0, 1) (the z-axis).")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define a (vec/make (list 1 2 3)))\n(define b (vec/make (list 4 5 6)))\n(define perp (vec/cross a b))\n(display (list 'perpendicular: (vec/->string perp)\n               'dot-with-a: (vec/dot a perp)\n               'dot-with-b: (vec/dot b perp)))" :note "Computes cross product and verifies orthogonality by checking dot products are zero.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (triangle-normal p1 p2 p3)\n  (vec/cross (vec/- p2 p1) (vec/- p3 p1)))\n(define (triangle-area p1 p2 p3)\n  (/ (vec/norm (triangle-normal p1 p2 p3)) 2))\n(let ((v0 (vec/make (list 0 0 0)))\n      (v1 (vec/make (list 1 0 0)))\n      (v2 (vec/make (list 0 1 0))))\n  (triangle-area v0 v1 v2))" :note "Uses cross product to compute a triangle's surface normal and area—standard in 3-D graphics.")
  )
  :caveats ("Input dimension must be exactly 3; 2-D or 4-D vectors raise 'dim-3-required." "Cross product is not commutative: a × b = -(b × a)." "For nearly parallel vectors, the result has very small magnitude and is numerically unstable." "The cross product is a 3-D concept; there is no generalization to other dimensions in this library.")
  :drawbacks ("Only works in 3-D; for 2-D, compute the scalar (pseudo) cross product using vec/dot indirectly or use geom/cross." "Slower than vec/dot; avoid in inner loops if a scalar test (like orientation) suffices." "Result magnitude grows as the sine of the angle; nearly parallel vectors give unreliable normals for graphics.")
  :usecases ("3-D graphics: computing surface normals for lighting calculations." "Robotics: finding the axis of rotation between two end-effector directions." "Computational geometry: determining the orientation (handedness) of point triples.")
  :related ("vec/dot" "vec/norm" "vec/normalize" "vec/angle-between" "geom/cross")
  :learn (:concept "The cross product and its right-hand-rule orientation in 3-D space." :prerequisites ("vec/make" "vec/dot" "vec/-") :progression "Master vec/cross before diving into matrix transformations (linalg/* verbs) or 3-D graphics (entity/* spatial verbs)."))

(verb
  :name "vec/dim"
  :library "vec"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(vec/dim v) -> number"
  :summary "Return the dimension (component count) of a vector."
  :impl-status "wired"
  :impl-file "src/wired-verbs.js"
  :impl-notes "Length lookup on the underlying list. Non-list inputs coerce to a 1-element list (dim 1); the empty list gives 0."
  :explanation "Returns the number of components in the vector as a non-negative integer. A vector with components [a, b, c] has dimension 3. This is O(1) introspection that does not modify the vector. Essential for dimension-polymorphic code and for validation before vec/+ that require matching dimensions."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(vec/dim '(1 2 3 4))" :note "A 4-component vector. Returns 4.")
    (:tier "apprentice" :code "(vec/dim '())" :note "Empty list has dimension 0. Valid, if uncommon — often signals an intermediate calculation ran out of components.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define (same-size? u v)\n  (= (vec/dim u) (vec/dim v)))\n(list (same-size? '(1 2 3) '(4 5 6)) (same-size? '(1 2) '(1 2 3)))" :note "Predicate for pre-checking vec/+ compatibility. Returns (#t #f).")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (safe-vec-op u v op)\n  (if (= (vec/dim u) (vec/dim v))\n      (op u v)\n      'dim-mismatch))\n(list (safe-vec-op '(1 2 3) '(4 5 6) vec/+)\n      (safe-vec-op '(1 2) '(1 2 3) vec/+))" :note "Guarded op: apply only when dims agree, else return the sentinel. Returns ((5 7 9) dim-mismatch).")
    (:tier "master" :code "(define (all-same-dim? vecs)\n  (cond ((null? vecs) #t)\n        (else\n         (let ((d (vec/dim (car vecs))))\n           (let loop ((rest (cdr vecs)))\n             (cond ((null? rest) #t)\n                   ((= (vec/dim (car rest)) d) (loop (cdr rest)))\n                   (else #f)))))))\n(list (all-same-dim? (list '(1 0) '(0 1) '(1 1)))\n      (all-same-dim? (list '(1 2 3) '(4 5))))" :note "Validate a whole batch: only proceed with (vec/+) or its friends if every vector in the list has matching dim. Returns (#t #f).")
  )
  :caveats ("Returns the logical dimension; an empty vector (dimension 0) is valid but uncommon." "Dimension is immutable once the vector is constructed; you cannot resize a vector in place." "Two vectors with the same dimension may still fail operations like vec/cross if dimension ≠ 3.")
  :drawbacks ("Not necessary for vectors created and used inline; useful mainly for validation in polymorphic contexts." "Should not be called in tight loops if you already know the dimension; cache it instead.")
  :usecases ("Validation: checking that incoming vectors match expected shape before computation." "Polymorphism: writing functions that work across vectors of any dimension (2-D, 3-D, n-D)." "Serialization: recording metadata about a vector for later reconstruction.")
  :related ("vec/make" "vec/ref" "vec/->string" "matrix/rows" "matrix/cols")
  :learn (:concept "Dimension as a fundamental property of a vector and a guard for operation composition." :prerequisites ("vec/make") :progression "Use vec/dim in guards before calling vec/+ or vec/cross; learn it early as a safety tool."))

(verb
  :name "vec/dot"
  :library "vec"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(vec/dot a b) -> number"
  :summary "Compute the dot product a·b (a scalar)."
  :explanation "Returns the sum of component-wise products: a·b = Σ(aᵢ × bᵢ). The result is a scalar (single number), not a vector. Both inputs must have identical dimension; dimension mismatch yields 'dim-mismatch. The dot product measures alignment: positive (< 90°), zero (perpendicular), or negative (> 90°). It is the foundation for projections, angles, and norms."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(define u (vec/make (list 1 2)))\n(define v (vec/make (list 3 4)))\n(vec/dot u v)" :note "Computes 1*3 + 2*4 = 11.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define a (vec/make (list 1 0 0)))\n(define b (vec/make (list 1 1 1)))\n(define projection-scale (/ (vec/dot a b) (vec/dot a a)))\n(vec/scale projection-scale a)" :note "Uses dot product to project vector b onto vector a.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (gram-matrix vecs)\n  (map (lambda (u)\n         (map (lambda (v) (vec/dot u v)) vecs))\n       vecs))\n(let ((basis (list (vec/make (list 1 0))\n                   (vec/make (list 0 1)))))\n  (gram-matrix basis))" :note "Constructs the Gram matrix (all pairwise dot products) of a set of vectors—used in linear independence checks.")
  )
  :caveats ("Dimension must match exactly; no broadcasting or zero-padding." "Returns 'dim-mismatch (not an error exception) on dimension mismatch." "Floating-point rounding accumulates in the sum; for high-dimensional vectors, consider Kahan summation if precision is critical." "Dot product with zero vector is always 0, making it unsuitable for distinguishing orthogonality in degenerate cases.")
  :drawbacks ("O(n) in dimension, so very high-dimensional vectors are slow to dot-product." "Not suitable as the sole test for perpendicularity (use vec/angle-between or tolerance-based checks)." "Result can overflow or underflow for very large or very small component values.")
  :usecases ("Linear algebra: computing projections, orthogonal decompositions, and inner products." "Physics: calculating work (force · displacement) or power in simulations." "Machine learning: computing similarities and distances between feature vectors.")
  :related ("vec/+" "vec/-" "vec/scale" "vec/norm" "vec/angle-between" "vec/cross")
  :learn (:concept "The dot product as a measure of alignment and the foundation of inner product spaces." :prerequisites ("vec/make" "+ (core form)") :progression "Master vec/dot before vec/norm (which uses dot internally) and vec/angle-between."))

(verb
  :name "vec/make"
  :library "vec"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(vec/make lst) -> vector"
  :summary "Construct a vector from a list of components."
  :explanation "Takes a Scheme list of numbers and returns a new vector object. Non-numeric elements yield 'nan. The order of elements in the list becomes the order of components in the vector. Lists are the standard way to bootstrap vectors in Sakura Scheme; once created, vectors are accessed via vec/ref (by index) or composed with arithmetic operators. This is the entry point for all vector operations."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(vec/make (list 3 4))" :note "Creates a 2-D vector with components [3, 4].")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define coords (list 1 2 3))\n(define v (vec/make coords))\n(vec/dot v v)" :note "Constructs a 3-D vector from a list and computes its squared norm (vec/dot v v = ‖v‖²).")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (list->vec-safe lst)\n  (if (every number? lst)\n    (vec/make lst)\n    (escalate 'non-numeric-element lst)))\n(define (batch-normalize vecs)\n  (map (lambda (lst)\n         (let ((v (list->vec-safe lst)))\n           (vec/normalize v)))\n       vecs))\n(batch-normalize (list (list 3 4) (list 1 0 0)))" :note "Wraps vec/make in validation logic and uses it to normalize a batch of vector-like lists.")
  )
  :caveats ("Input must be a proper list; improper lists (dotted pairs) are rejected." "Non-numeric elements are detected and yield 'nan; no partial construction." "An empty list creates a vector of dimension 0, which is valid but uncommon and can cause issues in dot products." "Once created, the internal structure cannot be modified; vectors are immutable.")
  :drawbacks ("O(n) construction time in dimension n; creating many high-dimensional vectors is slow." "No lazy or streaming construction; the entire list is consumed at once." "If a list is reused after vec/make, changes to the list do not affect the vector (deep copy semantics).")
  :usecases ("Initialization: bootstrap vectors from user input, file data, or computed lists." "Scripting: quick vector creation in REPL or test code." "Interoperability: convert list-based data formats to vectors for linear algebra.")
  :related ("vec/ref" "vec/dim" "vec/->string" "vec/+" "list (core form)" "matrix/make")
  :learn (:concept "Vector construction from lists and the transition from list-based to vector-based arithmetic." :prerequisites ("list (core form)" "number? (core form)") :progression "After vec/make, learn vec/ref (to access components) and vec/+ (to compose vectors)."))

(verb
  :name "vec/norm"
  :library "vec"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(vec/norm v) -> number"
  :summary "Compute the Euclidean length (magnitude) ‖v‖ = √(v·v)."
  :explanation "Returns the Euclidean norm of a vector as a non-negative real number. Computed as the square root of the dot product of the vector with itself: ‖v‖ = √(Σ vᵢ²). For a 2-D vector [3, 4], the norm is 5. The norm is always non-negative and is zero only for the zero vector. It is used to measure distance, normalize vectors, and compute vector magnitude."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(define v (vec/make (list 3 4)))\n(vec/norm v)" :note "A 2-D vector; norm is √(9+16) = 5.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define v (vec/make (list 1 2 2)))\n(define n (vec/norm v))\n(define unit-v (vec/scale (/ 1 n) v))\n(vec/norm unit-v)" :note "Computes the norm, then manually normalizes by scaling, then verifies the result has norm 1.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (distance u v)\n  (vec/norm (vec/- u v)))\n(define (within-tolerance? p1 p2 tol)\n  (< (distance p1 p2) tol))\n(let ((target (vec/make (list 1.0 1.0)))\n      (candidate (vec/make (list 1.01 0.99))))\n  (within-tolerance? target candidate 0.02))" :note "Uses vec/norm to compute Euclidean distance and implement a tolerance-based comparison for spatial proximity.")
  )
  :caveats ("Floating-point rounding in the dot product and sqrt can introduce errors; for very large or very small components, the result may be inaccurate." "Zero vector has norm 0; division by norm (as in normalization) requires a zero check." "The norm is always non-negative; negative norms are impossible." "High-dimensional vectors accumulate rounding errors in the dot product summation.")
  :drawbacks ("sqrt is computationally expensive; avoid calling vec/norm repeatedly in tight loops. Cache or use vec/dot(v, v) if you only need the squared norm." "Not suitable for sorting or ranking without external criteria; norms alone do not provide a total order on vectors." "Overflow/underflow risk for very large (≫ 1e308) or very small (≪ 1e-308) components.")
  :usecases ("Normalization: computing the magnitude before scaling to unit length (vec/normalize)." "Distance: measuring Euclidean distance between points (distance = ‖p2 - p1‖)." "Magnitude-based filtering: selecting vectors or points that exceed a threshold size.")
  :related ("vec/dot" "vec/normalize" "vec/scale" "vec/angle-between" "geom/distance")
  :learn (:concept "The Euclidean norm as a measure of vector magnitude and the foundation of normalization." :prerequisites ("vec/make" "vec/dot") :progression "After vec/norm, learn vec/normalize (which divides by norm) and use both in distance/similarity calculations."))

(verb
  :name "vec/normalize"
  :library "vec"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(vec/normalize v) -> vector"
  :summary "Produce a unit vector in the direction of v; the zero vector returns the symbol 'zero-vector."
  :explanation "Normalization scales a vector to length 1 while preserving its direction. It divides each component by the vector's Euclidean norm ‖v‖. This is essential for creating direction-only quantities in physics, graphics, and navigation. The zero vector cannot be normalized (no direction), so it returns the symbol 'zero-vector rather than raising an error."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(define v (list 3 4))\n(vec/normalize v)" :note "Scales (3, 4) with norm 5 to (0.6, 0.8), a unit vector.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define direction (vec/normalize (list (- target-x pos-x) (- target-y pos-y))))\n(define velocity (vec/scale direction speed))" :note "Normalize the difference to get a direction, then scale by speed to get a velocity of fixed magnitude.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (aim-at-target entity target-pos)\n  (let* ((delta (list (- (entity/x target-pos) (entity/x entity))\n                      (- (entity/y target-pos) (entity/y entity))))\n         (direction (vec/normalize delta)))\n    (entity/set-vel! entity (vec/scale direction (entity/get entity 'max-speed)))))" :note "Normalize the vector from entity to target, then apply it as a velocity at max speed, keeping direction exact.")
  )
  :caveats ("Passing a zero vector (all components 0) returns the symbol 'zero-vector; check for this before assuming a valid vector." "Result is deterministic only within device-level floating-point precision; comparing normalized vectors for exact equality will often fail." "The normalized vector has magnitude approximately 1, but not exactly 1 due to rounding.")
  :drawbacks ("Computing the norm (via sqrt) is moderately expensive; if you only need direction comparison, use vec/angle-between instead." "Normalizing a very small vector may lose precision; clip to a minimum magnitude if this is critical." "Does not modify the input vector; if you need in-place normalization, you must rebind the name.")
  :usecases ("Convert a displacement into a direction for movement or aiming." "Create a unit normal for surface reflections or lighting." "Decouple speed from direction in steering or animation." "Standardize vectors before geometric comparison or transformation.")
  :related ("vec/norm" "vec/scale" "vec/angle-between" "vec/dot" "entity/move!")
  :learn (:concept "Unit vectors and normalization as a way to separate direction from magnitude." :prerequisites ("vec/norm" "vec/make" "vec/scale") :progression "After mastering normalization, study vec/angle-between to compare directions without normalizing, and vec/cross for oriented geometry."))

(verb
  :name "vec/ref"
  :library "vec"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(vec/ref v i) -> number"
  :summary "Extract the i-th component of vector v (0-based indexing)."
  :impl-status "wired"
  :impl-file "src/wired-verbs.js"
  :impl-notes "Positional lookup on the underlying list. Out-of-range index returns () (empty list), NOT the 'nan symbol earlier docs promised. Guard with (vec/dim v) first if a signaled miss matters."
  :explanation "Vectors in Sakura Scheme are sequences of numeric components. vec/ref provides positional access by index, like car and cdr on lists. Index 0 is the first component, 1 the second, and so on."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(vec/ref '(10 20 30) 0)" :note "First component. Returns 10.")
    (:tier "apprentice" :code "(vec/ref '(10 20 30) 2)" :note "Third component (index 2). Returns 30.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define center '(320 240))\n(list (vec/ref center 0) (vec/ref center 1))" :note "Extract x and y from a 2-D position vector. Returns (320 240).")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (component-wise-op v f)\n  (let loop ((i 0) (result '()))\n    (if (>= i (vec/dim v))\n        (reverse result)\n        (loop (+ i 1)\n              (cons (f (vec/ref v i)) result)))))\n(component-wise-op '(2 3 4) (lambda (x) (* x x)))" :note "Iterate all components using vec/ref and vec/dim to build a new result. Returns (4 9 16) — component squares.")
    (:tier "master" :code "(define (dot-via-ref u v)\n  (let loop ((i 0) (acc 0))\n    (if (>= i (vec/dim u))\n        acc\n        (loop (+ i 1)\n              (+ acc (* (vec/ref u i) (vec/ref v i)))))))\n(dot-via-ref '(1 2 3) '(4 5 6))" :note "Hand-rolled dot product via vec/ref + vec/dim. Returns 32. Prefer the built-in vec/dot in real code; this shows the pattern.")
  )
  :caveats ("Indices are 0-based." "Out-of-range indices return () (empty list), not 'nan or an error. Guard with (vec/dim v) if a signaled miss matters." "vec/ref does not modify the vector; it is read-only.")
  :drawbacks ("For bulk operations (e.g., scaling all components), it is more efficient to use vec/scale, vec/+, or vec/- rather than looping with vec/ref." "No bounds checking exception; relies on the 'nan sentinel, which may hide logic errors if not tested explicitly.")
  :usecases ("Extract a single coordinate (x, y, or z) from a position or velocity vector." "Implement custom component-wise logic not covered by vec/+, vec/-, vec/scale, etc." "Validate or log individual vector components for debugging." "Iterate through vector components in a custom map or fold.")
  :related ("vec/dim" "vec/make" "vec/+" "vec/-" "vec/scale")
  :learn (:concept "Component access and iteration as building blocks for generic vector algorithms." :prerequisites ("vec/make" "vec/dim") :progression "After learning vec/ref, study vec/dim to understand vector size, then explore higher-level operations like vec/scale and vec/dot that combine ref patterns."))

(verb
  :name "vec/scale"
  :library "vec"
  :kind "meta"
  :signature "(vec/scale v k) -> vector"
  :summary "Multiply every component of vector v by scalar k, returning a new vector."
  :explanation "Scaling a vector uniformly (all components by the same factor) is one of the most fundamental operations in linear algebra and physics. It changes magnitude while preserving direction. Scaling by 0 produces the zero vector; scaling by 1 returns an equivalent vector; negative scales reverse direction. This is the bridge between direction (normalized vectors) and magnitude."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(define direction (list 1 0))\n(vec/scale direction 50)" :note "Scales the unit vector (1, 0) by 50 to get (50, 0), a magnitude-50 vector pointing right.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define velocity (list 3 4))\n(define dt 0.016)\n(define displacement (vec/scale velocity dt))\n(entity/move! player displacement)" :note "Multiply a velocity by time delta to get a small displacement per frame.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (physics-step entity dt gravity-scale)\n  (let* ((gravity (list 0 (- (* gravity-scale 9.8))))\n         (accel-this-frame (vec/scale gravity dt))\n         (new-vel (vec/+ (entity/vel entity) accel-this-frame)))\n    (entity/set-vel! entity new-vel)))" :note "Accumulate gravitational acceleration over a time step using vec/scale, composing with vec/+ for realistic motion.")
  )
  :caveats ("Scaling by 0 produces the zero vector, which cannot be normalized later (vec/normalize will return 'zero-vector)." "Scaling by a negative value reverses the vector's direction; check sign if direction matters." "Result is a new vector; the original v is not modified.")
  :drawbacks ("For 2-component or 3-component vectors, manual component multiplication is not significantly faster; use vec/scale for clarity." "Scaling by very large or very small factors may cause floating-point underflow or overflow; clamp magnitudes if needed." "No special handling for NaN or infinity; propagates them as-is.")
  :usecases ("Apply a time delta to a velocity or acceleration to compute displacement." "Adjust the magnitude of a direction vector without changing direction." "Dampen or amplify a force or acceleration in physics simulations." "Implement smooth easing by scaling a delta over time.")
  :related ("vec/normalize" "vec/+" "vec/-" "vec/norm" "entity/set-vel!")
  :learn (:concept "Scalar multiplication as a way to adjust magnitude while preserving direction." :prerequisites ("vec/make" "vec/normalize") :progression "After mastering vec/scale, learn vec/+ and vec/- to combine multiple scaled vectors, then explore vec/dot for projection and vec/cross for orientation."))

; ─── library: weather (1 verbs) ───

(verb
  :name "weather/conjure"
  :library "weather"
  :kind "null"
  :signature "(weather/conjure state [at: pos] [scale: num] [colour: color]) -> 'ok | escalate-token"
  :summary "Add a transient weather effect (rain, fog, wind, etc.) to the scene at a specified location and scale."
  :explanation "weather/conjure returns a descriptor that spawns a visual weather effect (particle system, shader overlay, or animation) anchored to a position in the world. It accepts keyword arguments: at (a 2-vector [x y] or object with :x :y), scale (a multiplier for effect intensity), and colour (a color override). The effect is temporary; it plays out and dissipates. Returns 'ok on success, or an escalate token if the weather subsystem is not wired (rare in production, common during testing)."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(weather/conjure 'rain :at (list 100 200))" :note "Spawn rain at world position (100, 200); simple weather effect.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define (storm-sequence ctx)\n  (let ((result (weather/conjure 'thunderstorm :at (card-rect 'player :center) :scale 1.5)))\n    (if (eq? result 'ok)\n      (next 'storming ctx)\n      (next 'escalate-weather ctx))))" :note "Conjure a thunderstorm at the player's center, scaled 1.5×; if successful, transition to storming state; if weather is unavailable, escalate.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (environmental-response ctx)\n  (let* ((biome (ctx-get 'biome ctx))\n         (weather-type (case biome\n                         ((tundra) 'blizzard)\n                         ((jungle) 'monsoon)\n                         ((desert) 'sandstorm)\n                         (else 'rain)))\n         (intensity (ctx-get 'danger-level ctx))\n         (conjure-result (weather/conjure weather-type\n                           :at (ctx-get 'epicenter ctx)\n                           :scale (/ intensity 10.0)\n                           :colour (ctx-get 'weather-tint ctx))))\n    (if (eq? conjure-result 'ok)\n      (next 'weathering (ctx-set 'active-weather weather-type ctx))\n      (escalate 'weather-system-offline ctx))))" :note "Select weather type based on biome, scale intensity by danger level, apply custom tint; handle both success and system unavailability gracefully.")
  )
  :caveats ("weather/conjure spawns an effect but does not control its duration; the effect plays out and stops automatically." "The at position is world-space; if the position is off-screen, the effect still runs but is invisible." "Unknown weather types (typos or unregistered states) are accepted but produce no visual effect; no error is raised." "If the weather subsystem is not wired (e.g., during headless testing), the descriptor returns an escalate token; you must handle escalation.")
  :drawbacks ("No way to stop or cancel a weather effect once spawned; effects run their full duration." "Multiple overlapping weather effects at the same location may cause visual aliasing or overdraw." "scale parameter is a raw multiplier; very large scales can degrade rendering performance.")
  :usecases ("Environmental storytelling: add atmosphere (fog, mist, particles) to a scene during cutscenes." "Dynamic hazards: spawn dangerous weather (lightning, fire) at the player's location as a hazard." "Biome transitions: conjure appropriate weather when entering a new biome or region.")
  :related ("scene/imagine" "surface/spotlight" "surface/dim" "card-emit")
  :learn (:concept "Transient environmental effects; keyword argument parsing and optional parameters." :prerequisites ("act" "next") :progression "After weather/conjure, explore surface/dim and surface/spotlight for static lighting effects, then move to card-emit for character-anchored particle effects."))

; ─── library: world (39 verbs) ───

(verb
  :name "world/after"
  :library "world"
  :kind "mut"
  :signature "(world/after n kind key) -> void"
  :summary "Schedule an event to fire on the message bus N frames from now."
  :explanation "In Sakura, the message bus is how entities and cards communicate asynchronously. `world/after` is a frame-counted timer: call it with a delay in frames, a message kind (symbol), and a key, and the world will emit `(kind key)` exactly N frames later. This is useful for: delayed actions (\"spawn an enemy 30 frames from now\"), timed sequences (\"play sound 1, then sound 2 after 60 frames\"), and cleanup (\"remove a temporary particle effect after its duration expires\"). The mutation is internal: no entity or card is modified, but the world's timer queue grows."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(world/after 30 'enemy-spawn 'goblin-1)" :note "Thirty frames from now, emit 'enemy-spawn with goblin-1 as the key; some listener (card or actor) will handle it.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define (timed-sequence)\n  (world/after 0 'sound 'kick)\n  (world/after 15 'sound 'snare)\n  (world/after 30 'sound 'kick))" :note "Fire three sounds in a drum pattern; each offset creates a rhythm.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (on-card-emit card payload)\n  (let ((duration (car payload)))\n    (world/after duration 'particle-fade (card-id-of card))\n    (next 'waiting card)))" :note "When a particle emitter fires, schedule its fade-out based on the duration payload. Common pattern in game state machines.")
  )
  :caveats ("Delay is in frames, not milliseconds; frame rate (e.g., 60 FPS) affects wall-clock time." "Events are guaranteed to fire exactly once, at the specified frame. If the game is paused or fast-forwarded, timing is frame-relative, not real-time." "If N <= 0, the event may fire immediately or on the next frame, depending on world tick order. Use 0 for \"fire now (deferred)\" semantics." "The key can be any value (symbol, string, list); it is passed as-is to listeners. No type checking.")
  :drawbacks ("Cannot cancel or reschedule an event once scheduled; design your state machine to ignore unwanted events." "Timer queue grows linearly with events; many pending timers = slight CPU cost each frame." "No built-in per-entity scoping; if entity A and entity B both use `world/after`, their events are global and unsorted." "If the world is reset (`world/reset!`), all pending timers are cleared.")
  :usecases ("Delayed spawn: enemy waves, NPC dialogue triggers." "Timed sequences: rhythm games, choreographed camera moves." "Cleanup: fade out particles, disable temporary UI, despawn effects." "State machine transitions: \"wait 120 frames, then check a condition and move to the next state.\"")
  :related ("world/reset!" "world/step" "on-frame" "time/every-ms")
  :learn (:concept "Deferred events and frame-based scheduling—decoupling logic from immediate execution." :prerequisites ("big-bang" "world/spawn") :progression "world/snapshot (to record the timer queue in a replay); cine/shot (to choreograph camera or entity sequences in parallel)"))

(verb
  :name "world/attract!"
  :library "world"
  :kind "mut"
  :signature "(world/attract! id cx cy strength) -> void"
  :summary "Pull an entity toward a point (cx, cy) using a softened inverse-square force."
  :explanation "Gravity, magnetism, and vortexes are all attraction forces. `world/attract!` applies an accelerating force to an entity that pulls it toward a target location with strength that softens as distance increases (inverse-square falloff). Unlike a direct velocity set, this integrates into the entity's physics: the entity accelerates, can overshoot, and interacts with friction and other forces. Use this for: gravity wells, vacuum effects, homing behavior, and orbital mechanics. The mutation is local to the entity's acceleration accumulator; it does not change position directly."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(world/attract! player-id 400 300 5)" :note "Pull the player toward (400, 300) with strength 5. Player accelerates toward the point.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define (gravity-well cx cy strength)\n  (for-each (lambda (id) (world/attract! id cx cy strength))\n            (group/find 'affected-by-gravity)))" :note "Loop over all entities tagged 'affected-by-gravity' and pull each toward the well center.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (on-frame id ctx)\n  (let ((vortex-x (ctx-get 'vortex-x ctx))\n        (vortex-y (ctx-get 'vortex-y ctx))\n        (strength (ctx-get 'vortex-strength ctx)))\n    (world/attract! id vortex-x vortex-y strength)\n    (next 'falling ctx)))" :note "In a card's frame handler, apply vortex pull based on context parameters. Strength decays or moves with the vortex.")
  )
  :caveats ("Attraction is applied every frame; strength is per-frame acceleration. High strength can cause instability or unrealistic jittery motion." "The entity must have physics enabled (mass > 0, embodiment set) to be affected. Non-physics entities ignore this verb." "Distance is Euclidean (sqrt(dx^2 + dy^2)); no line-of-sight or obstacle checks." "Attract and repel are independent: calling both on the same entity in one frame sums their effects.")
  :drawbacks ("Cannot clamp or cap the entity's speed; very strong attraction + high mass can produce runaway velocities." "Inverse-square falloff means nearby entities feel much stronger force; design distances carefully to avoid jerky behavior." "If target is at the entity, epsilon singularity softening still produces large acceleration; move target away or check distance in caller." "No drag damping built-in; combine with `entity/drag!` to avoid runaway oscillation.")
  :usecases ("Gravity well: enemies sucked into a black hole or vortex." "Homing missile or projectile: pulled toward a moving target." "Magnetic field: metal objects drawn to a lodestone or energy source." "Orbital mechanics: planet gravity, comet tail dynamics.")
  :related ("world/repel!" "world/wind!" "entity/gravity-scale!" "entity/accel!")
  :learn (:concept "Distance-based force fields—attraction as an emergent physics behavior, not teleportation." :prerequisites ("world/spawn" "entity/pos" "entity/vel") :progression "world/repel! (inverse of attraction); ai/seek (goal-seeking behavior on top of physics)"))

(verb
  :name "world/camera"
  :library "world"
  :kind "rd"
  :signature "(world/camera) -> [x y]"
  :summary "Return the camera's center position [x, y] this frame, including any active shake effect."
  :explanation "The camera is what the player sees: a viewport that frames part of the world. The camera can be shaken (impact effects), panned (smooth follow), or snapped (instant jump). `world/camera` reads the resolved camera center—the final [x, y] after all effects (shake, follow, bounds-clamping) are applied. This is the truth: use it to know exactly where the screen is looking. It is read-only; to change the camera, use `world/camera-snap!`, `world/camera-follow!`, or `world/camera-shake!`."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(let ((cam (world/camera)))\n  (list (car cam) (cadr cam)))" :note "Get the camera's current center; unpack x and y.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define (in-viewport? x y margin)\n  (let ((cam (world/camera)))\n    (and (> x (- (car cam) margin))\n         (< x (+ (car cam) margin)))))" :note "Check if a world point is within the camera viewport (within margin units of center).")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (on-frame id ctx)\n  (let* ((cam (world/camera))\n         (dist (entity/distance id (car cam) (cadr cam))))\n    (if (> dist 1000)\n      (escalate 'off-screen ctx)\n      (next 'active ctx))))" :note "Entity state machine: if off-screen (far from camera), switch to idle/despawn. Common culling pattern.")
  )
  :caveats ("Returns [x, y] as a two-element list; unpack with `car` and `cadr`." "The returned value includes active shake; if you want the non-shaken center, subtract the shake vector separately (not exposed by this verb)." "Camera position is post-bounds-clamping; if the world is small and camera is at bounds, the \"ideal\" follow target may be off-camera." "The camera state is updated during `world/step` after physics; if you call `world/camera` before the frame is stepped, you get the prior frame's camera.")
  :drawbacks ("Read-only; cannot modify camera directly from this call. Use `world/camera-snap!` or `world/camera-follow!` to change it." "No batch read of camera + viewport size together; must call `world/camera` and separately query viewport dimensions (e.g., `viewport-width`)." "Shake decay is baked in; cannot query pre-shake position or remaining shake amplitude.")
  :usecases ("Culling: skip rendering or updating entities far off-screen." "Viewport-relative positioning: HUD, crosshair, or tooltips anchored to screen center." "Debugging: visualize or log where the camera is each frame." "Procedural generation: spawn entities only near the camera to save memory.")
  :related ("world/camera-snap!" "world/camera-follow!" "world/camera-bounds!" "world/camera-shake!" "viewport-width")
  :learn (:concept "Camera as a query—learning what the screen sees right now." :prerequisites ("world/spawn" "entity/pos") :progression "world/camera-follow! (to control camera behavior); cine/follow (for cinematic camera choreography)"))

(verb
  :name "world/camera-bounds!"
  :library "world"
  :kind "mut"
  :signature "(world/camera-bounds! x y w h) -> void"
  :summary "Restrict the camera center to stay within a rectangular region (x, y, w, h)."
  :explanation "By default, the camera follows the player or target freely. In a bounded level (a room, a dungeon floor, a small map), you want to prevent the camera from showing the void or wandering off-map. `world/camera-bounds!` sets a hard clamp rect: the camera center can never move outside [x, x+w) by [y, y+h). This is typically called once per level load. The bounds are axis-aligned and do not rotate. The camera position is clamped after all other updates (follow, shake), so the shake can briefly violate bounds, but the underlying center stays inside."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(world/camera-bounds! 0 0 800 600)" :note "Confine camera to a 800×600 room at origin (0, 0).")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define (load-room room-id)\n  (let ((rect (room-rect room-id)))\n    (world/camera-bounds! (car rect) (cadr rect) (caddr rect) (cadddr rect))))" :note "On room load, set camera bounds from the room's bounding rect. Room rect is (x y w h).")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (transition-to-next-room next-id)\n  (world/camera-snap! (room-start-x next-id) (room-start-y next-id))\n  (world/camera-bounds! (room-x next-id) (room-y next-id) (room-w next-id) (room-h next-id))\n  (next 'explore ctx))" :note "On room transition: snap camera to new room start, set new bounds, resume play. Classic Metroidvania pattern.")
  )
  :caveats ("Bounds are the *center* of the screen, not the viewport edges. The viewport extends ±(viewport-width/2) and ±(viewport-height/2) from center, so visible boundaries will extend beyond the bounds rect." "If you call `world/camera-bounds!` with a rect smaller than the viewport, the camera center is clamped to a tiny area and the viewport fills with out-of-bounds pixels (usually black/void)." "Bounds are applied *after* shake; if shake amplitude is large, the camera can oscillate up to its bounds." "No smooth transition between bound changes; switching bounds mid-gameplay can pop the camera.")
  :drawbacks ("Bounds are axis-aligned; cannot define L-shaped or rotated level boundaries." "No soft bounds or easing; clamping is hard and instant." "Cannot query current bounds; you must track the active bounds in your own state." "If bounds are tighter than the viewport, the player sees off-level content; design your level rects carefully.")
  :usecases ("Room-based games: confine camera to one room at a time." "Scrolling platformer: prevent camera from wandering beyond level edges." "Top-down dungeon crawler: keep viewport within the current chamber." "Tutorial or confined arena: lock camera to a smaller play area.")
  :related ("world/camera" "world/camera-snap!" "world/camera-follow!" "viewport-width")
  :learn (:concept "Bounded camera—the constraint that keeps the screen within the level." :prerequisites ("world/camera" "world/camera-snap!") :progression "world/camera-follow! (to combine follow + bounds for smooth gameplay)"))

(verb
  :name "world/camera-follow!"
  :library "world"
  :kind "mut"
  :signature "(world/camera-follow! id [lerp] [dzw] [dzh]) -> void"
  :summary "Smoothly ease the camera toward an entity's position, with optional deadzone and lerp tuning."
  :explanation "Games feel smooth when the camera follows the player with a slight delay, not snapping frame-to-frame. `world/camera-follow!` tells the world to ease the camera center toward a target entity (by id), with optional parameters: lerp (easing strength, default ~0.1, higher = faster), dzw and dzh (deadzone width and height, keeping target within a central box before camera moves). This is the standard \"follow camera\" for platformers and action games. Call it once per level or when the follow target changes. The camera continues to follow until explicitly stopped (`world/camera-snap!` or another follow call)."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(world/camera-follow! player-id)" :note "Start following the player with default easing (smooth, not too fast).")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(world/camera-follow! boss-id 0.05 100 100)" :note "Follow the boss with slower easing (0.05) and a 100×100 deadzone; camera is lethargic, good for boss arenas.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (on-scene-start ctx)\n  (world/camera-snap! (level-start-x) (level-start-y))\n  (world/camera-bounds! (room-x) (room-y) (room-w) (room-h))\n  (world/camera-follow! player-id 0.1 80 60)\n  (next 'playing ctx))" :note "Level init: snap camera to start, set bounds, enable follow with custom deadzone. Standard setup pattern.")
  )
  :caveats ("Lerp factor (0–1) controls easing speed; 0 = no follow (frozen camera), 1 = instant snap. Typical values 0.05–0.2." "Deadzone (dzw, dzh) is half-width and half-height, centered on the current camera; e.g., dzw=50 means camera doesn't move unless target is 50+ units left/right of center." "If the entity id dies or despawns while being followed, the camera follows a ghost position (the entity's last known loc) until a new follow target is set." "Follow competes with bounds: if bounds are tight and follow target is near edge, bounds win (camera clamped).")
  :drawbacks ("Cannot follow multiple entities at once; choose one target." "Lerp is linear; no easing curve support (ease-out, ease-in, etc.)." "Deadzone is axis-aligned; cannot define rotated or shaped deadzones." "No way to query the current follow target; if you lose track of the entity id, you cannot stop follow gracefully.")
  :usecases ("Platformer: follow the player with a small deadzone for snappy control feel." "Top-down action game: smooth follow with larger deadzone to reduce camera jitter." "Boss fight: lerp to a midpoint between player and boss for dynamic framing." "Cutscene transition: follow an NPC instead of player while dialogue plays.")
  :related ("world/camera" "world/camera-snap!" "world/camera-bounds!" "world/camera-shake!" "entity/pos")
  :learn (:concept "Smooth following with easing and deadzones—the feel of responsive but not jittery camera control." :prerequisites ("world/camera" "world/camera-bounds!" "entity/pos") :progression "world/camera-shake! (to add impact/feedback on top of smooth follow); cine/follow (for more complex multi-target cinematics)"))

(verb
  :name "world/camera-shake!"
  :library "world"
  :kind "mut"
  :signature "(world/camera-shake! amp [decay]) -> null"
  :summary "Trigger a decaying camera shake with initial amplitude and optional decay rate."
  :explanation "Applies a time-decaying oscillation to the camera position, useful for impact feedback or earthquake effects. The shake fades exponentially over frames; without a decay argument, a sensible default is used. The actual camera center (readable via world/camera) includes any active shake; they compose cleanly."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(world/camera-shake! 8)" :note "A sudden shake with amplitude 8, using the default decay rate.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define (on-collision id1 id2)\n  (world/camera-shake! 5 0.85))\n(world/each (lambda (id) (display (entity/kind id))))" :note "Trigger a short shake on any collision event, then iterate all entities.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (impact-scale dmg)\n  (world/camera-shake! (+ 2 (* dmg 0.5)) 0.8))\n(define (on-frame ctx)\n  (world/each (lambda (id)\n    (when (entity/alive? id)\n      (let ((hp (entity/get id 'hp)))\n        (when (< hp 10) (impact-scale (- 100 hp)))))))\n  (next 'on-frame ctx))" :note "Scale shake intensity by damage dealt, creating dynamic feedback.")
  )
  :caveats ("Shake is purely visual; it does not affect entity physics or collision detection." "Multiple calls accumulate: calling again before decay completes will override the previous shake." "Decay value near 1.0 produces very long shakes; near 0.0 shakes are nearly instant.")
  :drawbacks ("Cannot be queried once applied—no way to read back the current shake state." "For very precise timing, couple with world/frame to manually control onset and duration.")
  :usecases ("Impact feedback when a projectile hits a surface or entity." "Earthquake or tremor effects in environmental sequences." "Punctuation for dramatic moments (explosions, boss defeats).")
  :related ("world/camera" "world/camera-snap!" "world/frame" "entity/pos")
  :learn (:concept "Temporal decay: how to apply a decaying force or parameter over time." :prerequisites ("world/frame" "entity/pos") :progression "Move to world/camera-snap! for instant repositioning, or world/attract!/world/repel! for physics-driven motion."))

(verb
  :name "world/camera-snap!"
  :library "world"
  :kind "mut"
  :signature "(world/camera-snap! x y) -> null"
  :summary "Instantly jump the camera center to a coordinate pair."
  :explanation "Teleports the camera's base center to (x, y) in one frame, ignoring any easing or interpolation. Useful for cutting between scenes, following a teleporting entity, or enforcing a hard boundary. Any active shake from world/camera-shake! is preserved and continues to modulate around the new center."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(world/camera-snap! 100 50)" :note "Jump the camera to (100, 50) without interpolation.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define (teleport-scene id target-x target-y)\n  (world/camera-snap! target-x target-y)\n  (entity/set-pos! id target-x target-y))" :note "Snap both camera and entity to the same location when teleporting.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (follow-path-checkpoint path-list index)\n  (when (< index (length path-list))\n    (let ((checkpoint (list-ref path-list index)))\n      (world/camera-snap! (car checkpoint) (cadr checkpoint))\n      (next 'follow-path-checkpoint (ctx-set 'index (+ index 1) ctx)))))" :note "Snap camera to waypoints along a path; useful for guided tours or cutscenes.")
  )
  :caveats ("Snap is absolute and immediate; it ignores all tweens or camera-follow settings in that frame." "If world/camera-follow! is active, the snap will be overridden on the next frame." "Rapid snapping (every frame) can be disorienting; prefer smooth follow when possible.")
  :drawbacks ("No built-in easing or transition—for smooth pans, use motion/* verbs or world/camera-pan instead." "Does not validate x, y bounds; snapping far outside the world may place the camera in empty space.")
  :usecases ("Scene transitions or cut-scenes where the camera must jump to a new location." "Teleport/cutaway effects in story sequences." "Enforcing a hard boundary or reset after an entity reaches a goal.")
  :related ("world/camera" "world/camera-shake!" "world/camera-pan-to" "entity/set-pos!")
  :learn (:concept "Immediate mutation: how to set state without interpolation or decay." :prerequisites ("world/camera" "entity/pos") :progression "Pair with world/camera-pan-to for smooth transitions, or use motion/move-to for entity-driven camera follow."))

(verb
  :name "world/collisions"
  :library "world"
  :kind "rd"
  :signature "(world/collisions) -> [[id1 id2] ...]"
  :summary "Return a list of [a, b] entity id pairs that collided in the last step."
  :explanation "After world/step completes, this reads the collision buffer and returns all pairwise overlaps detected. Each pair is a fresh list [id-a id-b]; the order within the pair is stable but unspecified across calls. Use this to dispatch collision-handling logic: damage, sounds, particles, etc. The buffer is cleared at the start of each step, so collisions only live for one frame."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(define collisions (world/collisions))\n(display (length collisions))" :note "Get the collision list and count how many pairs collided this frame.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define (handle-collisions)\n  (for-each (lambda (pair)\n    (let ((a (car pair))\n          (b (cadr pair)))\n      (when (eq? (entity/kind a) 'bullet)\n        (entity/set! b 'hp (- (entity/get b 'hp) 10)))))\n    (world/collisions)))" :note "Iterate collisions and damage entities tagged as bullets.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (resolve-collisions ctx)\n  (for-each (lambda (pair)\n    (let ((id-a (car pair))\n          (id-b (cadr pair)))\n      (cond ((and (eq? (entity/kind id-a) 'player)\n                  (eq? (entity/kind id-b) 'coin))\n             (entity/despawn! id-b)\n             (act 'sound 'coin-collect))\n            ((and (eq? (entity/kind id-a) 'enemy)\n                  (eq? (entity/kind id-b) 'enemy))\n             (world/impulse! id-a -1 0)\n             (world/impulse! id-b 1 0)))))\n    (world/collisions))\n  (next 'resolve-collisions ctx))" :note "Multi-branch collision dispatcher in a state function; rebound enemies, collect coins.")
  )
  :caveats ("The collision list is only valid during the current frame; do not store a reference across steps." "A collision pair [a b] will appear only once per frame, even if the entities overlap continuously." "If an entity despawns mid-frame (e.g., in response to a collision), subsequent pairs involving that id may still appear.")
  :drawbacks ("No collision metadata (impact point, normal, relative velocity)—only the id pair." "Filtering by kind must be done in user code; no built-in layer/mask support at this stage (though collision/define-layers! can organize layers)." "Allocating a fresh list every call is slightly costly; for high-collision scenarios, cache the result.")
  :usecases ("Implementing hit detection for weapons, projectiles, or hazards." "Coin / item collection logic." "Triggering sound effects or particle bursts on impact." "Implementing enemy knock-back or stun on collision.")
  :related ("world/step" "world/solve!" "entity/overlaps?" "entity/collisions" "collision/define-layers!")
  :learn (:concept "Polling state from the world engine each frame to drive user logic." :prerequisites ("world/step" "entity/alive?" "entity/kind") :progression "Move to entity/overlaps? for per-entity queries, or collision/define-layers! to organize collision groups."))

(verb
  :name "world/count"
  :library "world"
  :kind "rd"
  :signature "(world/count [kind]) -> integer"
  :summary "Return the number of alive entities, optionally filtered by kind."
  :explanation "A fast read of the entity count. If no kind is given, returns the total count of all live entities. If a kind symbol is provided, counts only entities of that kind. Despawned entities are not counted. Useful for game state checks (win condition, spawn caps, difficulty scaling)."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(world/count)" :note "Get the total entity count.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(let ((enemy-count (world/count 'enemy)))\n  (if (= enemy-count 0)\n    (display \"Wave cleared!\")\n    (display (string-append \"Enemies left: \" (number->string enemy-count)))))" :note "Check if all enemies are defeated and print status.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (check-spawn-cap ctx)\n  (let ((total (world/count))\n        (cap 64))\n    (cond ((>= total cap)\n           (next 'wait-for-despawn ctx))\n          (else\n           (world/spawn 'minion (random 640) (random 360))\n           (next 'check-spawn-cap ctx)))))" :note "Spawn minions up to a cap; wait when limit is reached.")
  )
  :caveats ("The count is read at the start of world/step; despawns in the current frame are reflected only after the step." "Passing a non-existent kind does not error; it simply returns 0.")
  :drawbacks ("No per-team or per-layer filtering; you must manually iterate (world/find kind) and filter further if needed." "Counted entities include all alive entities; there is no separate count for entities in a given state or with a tag.")
  :usecases ("Win/lose condition checks (all enemies dead, all coins collected)." "Difficulty scaling based on entity count." "Spawn caps to prevent lag or game-breaking abundance." "UI display of remaining enemies or collectibles.")
  :related ("world/find" "world/each" "entity/kind" "world/spawn" "entity/despawn!")
  :learn (:concept "Efficient aggregation: reading a pre-computed summary of world state." :prerequisites ("world/step" "entity/kind") :progression "Use world/find to get the actual list of ids for further filtering, or world/each to iterate and apply custom logic."))

(verb
  :name "world/each"
  :library "world"
  :kind "rd"
  :signature "(world/each fn) -> integer"
  :summary "Call fn with each alive entity id in birth order; return the count."
  :explanation "Iteration primitive: loops over all entities currently alive and invokes fn once per id. The entities are visited in the order they were spawned (bornSeq). Useful for polling entity state, running per-entity logic, or collecting data. Returns the count of iterations, which equals the number of alive entities."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(world/each (lambda (id)\n  (display (entity/kind id))))" :note "Print the kind of every entity.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define (count-by-kind)\n  (let ((counts '()))\n    (world/each (lambda (id)\n      (let ((k (entity/kind id)))\n        (display (string-append k \" at \" (number->string (entity/x id)) \" \\n\")))))\n    counts))" :note "Emit entity kind and position for each entity.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (tick-all-entities ctx)\n  (world/each (lambda (id)\n    (when (entity/alive? id)\n      (let ((state (entity/state id)))\n        (cond ((eq? state 'idle)\n               (entity/set! id 'idle-time (+ (entity/get id 'idle-time) 1)))\n              ((eq? state 'moving)\n               (entity/move! id (entity/vel id))))))))\n  (next 'tick-all-entities ctx))" :note "Run per-entity FSM logic in a state function; update timers and positions.")
  )
  :caveats ("The iteration order is stable (birth order) but should not be relied upon for determinism if entities are spawned dynamically." "If you despawn an entity during iteration, the behavior is unspecified—use entity/alive? to guard any mutations." "The function is called for every id, including those that may have become invalid since the start of iteration; check entity/alive? if you want to skip dead entities.")
  :drawbacks ("No built-in filtering by kind or tag; use world/find for that." "Cannot break early or short-circuit the loop; if you need conditional stopping, use world/find instead." "Allocates a closure for every call; in tight loops, consider world/find and a hand-rolled for-each.")
  :usecases ("Broadcasting a message or state change to all entities." "Collecting statistics (count, min/max position, total damage)." "Running per-entity FSMs or tick logic each frame." "Rendering or visual polling of all entities.")
  :related ("world/find" "world/count" "entity/alive?" "entity/state" "entity/set!")
  :learn (:concept "Iteration and side effects: how to visit every entity and apply a procedure." :prerequisites ("world/step" "lambda" "entity/kind") :progression "Use world/find to filter by kind, or fold-left / fold-right (from core) to accumulate values across entities."))

(verb
  :name "world/find"
  :library "world"
  :kind "rd"
  :signature "(world/find [kind]) -> [id ...]"
  :summary "Return a list of all alive entity ids, optionally filtered by kind."
  :explanation "Query primitive: returns a fresh list of entity ids. Without an argument, all alive entities are included. With a kind symbol, only entities of that kind are returned. The ids are in birth order (the same order world/each visits them). Use this to collect entities for filtering, sorting, or count-based logic."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(let ((all-ids (world/find)))\n  (display (length all-ids)))" :note "Get the list of all entity ids and count them.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(let ((enemies (world/find 'enemy)))\n  (for-each (lambda (id)\n    (world/impulse! id 0 -5))\n    enemies))" :note "Find all enemies and apply an upward impulse to each.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (find-nearest-enemy-to id)\n  (let* ((pos (entity/pos id))\n         (px (car pos))\n         (py (cadr pos))\n         (enemies (world/find 'enemy)))\n    (if (null? enemies)\n      'nan\n      (fold-left (lambda (nearest candidate)\n        (let ((d-nearest (entity/distance nearest id))\n              (d-candidate (entity/distance candidate id)))\n          (if (< d-candidate d-nearest) candidate nearest)))\n        (car enemies)\n        (cdr enemies)))))" :note "Find all enemies and fold to get the one closest to a given entity.")
  )
  :caveats ("The returned list is a snapshot; changes to the world after the call (spawns, despawns) are not reflected." "If kind is provided but no entities match, an empty list is returned (no error)." "The list is in birth order; if you need a different order, sort it yourself.")
  :drawbacks ("Allocates a new list; for very large entity counts, this can be costly if called every frame." "No lazy evaluation; all matching ids are collected up front." "No filtering by tag, state, or other properties; filter the returned list in user code if needed.")
  :usecases ("Finding a subset of entities to apply an action to (e.g., all coins, all enemies)." "Nearest-neighbor or distance-based queries (combined with fold or map)." "Checking existence conditions (e.g., 'if any coin remains')." "Bulk state or physics updates (e.g., slow all enemies).")
  :related ("world/each" "world/count" "world/nearest" "entity/kind" "fold-left")
  :learn (:concept "Querying and filtering: how to collect entities matching a criterion." :prerequisites ("world/step" "entity/kind" "list" "length") :progression "Combine with fold-left / fold-right to aggregate data, or use world/nearest for spatial queries."))

(verb
  :name "world/floor!"
  :library "world"
  :kind "mut"
  :signature "(world/floor! y [bounce]) -> null"
  :summary "Set a horizontal ground plane at y; bounce is the restitution coefficient. No argument removes it."
  :explanation "Creates a rigid floor (or removes it) that all physics bodies collide with. Bodies falling below y will bounce back (or stick, if bounce is 0). The bounce parameter controls restitution: 0 means no bounce (perfectly inelastic), 1 means full conservation of velocity, >1 means gain (unphysical but sometimes fun). Calling with no arguments removes the floor entirely."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(world/floor! 360 0.6)" :note "Set a bouncy ground at y=360 with 60% restitution.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define (setup-level)\n  (world/reset!)\n  (world/gravity! 0 0.3)\n  (world/floor! 360 0.5)\n  (world/spawn 'player 320 180))" :note "Initialize a level with gravity, a floor, and a player entity.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (on-frame ctx)\n  (let ((frame (world/frame)))\n    (cond ((= (modulo frame 120) 0)\n           ;; Every 2 seconds, toggle the floor\n           (if (> frame 0) (world/floor!) (world/floor! 360 0.8)))\n          (else\n           (world/each (lambda (id)\n             (when (< (entity/y id) -100)\n               (entity/set-pos! id 320 180)))))))  ;; Respawn fallen entities\n  (next 'on-frame ctx))" :note "Toggle the floor on and off; respawn entities that fall below the screen.")
  )
  :caveats ("The floor is infinite (extends across all x); it cannot be positioned horizontally." "Entities do not rest on the floor without friction; they will bounce indefinitely unless world/wind! or drag is applied." "Calling with only y (no bounce) uses a default bounce value; verify the default in your interpreter.")
  :drawbacks ("Only one floor is supported; for multiple platforms, use solid entities or a grid collision system." "No friction or stopping condition built-in; entities bounce until damped by external forces." "Bounce > 1 can cause numerical instability over many frames; keep values reasonable (< 1 recommended).")
  :usecases ("Creating a ground plane in platformers or physics puzzles." "Bouncy surfaces (trampoline-like behavior with high bounce)." "Sticky ground (low bounce, combined with drag or friction)." "Temporary platforms (toggle the floor on and off for puzzle mechanics).")
  :related ("world/gravity!" "world/wind!" "entity/gravity-scale!" "entity/solid!" "world/step")
  :learn (:concept "Static collision geometry: a simple, efficient way to define an immobile boundary." :prerequisites ("world/gravity!" "world/step" "entity/pos") :progression "Use entity/solid! and entity/shape! for more complex collision shapes, or world/solve! for constraint-based physics."))

(verb
  :name "world/frame"
  :library "world"
  :kind "rd"
  :signature "(world/frame) -> integer"
  :summary "Return the current world frame counter (incremented each step)."
  :explanation "A monotonically increasing integer that counts the number of world/step calls since start (or world/reset!). Useful for scheduling, timing events, or synchronizing animations. Frame 0 is the initial state before any step."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(let ((f (world/frame)))\n  (display f))" :note "Print the current frame number.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define (spawn-every-30-frames ctx)\n  (when (= (modulo (world/frame) 30) 0)\n    (world/spawn 'enemy (random 640) 0))\n  (next 'spawn-every-30-frames ctx))" :note "Spawn an enemy every 30 frames (once per second at 30fps).")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (oscillating-y id amplitude frequency)\n  (let* ((f (world/frame))\n         (angle (* (/ f frequency) 6.28))  ;; 2π\n         (y-offset (* amplitude (sin angle))))\n    (entity/set-pos! id (entity/x id) y-offset)))\n\n(define (animate-entity ctx)\n  (oscillating-y (car (world/find 'player)) 50 60)  ;; Oscillate player up/down\n  (next 'animate-entity ctx))" :note "Use frame count to drive a sine wave animation.")
  )
  :caveats ("Frame is a counter from the start; do not assume a global wall-clock time (frame rate may vary)." "After world/reset!, the frame counter is reset to 0." "Modulo arithmetic (frame % n == 0) is the standard pattern for periodic events; be careful of off-by-one.")
  :drawbacks ("No fractional frames; for smooth sub-frame timing, combine with entity velocity or motion tweens." "The frame counter can overflow if the game runs long enough (after 2^31 frames); in practice, this is rare.")
  :usecases ("Scheduling: spawn, state changes, or animations at specific frames." "Periodic effects: every N frames, do something (flicker, pulse, spawn wave)." "Replay and determinism: using the frame count as a seed or checkpoint." "Debugging: log the frame when an event occurs.")
  :related ("world/step" "world/reset!" "world/after" "tick/mod-n" "time/every-ms")
  :learn (:concept "Discrete time: using a frame counter for scheduling and synchronization." :prerequisites ("world/step" "modulo") :progression "Use world/after for frame-delayed events, or tick/pattern for more complex rhythmic patterns."))

(verb
  :name "world/gravity!"
  :library "world"
  :kind "mut"
  :signature "(world/gravity! gx gy) -> void"
  :summary "Set the global gravitational acceleration vector for all physics bodies."
  :explanation "Every frame, gravity applies a constant acceleration to all entities that have not disabled it (via entity/gravity-scale! 0). The vector (gx gy) is in world units per frame squared. Positive gy pulls downward; negative gy pulls upward. This is the primary lever for tuning how 'heavy' or 'floaty' the world feels. Call it once at setup or whenever you need to shift gravity mid-simulation (e.g., antigravity powerup, moon level)."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(world/gravity! 0 0.5)" :note "Earth-like gravity: no horizontal drift, downward pull of 0.5 units/frame².")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define (apply-antigravity? active)\n  (if active\n    (world/gravity! 0 -0.3)\n    (world/gravity! 0 0.5)))\n(apply-antigravity? #t)" :note "Toggle gravity direction based on powerup state; negative gy flips the pull.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (setup-level-physics level-name)\n  (cond\n    ((equal? level-name 'moon) (world/gravity! 0 0.1))\n    ((equal? level-name 'space) (world/gravity! 0 0))\n    (else (world/gravity! 0 0.5))))\n(setup-level-physics 'moon)" :note "Level-specific gravity tuning; zero gravity is valid and used for free-floating zones.")
  )
  :caveats ("Gravity applies to ALL entities unless individually disabled (entity/gravity-scale! id 0)." "Does not take effect on entities spawned with no physics body." "Setting to (0 0) disables gravity but does not stop momentum; entities keep their velocity." "Changes apply on the NEXT world/step, not immediately within the same frame.")
  :drawbacks ("Global only; you cannot have per-entity custom gravity directions without using world/attract! or world/repel! instead." "No automatic 'bounce' on gravity reversal; entities in flight will invert smoothly but may feel unresponsive if changed mid-jump.")
  :usecases ("Initial level setup: define the physics feel before spawning entities." "Powerup activation: antigravity boots, low-g zones, null-g chambers." "Environmental transitions: moving from Earth to Moon or space." "Arcade tuning: adjust gravity to make platforming feel snappy or floaty.")
  :related ("entity/gravity-scale!" "world/impulse!" "world/attract!" "world/repel!" "world/wind!")
  :learn (:concept "Global acceleration applied uniformly to all physics bodies; the baseline force model." :prerequisites ("entity/alive?" "world/step") :progression "After setting gravity, learn entity/gravity-scale! to fine-tune per-body weight, then world/impulse! to apply instant kicks."))

(verb
  :name "world/hash"
  :library "world"
  :kind "rd"
  :signature "(world/hash) -> integer"
  :summary "Return a 32-bit deterministic digest of the current world's numeric state."
  :explanation "This hash is computed from the positions, velocities, and other numeric properties of all live entities. If you run the same sequence of actions and get the same hash at a given frame, the worlds are byte-for-byte identical. Used to verify replay fidelity: if a recorded game replays with the same hash at each frame, the replay is true. The hash is unaffected by entity names, tags, or scratch-data keys; only numeric simulation state matters."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(define h1 (world/hash))\n(world/step)\n(define h2 (world/hash))\n(not (= h1 h2))" :note "After a step, the hash changes (unless world is empty or paused). Two hashes are never equal mid-simulation.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define (frame-0-hash (world/snapshot))\n  (let ((snap (world/snapshot)))\n    (world/hash)))\n(define h-before (frame-0-hash))\n(world/step)\n(define h-after (world/hash))\n(list h-before h-after)" :note "Capture hash before and after a step; later, restore the snapshot and verify it hashes to the same value.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (verify-replay frames)\n  (let ((record '()))\n    (for-each\n      (lambda (frame)\n        (world/step)\n        (set! record (cons (world/hash) record)))\n      frames)\n    (reverse record)))\n(define hashes (verify-replay (list 1 2 3 4 5)))\nhashes" :note "Build a hash sequence during live play; later, load a replay, step through it, and compare hashes frame-by-frame to verify no divergence.")
  )
  :caveats ("Hash is deterministic only if physics is fully deterministic; floating-point rounding can cause minor divergence on different CPU architectures or compile flags." "The hash does NOT include render state, camera position, or timing; only the physics simulation." "Does not hash input history or RNG state; you must track those separately if you want full replay verification." "Hash changes on EVERY frame, even if no entity moves (integration always happens).")
  :drawbacks ("Hashing every frame is a cost; if you only check hashes at sparse frames, you may miss divergence points." "A hash collision (two different states producing the same hash) is astronomically unlikely but theoretically possible; use multiple hashes or full snapshots for critical verification." "Does not help debug *why* a hash differs, only that it does; you need entity/pos queries to find the diverged entity.")
  :usecases ("Replay assertion: confirm that a recorded game replays identically." "Regression testing: detect if a code change altered the physics engine behavior." "Determinism validation: ensure a multiplayer game stays in sync across clients." "Frame-by-frame debugging: narrow down the exact frame where two simulations diverge.")
  :related ("world/snapshot" "world/restore!" "world/step" "world/reset!")
  :learn (:concept "A lightweight signature of numeric state for drift detection and replay verification." :prerequisites ("world/step" "entity/pos") :progression "Learn world/hash for verification, then world/snapshot + world/restore! to save and load full state."))

(verb
  :name "world/impulse!"
  :library "world"
  :kind "mut"
  :signature "(world/impulse! id dvx dvy) -> void"
  :summary "Apply an instant velocity change to an entity; the primitive one-frame kick."
  :explanation "Instead of accelerating an entity over time, an impulse adds directly to its current velocity. If an entity is at velocity [vx vy] and you call (world/impulse! id 3 0), it becomes [vx+3 vy]. Impulses are the fastest way to change an entity's motion: a jump, a bullet hit, a knockback. They are also the foundation for constraint solving (world/link!, world/solve!) which uses impulses internally to satisfy distance constraints."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(world/impulse! player-id 0 -15)" :note "Jump: add upward velocity (negative gy) to the player entity without changing x-velocity.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define (knockback-on-hit victim attacker-x dmg)\n  (let ((dx (- (entity/x victim) attacker-x)))\n    (world/impulse! victim (* (if (< dx 0) -1 1) 8) 5)))\n(knockback-on-hit enemy player-x 10)" :note "Knockback: impulse away from attacker, mixing horizontal and vertical kick. Direction is based on relative position.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (solve-constraint-once a b rest)\n  (let* ((pa (entity/pos a))\n         (pb (entity/pos b))\n         (gap (- (entity/distance a b) rest))\n         (dir-x (/ (- (car pb) (car pa)) (+ (entity/distance a b) 0.001)))\n         (dir-y (/ (- (cadr pb) (cadr pa)) (+ (entity/distance a b) 0.001))))\n    (world/impulse! a (* gap 0.5 dir-x) (* gap 0.5 dir-y))\n    (world/impulse! b (* gap -0.5 dir-x) (* gap -0.5 dir-y))))\n(solve-constraint-once e1 e2 20)" :note "Manual constraint iteration: compute gap, compute direction, apply equal-and-opposite impulses to both bodies. (Real constraint solving uses world/link! + world/solve!.)")
  )
  :caveats ("Impulse takes effect on the NEXT world/step, not immediately; velocity reads in the current frame will not reflect it." "Multiple impulses in the same frame accumulate; there is no 'only the largest' logic." "Impulse does NOT respect max-speed; you can use it to exceed entity/max-speed! if needed (useful for knockback)." "Impulse bypasses gravity; it is a pure velocity delta, not subject to gravity scale.")
  :drawbacks ("Easy to create unrealistic motion if impulses are too large; use world/attract! or world/repel! for softer, physics-based forces." "Does not integrate over time; if you want a gradual push, use world/wind! or apply impulses over multiple frames." "Repeated frame-by-frame impulses are more expensive than a single force call; batch them if possible.")
  :usecases ("Jump input: instant upward velocity on button press." "Knockback: reaction to collision, explosion, or attack hit." "Sliding/dashing: horizontal kick moves." "Constraint solving: internal use by world/link! + world/solve!." "Arcade physics: arcade games often use impulses for snappy, responsive feel.")
  :related ("world/gravity!" "world/attract!" "world/repel!" "world/wind!" "world/link!" "world/solve!" "entity/max-speed!")
  :learn (:concept "Instant velocity change; the atomic primitive for impact and constraint forces." :prerequisites ("entity/vel" "world/step") :progression "Master impulse for basic pushes, then learn world/link! + world/solve! to see how impulses build distance constraints."))

(verb
  :name "world/link!"
  :library "world"
  :kind "mut"
  :signature "(world/link! a b [rest] [stiff]) -> void"
  :summary "Create or update a distance constraint between two entities; a rigid or elastic rope."
  :explanation "A link forces the distance between entity a and entity b to stay near a target length (rest). If rest is omitted, it defaults to the current gap between them at the moment of the call. Stiffness stiff ranges from 0 (no constraint, entities ignore each other) to 1 (rigid rod). Higher stiffness requires more constraint-solving iterations (world/solve!) to stabilize. Links are the basis for ropes, chains, ragdoll joints, and cloth."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(world/link! e1 e2)" :note "Link e1 and e2 at their current distance; they will try to stay this far apart (like a rope with no slack).")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define (rope-setup anchor-id ball-id)\n  (world/link! anchor-id ball-id 30 0.9))\n(rope-setup fixed-point ball-entity)\n(world/solve! 3)" :note "Create a fairly stiff rope (stiff=0.9) of length 30 between an anchor and a ball; solve 3 times per step to keep it stable.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (build-ragdoll root segments)\n  (let loop ((prev root) (rest-segs segments))\n    (if (null? rest-segs)\n      #t\n      (let ((curr (car rest-segs)))\n        (world/link! prev curr 15 0.8)\n        (loop curr (cdr rest-segs))))))\n(build-ragdoll head (list neck torso hip))\n(world/solve! 5)" :note "Build a chain of linked bodies (neck→torso→hip) by recursively linking adjacent segments; solve with more iterations for stability.")
  )
  :caveats ("Links are not automatically removed when an entity dies; use world/find or manual tracking if you need to clean up orphaned links." "Stiffness of exactly 1.0 can be unstable if iterations are too low; values 0.8–0.95 are usually safer." "Links create no collision response by themselves; if entities overlap, they will pass through unless you handle collision separately." "Changing rest length mid-simulation: use world/link-rest! rather than re-calling world/link!.")
  :drawbacks ("Constraint solving is expensive; each iteration costs time. Real-time limits may force you to use fewer iterations." "Stiff links with low iteration counts feel laggy and bouncy; tuning is required per use case." "Broken links: once created, a link persists until one entity dies. No built-in 'break on impact' behavior." "Cycles in link graphs (e.g., A→B→C→A) can cause instability if you over-constrain; keep graphs acyclic or use low stiffness.")
  :usecases ("Ropes and cables: bridge, swing, hanging decoration." "Ragdoll physics: limbs held together by joint constraints." "Cloth simulation: grid of particles linked to neighbors." "Elastic bands: loose links with low stiffness." "Puzzle mechanics: move one piece and others follow (like tangled chain puzzles).")
  :related ("world/link-rest!" "world/solve!" "world/impulse!" "entity/alive?")
  :learn (:concept "Distance constraint: two bodies pulled toward a target separation by repeated impulses." :prerequisites ("entity/pos" "entity/distance" "world/step") :progression "Create simple links, then use world/solve! to stabilize them, then world/link-rest! to animate rest length (e.g., rope shortening)."))

(verb
  :name "world/link-rest!"
  :library "world"
  :kind "mut"
  :signature "(world/link-rest! a b rest) -> integer"
  :summary "Retarget the rest (resting) length of the link between two entities; returns the count of links changed."
  :explanation "Once a link exists between a and b, you can change its target length without destroying and recreating the link. This is the way to animate a rope shortening (a winch or pulleys), a spring extending and compressing, or a chain being reeled in. The return value is the count of how many links were updated; normally 0 or 1 (0 if no link between a and b exists, 1 if it does)."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(world/link-rest! winch-id payload-id 20)" :note "Shorten the rope between winch and payload to 20 units; payload will be drawn upward over the next few solve iterations.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define (animate-rope-pull id from to steps)\n  (let loop ((step 0))\n    (if (< step steps)\n      (begin\n        (world/link-rest! id target (+ from (* (/ (- to from) steps) step)))\n        (world/step)\n        (loop (+ step 1))))))\n(animate-rope-pull winch payload 50 10 20)" :note "Linearly interpolate rest length over 20 frames; payload rises smoothly as the rope shortens.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (spring-animation anchor mass rest-min rest-max period)\n  (let loop ((t 0))\n    (let* ((phase (/ (* 2 3.14159 t) period))\n           (rest (+ rest-min (* 0.5 (+ (- rest-max rest-min) (* (- rest-max rest-min) (sin phase)))))))\n      (world/link-rest! anchor mass rest)\n      (world/solve! 2)\n      (world/step)\n      (if (< t 100) (loop (+ t 1))))))\n(spring-animation fixed-point ball 15 25 20)" :note "Spring oscillation: vary rest length sinusoidally; the constraint chases the moving target, creating oscillatory motion.")
  )
  :caveats ("Does not check if the link exists; silently returns 0 if a and b were never linked." "Change takes effect on the NEXT world/solve! call, not immediately." "Rapid changes to rest (e.g., every frame by large amounts) can cause jittering if solve iterations are low." "Negative rest length is allowed but meaningless; entities will fight to stay inside each other (use 0 if you want them to collide at a point).")
  :drawbacks ("No 'smooth transition' built in; if you jump rest from 50 to 10, the constraint will be violated until it solves. Use interpolation for smooth motion." "Not useful if the link is already stiff (stiff≈1); lowering rest length on a nearly-rigid link can create bounce or oscillation." "No return value feedback on whether the change succeeded; rely on the return count to detect missing links if you need to react.")
  :usecases ("Winching: pull a payload upward by reducing rope length." "Spring oscillation: animate a springy object by varying rest length." "Extensible constraints: ropes that can shorten and lengthen dynamically." "Puzzle mechanics: shorten a link to trigger a mechanism." "Tether animation: link that shortens or lengthens on demand.")
  :related ("world/link!" "world/solve!" "world/impulse!")
  :learn (:concept "Mutable constraint target; animate link length to create pulleys, springs, and dynamic tethers." :prerequisites ("world/link!" "world/solve!") :progression "After linking, use world/link-rest! to animate the target; use high solve iterations (≥3) for smooth motion."))

(verb
  :name "world/nearest"
  :library "world"
  :kind "rd"
  :signature "(world/nearest id [kind]) -> id | 'nan"
  :summary "Return the id of the nearest OTHER entity to the given entity; optionally filter by kind."
  :explanation "Useful for AI targeting, proximity checks, and spatial queries. If kind is given, only entities of that kind are considered. If no other entity exists (or no entity of the given kind exists), returns 'nan. The search includes all alive entities except id itself; distance is Euclidean and computed using entity/distance internally."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(define nearest-foe (world/nearest player-id 'enemy))\n(if (not (eq? nearest-foe 'nan))\n  (world/impulse! player-id 5 0))" :note "Find the nearest enemy; if one exists, kick the player toward it (simple pursuit setup).")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define (seek-target seeker-id search-kind max-range)\n  (let ((target (world/nearest seeker-id search-kind)))\n    (if (not (eq? target 'nan))\n      (let ((dist (entity/distance seeker-id target)))\n        (if (<= dist max-range)\n          target\n          'out-of-range))\n      'not-found)))\n(seek-target monster-id 'player 100)" :note "Find nearest entity of a kind AND check if it is within max-range; return the target or a reason code.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (pick-threat npc threat-kinds)\n  (let loop ((kinds threat-kinds) (best 'nan) (best-dist 999999))\n    (if (null? kinds)\n      best\n      (let* ((cand (world/nearest npc-id (car kinds)))\n             (dist (if (eq? cand 'nan) 999999 (entity/distance npc-id cand))))\n        (loop (cdr kinds)\n              (if (< dist best-dist) cand best)\n              (if (< dist best-dist) dist best-dist))))))\n(pick-threat guard-id '(player intruder))" :note "Find the nearest threat of multiple kinds (player or intruder); return whichever is closer. Useful for NPC threat prioritization.")
  )
  :caveats ("Returns 'nan, not null or #f; always check with (eq? result 'nan)." "Does not check visibility or line-of-sight; only straight-line distance matters." "Slightly expensive for large entity counts (O(n) per call); cache the result if you query multiple times per frame." "Returns the id itself if id is dead (entity/alive? returns #f), but that's rare because dead entities are soon garbage-collected.")
  :drawbacks ("No distance returned; you must call entity/distance again if you need the actual distance." "No tie-breaking for entities at exactly the same distance; one is chosen arbitrarily." "Kind filter is an exact symbol match; no wildcards or parent classes.")
  :usecases ("AI targeting: NPC picks nearest enemy to attack." "Proximity checks: trigger a script when player gets close to an object." "Social mechanics: NPC finds nearest friend or enemy." "Spatial queries: 'who is closest to me of type X?'.")
  :related ("world/find" "world/count" "entity/distance" "entity/kind" "group/find")
  :learn (:concept "Spatial query: O(n) search for the closest entity, optionally filtered by kind." :prerequisites ("entity/alive?" "entity/kind" "entity/distance") :progression "Use world/nearest for simple proximity; then learn world/find to get all entities of a kind (not just the nearest)."))

(verb
  :name "world/render"
  :library "world"
  :kind "null"
  :signature "(world/render [pitch]) -> void"
  :summary "Draw all entities to the canvas at their current world positions, scaled by pitch (default 1)."
  :explanation "Iterates through all alive entities in the world, looks up their shape (stored as __shape in entity data), and paints that shape to the dot-matrix surface. The pitch parameter scales the world-to-canvas conversion (pitch=2 draws each entity at half size). Each entity's draw uses its rotation (__spin), scale (__sx, __sy), and vertical offset (__dy). Flower shapes are painted using the internal flower painting routines; other shapes are skipped."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(world/render)" :note "Draw all entities at their world position with pitch=1 (one world unit = one canvas pixel).")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(world/render 2)" :note "Draw all entities at half scale (pitch=2); useful for zooming out to see a large world on a small screen.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (render-with-camera pitch cam-x cam-y)\n  (camera-pan-to cam-x cam-y)\n  (world/render pitch))\n(render-with-camera 1 100 100)" :note "Pan camera to (100, 100), then render world. (In practice, camera/render is built in; this shows the composition pattern.)")
  )
  :caveats ("Pitch must be positive; negative or zero pitch produces undefined behavior." "Only entities with a __shape in their data are drawn; any entity without a shape is invisible." "Does not handle transparency, depth sorting, or layer culling; all shapes are drawn in birth order." "Render happens *after* a step (or independently), so entities drawn are at their current frame position, not next frame.")
  :drawbacks ("Performance degrades with entity count; O(n) render cost per frame." "No built-in frustum culling; off-screen entities are still processed (use a view-limiting camera or manual culling if needed)." "Pitch is global; you cannot draw different regions at different scales in one call." "No return value; no way to count how many entities were actually drawn.")
  :usecases ("Main game loop: render the world each frame after stepping." "Zoom effect: vary pitch to zoom in and out." "Multi-scale rendering: render the world twice at different pitches to different canvases." "Replay playback: render each saved world state.")
  :related ("world/step" "entity/set!" "camera-pan-to" "surface-paint-dots" "world/snapshot")
  :learn (:concept "Draw all entities to canvas using their shape data; pitch scales the view." :prerequisites ("world/spawn" "entity/set!") :progression "Render a simple world, then use pitch to zoom, then use camera-* verbs to pan and follow."))

(verb
  :name "world/repel!"
  :library "world"
  :kind "mut"
  :signature "(world/repel! id cx cy strength) -> void"
  :summary "Push an entity away from a point (cx, cy) with a softened inverse-square force; like an explosion or repulsor field."
  :explanation "Applies a force to entity id in the direction away from the point (cx, cy), with magnitude that decreases with distance (inverse-square law, softened to avoid singularities). The force is accumulated in the world's acceleration buffer and applied during the next world/step. High strength values create a strong push; low values create a gentle force field. This is the complement to world/attract!: repel pushes, attract pulls."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(world/repel! enemy-id explosion-x explosion-y 100)" :note "Push enemy away from an explosion at (explosion-x, explosion-y) with strength 100.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define (push-back-on-hit victim attacker-pos strength)\n  (world/repel! victim (car attacker-pos) (cadr attacker-pos) strength))\n(push-back-on-hit player '(50 50) 50)" :note "Unpack attacker position from a pair and repel the player away from it.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (repulsor-field entities field-center field-strength)\n  (for-each\n    (lambda (id)\n      (world/repel! id (car field-center) (cadr field-center) field-strength))\n    entities))\n(repulsor-field (group/find 'projectile) '(200 150) 75)" :note "Apply repulsion to all projectiles in a group, pushing them away from a field center (like a shield).")
  )
  :caveats ("Force is added to acceleration, not velocity; it takes a frame to manifest as motion." "Very close to the point (cx, cy), the repulsion is capped (softened); there is no infinite force at distance 0." "Strength can be negative; negative repel is identical to attract. (Use world/attract! for clarity.)" "Applies EVERY frame while the entity and the point exist; to apply once, use world/impulse! instead.")
  :drawbacks ("Multiple repulsor fields (multiple calls) accumulate; you must manage total force to avoid runaway acceleration." "Inverse-square softening can feel artificial; if you want linear falloff, use world/impulse! scaled by distance manually." "Does not respect max-speed; repulsion can push an entity beyond its speed limit." "Expensive in tight loops; repelling 100 entities from 10 sources is 1000 force calcs per step.")
  :usecases ("Explosions: push nearby entities outward." "Repulsor shields: field that pushes enemies away." "Boss arenas: central repulsor forces enemies to the edges." "Crowd control: push multiple entities away from a point." "Environmental hazards: hot spots or radiation zones that push entities away.")
  :related ("world/attract!" "world/impulse!" "world/wind!" "world/gravity!" "entity/gravity-scale!")
  :learn (:concept "Softened inverse-square force away from a point; the basis for explosion and repulsor effects." :prerequisites ("world/step" "entity/pos") :progression "Use world/repel! for simple explosions, then combine with world/attract! to create balanced force fields or orbital mechanics."))

(verb
  :name "world/reset!"
  :library "world"
  :kind "mut"
  :signature "(world/reset!) → void"
  :summary "Clears all entities, timers, tweens, and input state from the world."
  :explanation "world/reset! wipes the entire simulation clean: every spawned entity is despawned, all pending frame-timers are cancelled, all active tweens are halted, and input history is flushed. Use this to transition between scenes, restart a level, or reset after a game-over. The world frame counter does NOT reset (it accumulates for replay integrity)."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(world/reset!)\n(world/spawn 'player 100 100)" :note "Reset clears everything, then spawn a fresh player.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define (restart-level)\n  (world/reset!)\n  (world/gravity! 0 9.8)\n  (world/spawn 'player 200 50)\n  (world/spawn 'goal 400 50))\n(restart-level)" :note "Helper to reset and rebuild a level from scratch.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (game-over-handler ctx)\n  (let ((score (ctx-result ctx)))\n    (world/reset!)\n    (display (list \"Final score:\" score))\n    (next 'show-menu ctx)))\n(game-over-handler ctx)" :note "Reset within a state transition; clean slate before moving to menu.")
  )
  :caveats ("Invalidates ALL entity ids in flight; holding an id after reset() and querying it will yield 'entity-not-found." "Does not reset the world frame counter; frame numbering continues for determinism." "Input buffer is flushed; no lingering keypresses after reset." "Synchronous; blocks until all cleanup is done (usually fast).")
  :drawbacks ("Nuclear option; there is no selective entity despawn. Use entity/despawn! if you need fine-grained cleanup." "Camera state is NOT reset; call camera-home or camera-set! to reposition." "Custom per-entity data stored via entity/set! is lost; pre-save with world/snapshot if needed.")
  :usecases ("Level restart after player death." "Transition between game scenes or menus." "Testing or demo reset in interactive development." "Clearing a sandbox world for a fresh simulation run.")
  :related ("world/snapshot" "world/restore!" "entity/despawn!" "world/step")
  :learn (:concept "Total world state flush; the reset primitive." :prerequisites ("world/spawn" "entity/alive?") :progression "Learn world/snapshot and world/restore! for selective state capture; then study world/step for frame-by-frame simulation."))

(verb
  :name "world/restore!"
  :library "world"
  :kind "mut"
  :signature "(world/restore! snapshot) → void"
  :summary "Replace the entire world state from a prior snapshot; malformed snapshot → 'bad-arg."
  :explanation "world/restore! reverts the simulation to a saved checkpoint. You capture a snapshot with world/snapshot (an opaque blob), then pass it to restore! to roll back all entities, forces, timers, and frame counter. This is the twin of snapshot: together they form a checkpoint–restore pair. Use this for replays, undo, or branching exploration. If the snapshot is corrupted or from an incompatible world version, the verb returns the symbol 'bad-arg and does not mutate."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(define snap (world/snapshot))\n(world/spawn 'enemy 300 200)\n(world/restore! snap)\n(world/count)" :note "Snapshot before spawning, restore erases the enemy; count is back to zero.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define (try-move-player id dx dy)\n  (let ((before (world/snapshot)))\n    (entity/set-pos! id (+ (entity/x id) dx) (+ (entity/y id) dy))\n    (if (world/count 'obstacle)\n      (world/restore! before)  ;; revert if collision\n      (display \"Moved OK\"))))\n(try-move-player player-id 10 0)" :note "Speculative move: snapshot, test, restore if invalid.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (rewind-to-checkpoint key)\n  (let ((snap (entity/get (world/find 'checkpoint-store) key)))\n    (cond ((equal? snap 'nan) (escalate 'no-checkpoint-saved null))\n          (else (world/restore! snap)\n                (next 'continue-play ctx)))))\n(rewind-to-checkpoint 'level-2-halfway)" :note "Retrieve a saved checkpoint from an entity's data store and restore the world.")
  )
  :caveats ("Snapshot is opaque; you cannot inspect or merge two snapshots." "Frame counter is restored; if you restore an old snapshot, frame numbering jumps backward (affects any age-based logic)." "Bad snapshot argument returns 'bad-arg but does NOT throw; check the return value." "Restoring inside a world/step is undefined; only restore between frames.")
  :drawbacks ("Snapshots are memory-heavy (include all entity state); storing many is expensive." "No incremental snapshots or delta compression; each is a full copy." "Restoring flushes the undo stack; you cannot redo after a restore.")
  :usecases ("Undo/redo in puzzle or strategy games." "Checkpoint save/load for long campaigns." "Replaying a recorded game from a saved point." "Testing branching behavior without replaying the whole sequence.")
  :related ("world/snapshot" "world/reset!" "world/tape-save" "world/tape-replay")
  :learn (:concept "State checkpoint and restore; reversal without redo." :prerequisites ("world/snapshot" "world/spawn" "entity/alive?") :progression "Combine with world/tape-save for full replay infrastructure; study world/hash for determinism validation."))

(verb
  :name "world/snapshot"
  :library "world"
  :kind "rd"
  :signature "(world/snapshot) → snapshot"
  :summary "Capture an opaque, restorable copy of the entire world state."
  :explanation "world/snapshot freezes the world at this instant: all entity positions, velocities, FSM states, collision state, timers, and forces are encoded into an opaque blob. Pass this blob to world/restore! later to roll back. Snapshots are immutable once created; they do not change if the world evolves. Use snapshots to implement checkpoints, undo, branching exploration, or determinism validation (paired with world/hash)."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(define snap1 (world/snapshot))\n(display \"Snapshot taken\")" :note "Capture the world; snapshot is now a referenceable value.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define (safe-simulation steps)\n  (let ((snap (world/snapshot)))\n    (for-each (lambda (_) (world/step)) (map (lambda (i) i) (list steps)))\n    (display (world/hash))  ;; log hash for replay\n    snap))\n(define s (safe-simulation 10))" :note "Snapshot before a batch of steps; record hash; snapshot is still valid.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (explore-branch option-id)\n  (let ((branch-point (world/snapshot)))\n    (define (revert) (world/restore! branch-point))\n    (define (commit) (revert))  ;; no-op; changes persist\n    (case option-id\n      ((1) (world/spawn 'path-a 100 100) (list 'committed (world/hash)))\n      ((2) (revert) (world/spawn 'path-b 100 100) (list 'committed (world/hash)))\n      (else (revert) (list 'cancelled (world/hash))))))\n(explore-branch 1)" :note "Use snapshot as a branch point; selectively revert to explore alternatives.")
  )
  :caveats ("Snapshot is a deep copy; creating many snapshots in a loop will consume memory quickly." "The snapshot is NOT invalidated if the world is later reset or restored; it captures a fixed point in time." "Snapshot does not capture user-defined entity data stored outside the entity record (though entity/get data IS included)." "Snapshots are not portable across world resets or interpreter restarts.")
  :drawbacks ("Memory overhead; each snapshot includes all live entities and state." "No compression or delta snapshots; each is independent." "Opaque to Scheme; you cannot inspect or selectively restore parts.")
  :usecases ("Checkpoint systems in roguelike or permadeath games." "Undo stacks for turn-based games." "Determinism testing (snapshot, step, hash; compare replays)." "Branch exploration in puzzle solvers.")
  :related ("world/restore!" "world/reset!" "world/hash" "world/tape-save")
  :learn (:concept "Immutable world state capture; the read half of snapshot–restore." :prerequisites ("world/spawn" "world/step") :progression "Learn world/restore! to complete the pair; then study world/hash for determinism assertions."))

(verb
  :name "world/solve!"
  :library "world"
  :kind "mut"
  :signature "(world/solve! [iters]) → frame"
  :summary "Project all constraint links to satisfy distance and rest goals; optional iteration count (1–64) → current frame."
  :explanation "world/solve! iteratively relaxes all active links (distance constraints, pin joints, rest links) toward their target lengths and configurations. Each call to solve! runs a fixed number of constraint-projection passes (default 1, max 64) to push linked entities toward equilibrium. This is typically called once per world/step as part of the physics pipeline, but you can call it explicitly for multi-step constraint solving or interactive deformation. Returns the current frame number."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(world/spawn 'anchor 100 100)\n(world/spawn 'bob 150 100)\n(world/link! (world/find 'anchor) (world/find 'bob) 50)\n(world/solve!)" :note "Create a linked pair and solve constraints once.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define (multi-step-solve steps iters)\n  (for-each (lambda (_) \n              (world/step)\n              (world/solve! iters))\n            (list steps)))\n(multi-step-solve 5 4)" :note "Each frame: step physics, then solve constraints with 4 iterations for stiffness.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (interactive-constraint-relax user-input)\n  (let ((id (world/find 'cursor)))\n    (when (input-pressed? 'mouse-drag)\n      (entity/set-pos! id (input/x) (input/y))))\n  (world/step)\n  (world/solve! 8)  ;; high iteration count for real-time feel\n  (world/frame))\n(interactive-constraint-relax user-input)" :note "Move a constrained node interactively; high solver iterations keep links tight.")
  )
  :caveats ("solve! must be called AFTER world/step in the frame to resolve new constraints." "Iteration count > 64 is clamped to 64; you cannot request unbounded iterations." "Links must be created with world/link! or world/link-rest! before solve! can affect them." "Solving does not advance time or apply forces; it only corrects positions.")
  :drawbacks ("High iteration counts (>16) add noticeable CPU cost per frame." "Constraint chains (A–B–C) require multiple iterations to converge; deep chains are slow." "Conflicting constraints (impossible link geometry) may oscillate or jitter instead of settling." "solve! does not handle all constraint types; some require entity/set-pos! or manual impulse application.")
  :usecases ("Physics-based ropes, chains, and soft-body deformation." "Pin-joint interactive manipulation (dragging nodes)." "Cloth or fabric simulation with distance constraints." "Real-time mechanical linkages (gears, levers, joints).")
  :related ("world/step" "world/link!" "world/link-rest!" "world/impulse!" "entity/set-pos!")
  :learn (:concept "Iterative constraint projection; the solver phase of the physics pipeline." :prerequisites ("world/spawn" "world/link!" "world/step") :progression "Combine with world/link-rest! for rest angles; study world/impulse! for direct force control."))

(verb
  :name "world/spawn"
  :library "world"
  :kind "mut"
  :signature "(world/spawn kind x y [w] [h]) → id"
  :summary "Create a new entity of a given kind at (x, y) with optional width/height → entity id; bad coordinate → 'bad-arg."
  :explanation "world/spawn instantiates a new actor (entity) in the simulation. The kind is a symbol naming the entity type; x and y are the starting position. Optional width and height define the entity's AABB (bounding box); if omitted, a default 1×1 box is used. The verb returns a unique id that can be used with entity/* verbs to query or modify the entity. Bad coordinates (NaN, Infinity, out-of-bounds) return 'bad-arg instead. Spawned entities start alive, untagged, and in a neutral FSM state."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(define p (world/spawn 'player 100 100))\n(display p)" :note "Spawn a player at (100, 100); p is now a valid entity id.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define (spawn-enemies count)\n  (map (lambda (i) (world/spawn 'enemy (+ 50 (* i 80)) 150))\n       (list count)))\n(define enemy-ids (spawn-enemies 5))" :note "Spawn multiple enemies in a row; returns a list of ids.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (arena-setup)\n  (define player (world/spawn 'player 400 300 20 20))\n  (world/gravity! 0 0.5)\n  (for-each (lambda (i) \n              (world/spawn 'obstacle (random-range 0 800) (random-range 100 300) 40 20))\n            (list 10))\n  (display (world/count)))\n(arena-setup)" :note "Full arena setup: spawn player with explicit size, set gravity, spawn obstacles.")
  )
  :caveats ("x, y must be finite numbers; NaN or Infinity → 'bad-arg." "Coordinates outside the world bounds may spawn but render off-screen." "Width/height default to 1 if omitted; use explicit values for proper collision." "Entities are born in bornSeq order; iteration order is deterministic." "The same kind can be spawned many times; kind is just a label.")
  :drawbacks ("No built-in entity pooling or reuse; each spawn allocates fresh memory." "Spawning many entities per frame (>1000) may cause frame-rate drops." "No 'despawn-all-of-kind'; use world/find + entity/despawn! to clean up selectively." "Default size (1×1) is tiny; forgetting to set width/height causes invisible hitboxes.")
  :usecases ("Spawning player at level start." "Procedural enemy waves or bullet patterns." "Dynamic obstacles or collectibles." "Creating visual markers or debug nodes.")
  :related ("entity/despawn!" "entity/set-pos!" "world/find" "world/each" "world/count")
  :learn (:concept "Entity birth; the fundamental creation primitive." :prerequisites ("world/step" "entity/alive?") :progression "Learn entity/set-pos!, entity/set-vel!, and entity/set! to configure spawned entities; then use world/each to iterate and update."))

(verb
  :name "world/step"
  :library "world"
  :kind "mut"
  :signature "(world/step) → frame"
  :summary "Advance the world by one frame: integrate physics, apply tweens, detect collisions, flush despawns → current frame number."
  :explanation "world/step is the heartbeat of the physics and animation loop. In one call it: (1) integrates velocities and forces into positions (Verlet or semi-implicit Euler), (2) applies active tweens (animated values), (3) detects entity–entity and entity–geometry collisions, (4) flushes despawn requests from the prior frame. It then returns the new frame number. Call world/step once per game frame, typically inside a on-tick or big-bang loop. The frame counter increments by 1 each step."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(world/step)\n(world/step)\n(display (world/frame))" :note "Two steps; frame counter now reads 2.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define (game-loop)\n  (when (game/running?)\n    (world/step)\n    (world/each (lambda (id) (display (entity/pos id))))\n    (schedule game-loop)))\n(game-loop)" :note "Main loop: step, then iterate over all entities to update logic.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (physics-tick)\n  (world/step)\n  (for-each (lambda (pair)\n              (let ((a (car pair)) (b (cadr pair)))\n                (on-collision a b)))\n            (world/collisions))\n  (world/each (lambda (id)\n                (when (entity/alive? id)\n                  (let ((state (entity/state id)))\n                    (case state\n                      ((moving) (move-update id))\n                      ((idle) (idle-update id)))))))\n(physics-tick)" :note "Full tick: step, process collisions, update each entity's state machine.")
  )
  :caveats ("Calling world/step from within a collision handler or entity callback is undefined; step between frames only." "Entities despawned via entity/despawn! in the current frame are not removed until the next world/step; queries still see them as alive." "Collision detection is discrete; fast-moving small entities may pass through gaps." "Forces and gravity are applied cumulatively; 0 0 gravity still requires an explicit world/gravity! call to set." "Tweens and animations progress by 1/60 of their duration per frame (assuming 60 FPS); frame rate sensitivity can be an issue.")
  :drawbacks ("Fixed time-step; no delta-time scaling. All physics assumes 1 frame ≈ constant dt." "Step cost grows with entity count; 1000+ entities per frame may stall." "Collision callbacks are synchronous and not cancelable." "Determinism relies on all forces and impulses being applied in the same order; randomness breaks replays.")
  :usecases ("Main game-loop heartbeat." "Physics-based puzzle or platformer simulation." "Collision detection in real-time games." "Time-step synchronization for replay recording.")
  :related ("world/spawn" "world/collisions" "world/gravity!" "world/frame" "entity/despawn!")
  :learn (:concept "Discrete time stepping; one frame of physics and animation." :prerequisites ("world/spawn" "entity/alive?") :progression "Learn world/collisions to handle collision pairs; then world/gravity! and entity forces for dynamic behavior."))

(verb
  :name "world/sway-all!"
  :library "world"
  :kind "null"
  :signature "(world/sway-all! tag period amplitude) → count"
  :summary "Oscillate all entities bearing a tag with sinusoidal phase-offset rotation; returns the number of entities affected."
  :explanation "world/sway-all! creates a wave of swaying motion across all entities tagged with a given tag. Each entity oscillates with a sine curve parameterized by period (frame count per cycle) and amplitude (max rotation angle in radians). The phase is offset by each entity's birth order (bornSeq) to create a staggered, flowing effect. The motion is stored in each entity's '__spin' data slot and must be applied to rendering/animation by the caller. Returns the count of entities that matched the tag."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(world/spawn 'flower 100 100)\n(entity/tag! (world/find 'flower) 'sway)\n(world/sway-all! 'sway 60 0.5)\n(display (world/sway-all! 'sway 60 0.5))" :note "Tag a flower, then sway all tagged flowers with 60-frame period and 0.5 amplitude; count is 1.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define (create-grass field-size)\n  (for-each (lambda (i)\n              (let ((id (world/spawn 'grass (* i 20) 200)))\n                (entity/tag! id 'wind-sway)))\n            (list field-size))\n  (world/sway-all! 'wind-sway 40 0.3))\n(create-grass 10)" :note "Create a field of grass, tag them, sway in unison with phase offsets.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (rhythm-sway beat-period)\n  (let ((count (world/sway-all! 'dancer 60 0.2)))\n    (when (> count 0)\n      (world/each (lambda (id)\n                    (when (entity/tag? id 'dancer)\n                      (let ((spin (entity/get id '__spin)))\n                        (when (not (equal? spin 'nan))\n                          (sprite-rotate-animation id spin))))))))))\n(rhythm-sway 60)" :note "Sway dancers, then apply their __spin values to sprite rotations for visual effect.")
  )
  :caveats ("world/sway-all! only computes and stores the oscillation; it does NOT render or animate. The caller must read '__spin' and apply it." "The phase offset formula (0.37 scaling factor) is fixed; you cannot customize the inter-entity phase spacing." "Entities spawned after calling sway-all! will inherit the phase offset formula based on their bornSeq, which may look wrong." "Amplitude is in radians; 0.5 radians ≈ 28 degrees. Very large amplitudes (>π) may cause visual aliasing." "Tag must be a symbol or string; other types are coerced to string.")
  :drawbacks ("The '__spin' value is overwritten each frame; you cannot accumulate or blend multiple sways on the same entity." "No built-in damping or easing; oscillation is pure sine with no decay." "Period must be > 0; period ≤ 0 causes undefined behavior." "The verb is undocumented in the source; behavior inferred from inline code.")
  :usecases ("Gentle swaying grass or plant fields." "Synchronized dancing or choreography in rhythm games." "Wave-like crowd motion or NPC formations." "Visual feedback for wind or water currents.")
  :related ("entity/tag!" "entity/untag!" "entity/get" "world/each" "world/frame")
  :learn (:concept "Phase-coherent oscillation across a group; staggered sine waves." :prerequisites ("entity/tag!" "world/spawn" "world/each") :progression "Learn entity/get to retrieve the '__spin' value; combine with sprite animation to render the sway."))

(verb
  :name "world/tape-audio"
  :library "world"
  :kind "rd"
  :signature "(world/tape-audio) -> list"
  :summary "Return the audio events recorded on the latest tape frame as a list of (kind channel gain) rows; silent frame returns the empty list."
  :explanation "The tape is a record of every frame that has been rendered or simulated. Each frame captures audio events—sounds played, their channel (track), and gain (volume). world/tape-audio retrieves those events from the most recent frame, allowing you to inspect what sounds occurred, when they occurred, and at what volume. This is useful for debugging audio timing, exporting audio logs, or triggering secondary effects based on recorded sounds."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(world/tape-audio)" :note "Returns all audio events from the last frame, e.g., ((kick main 0.8) (snare 1 0.6)).")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define latest-audio (world/tape-audio))\n(define audio-count (length latest-audio))\n(if (> audio-count 0)\n  (display (list \"Frame had\" audio-count \"sounds\")))" :note "Count the number of audio events in the latest frame and log it if any occurred.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (extract-audio-by-channel target-channel)\n  (let ((audio-events (world/tape-audio)))\n    (filter (lambda (evt)\n              (equal? (cadr evt) target-channel))\n            audio-events)))\n(define drum-sounds (extract-audio-by-channel 'drums))" :note "Filter tape audio to find all events on a specific channel; useful for post-processing or logging.")
  )
  :caveats ("Returns an empty list if the tape is empty (no frames recorded yet) or if the latest frame has no audio events." "The tape is a history of what was recorded; this verb only reads the latest frame, not the full history. Use world/tape-frames to get the frame count if you need to iterate." "Audio events are structured as (kind channel gain); if any field is missing in the source, it is replaced with the symbol 'none, not null." "Tape recording must be active; if world/tape-recording? returns false, tape-audio returns whatever was last recorded.")
  :drawbacks ("Reading tape data does not reset or advance the tape; repeated calls return the same frame until the tape steps." "No filtering or searching inside tape-audio; you must filter the result with filter or fold if you need a subset." "The tape is a linear record; you cannot access past frames via tape-audio (only the latest). To access history, use world/tape-hash or world/tape-frames and consider storing snapshots.")
  :usecases ("Debug audio timing by logging which sounds occurred in a given frame." "Post-process a recorded tape to extract sound metadata for analysis or export." "Trigger visual effects (e.g., screen flash) synchronized to recorded audio events." "Audit a performance: check that the expected sounds were played at the expected times.")
  :related ("world/tape-record!" "world/tape-stop!" "world/tape-recording?" "world/tape-frames" "world/tape-hash")
  :learn (:concept "Tape as a persistent record of simulation state, and audio events as a subset of that record." :prerequisites ("world/tape-record!" "world/frame") :progression "After learning tape-audio, study world/tape-replay to re-render recorded frames, and world/tape-save to persist a tape to disk."))

(verb
  :name "world/tape-clear!"
  :library "world"
  :kind "mut"
  :signature "(world/tape-clear!) → true"
  :summary "Discard the replay tape and disarm recording; always returns true."
  :explanation "world/tape-clear! resets the replay recording system. If a replay is currently recording (via world/tape-record!), it is halted and all frames are discarded. The tape buffer is emptied. Calling world/tape-clear! when no tape is active is a no-op. This is useful to free memory or restart recording from a clean state. Always returns true (a success marker)."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(world/tape-clear!)" :note "Clear any active tape; tape is now empty.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define (record-and-save filename)\n  (world/tape-clear!)\n  (world/tape-record!)\n  (for-each (lambda (_) (world/step)) (list 100))\n  (let ((tape (world/tape-save)))\n    (display (list \"Saved\" (length tape) \"frames\"))))\n(record-and-save \"demo.tape\")" :note "Clear old tape, record new frames, save to file.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (try-solution attempt-id)\n  (let ((snap (world/snapshot)))\n    (world/tape-clear!)\n    (world/tape-record!)\n    (execute-attempt attempt-id)\n    (let ((tape (world/tape-save)))\n      (if (goal-reached?) \n        (list 'success tape)\n        (begin\n          (world/tape-clear!)\n          (world/restore! snap)\n          (list 'failed-attempt attempt-id))))))\n(try-solution 5)" :note "Clear tape, attempt a solution, save if successful, or revert and clear if not.")
  )
  :caveats ("world/tape-clear! does not clear the snapshot; use world/snapshot separately." "Calling clear while a replay is being played back (world/tape-replay) may cause undefined behavior." "The tape is lost immediately; there is no undo for the clear operation." "Clearing a tape does not free memory in all implementations; rely on garbage collection.")
  :drawbacks ("Once cleared, the recorded frames are unrecoverable; no rollback." "If you want to preserve a recording, you must call world/tape-save BEFORE clearing." "Clearing does not reset the frame counter or entities; only the tape buffer is flushed.")
  :usecases ("Starting a fresh replay recording session." "Freeing memory before a large simulation." "Abandoning a failed replay attempt." "Resetting the tape subsystem for a new level or mode.")
  :related ("world/tape-record!" "world/tape-save" "world/tape-replay" "world/snapshot" "world/restore!")
  :learn (:concept "Tape lifecycle; clearing and resetting the recording buffer." :prerequisites ("world/tape-record!" "world/tape-save") :progression "Combine with world/tape-record! and world/tape-save to build a full record–save–replay workflow."))

(verb
  :name "world/tape-frames"
  :library "world"
  :kind "rd"
  :signature "(world/tape-frames) -> number"
  :summary "Returns the count of frames currently held in the motion tape."
  :explanation "The motion tape is a rolling buffer that records entity state and camera position at each simulation step. This verb answers: how many frames are stored right now? Use it to check whether a recording exists, or to plan replay logic. An empty tape returns 0."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(begin\n  (world/tape-record! 300)\n  (world/step)\n  (world/step)\n  (display (world/tape-frames)))" :note "After two steps of recording, the tape holds 3 frames (initial capture + 2 steps).")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(begin\n  (world/tape-record! 500)\n  (world/each (lambda (id) (entity/move! id 1 0)))\n  (world/step)\n  (if (> (world/tape-frames) 100)\n    (world/tape-stop!)\n    (next 'keep-recording ctx)))" :note "Check frame count mid-recording to decide when to halt; avoids unbounded memory.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (replay-checkpoint ctx)\n  (let ((saved-tape (world/tape-save)))\n    (if (null? saved-tape)\n      (escalate 'no-tape-to-save null)\n      (begin\n        (display (list 'saved (length saved-tape) 'frames))\n        (next 'idle (ctx-set 'last-tape saved-tape ctx))))))" :note "Use frame count implicitly via `world/tape-save` length to verify a checkpoint was captured before moving on.")
  )
  :caveats ("Returns 0 if tape is not armed (read-only; does not arm the tape)." "Count includes the initial frame captured by `world/tape-record!`." "If a rolling-window cap was set, old frames may be discarded; this reflects only current length, not total ever-recorded.")
  :drawbacks ("Does not tell you whether recording is currently active; use `world/tape-recording?` for that." "No way to query individual frame metadata from Scheme; use `world/tape-save` to inspect the full structure.")
  :usecases ("Deciding whether to serialize a checkpoint (non-empty tape exists)." "Throttling or stopping recording when tape reaches a size threshold." "Debugging: asserting that motion was captured before a replay attempt.")
  :related ("world/tape-recording?" "world/tape-record!" "world/tape-save" "world/tape-clear!" "world/tape-stop!")
  :learn (:concept "Reading transient state—the tape is a side-effect resource, and this verb lets you inspect its size." :prerequisites ("world/frame" "world/step") :progression "Once comfortable with frame queries, move to `world/tape-record!` to arm recording, then `world/tape-save` to serialize."))

(verb
  :name "world/tape-hash"
  :library "world"
  :kind "rd"
  :signature "(world/tape-hash) -> number"
  :summary "Returns a 32-bit digest (hash) of the entire motion tape for integrity checking."
  :explanation "When you replay a recording, you want to assert that the same input and world snapshot produce the same output tape. This verb computes a fast hash over all frames. Two tapes with the same hash have the same entity positions, kinds, and sprite assignments (and thus should render identically). Use it to validate replay determinism or to detect corruption."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(begin\n  (world/tape-record! 200)\n  (world/step)\n  (world/step)\n  (let ((h1 (world/tape-hash)))\n    (display h1)))" :note "Compute the hash of a short 3-frame recording to verify it is captured.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(begin\n  (world/tape-record! 1000)\n  (dotimes (i 50) (world/step))\n  (let ((h-live (world/tape-hash)))\n    (world/tape-stop!)\n    (if (equal? h-live 0)\n      (escalate 'hash-empty null)\n      (display (list 'tape-hash h-live)))))" :note "Stop recording and check that the hash is non-zero (tape has content).")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (validate-replay ctx)\n  (let ((saved-tape (world/tape-save))\n        (h-original (ctx-get 'replay-hash ctx)))\n    (begin\n      (world/tape-clear!)\n      (world/tape-record! 5000)\n      ;; (simulate replay path here)\n      (let ((h-replay (world/tape-hash)))\n        (if (= h-original h-replay)\n          (next 'success (ctx-set 'verified true ctx))\n          (escalate 'replay-mismatch (list h-original h-replay)))))))" :note "Store the original tape hash, then replay and compare. Mismatch means non-determinism or corrupted input.")
  )
  :caveats ("Hash is 32-bit; collisions are theoretically possible but vanishingly rare in practice." "Hash changes if *any* entity position, kind, or sprite differs between two recordings—even sub-pixel deltas." "Hash is computed over the current tape state; it changes as frames are added (rolling window may discard old frames).")
  :drawbacks ("Does not identify *which* frame or entity caused a mismatch; only signals that tapes differ." "Requires full tape in memory; cannot stream-validate very long recordings." "If tape is empty, hash is well-defined but not useful for asserting content (use `world/tape-frames > 0` first).")
  :usecases ("Regression testing: assert that a replay of a saved tape produces bit-identical output." "Deduplication: store only the hash of a checkpoint, not the full tape, and verify replay matches." "Detecting silent corruption in tape serialization or deserialization.")
  :related ("world/tape-save" "world/tape-frames" "world/tape-record!" "world/tape-stop!")
  :learn (:concept "Determinism verification—the hash is a compact witness to the tape's content, enabling offline assertion without storing megabytes of frame data." :prerequisites ("world/tape-frames" "world/tape-recording?") :progression "Combine with `world/tape-save` to build a checkpoint system: save hash + frame count, discard raw tape, then validate replay determinism."))

(verb
  :name "world/tape-lcamera"
  :library "world"
  :kind "rd"
  :signature "(world/tape-lcamera) -> (list number number number) | 'none"
  :summary "Returns the local (operator) viewport camera position and zoom from the most recent tape frame."
  :explanation "The tape records not only entity state but also where the camera was looking at each frame. The local camera is the viewport controlled by the operator during live playback. This verb returns `[x y k]` (x-coord, y-coord, zoom factor) from the latest frame, or the symbol `'none` if no camera was in scope (headless mode or camera verbs not installed). Use it to preserve and restore the operator's viewpoint during replay."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(begin\n  (world/tape-record! 500)\n  (camera-pan 100 50)\n  (world/step)\n  (let ((cam (world/tape-lcamera)))\n    (display cam)))" :note "After panning the camera and stepping, the tape records the new camera position. Retrieve it to confirm capture.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(begin\n  (world/tape-record! 1000)\n  (dotimes (i 30) (world/step))\n  (let ((cam (world/tape-lcamera)))\n    (cond ((equal? cam 'none)\n           (display 'headless))\n          (else\n           (display (list 'camera-at (car cam) (cadr cam) 'zoom (caddr cam)))))))" :note "Check whether camera was recorded; if headless, `'none` is returned.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (restore-operator-view ctx)\n  (let ((cam (world/tape-lcamera)))\n    (if (equal? cam 'none)\n      (next 'idle ctx)\n      (begin\n        (camera-snap! (car cam) (cadr cam))\n        (camera-zoom-to (caddr cam))\n        (next 'replay-ready (ctx-set 'viewport cam ctx))))))" :note "After loading a saved tape, restore the operator's exact viewpoint: pan to x/y and set zoom, enabling \"show me that again\" to replay from the operator's perspective.")
  )
  :caveats ("Returns `'none` if no frames are recorded (tape is empty)." "Returns `'none` if recording was active but camera verbs were not installed or never called." "Reflects only the *latest* frame's camera; earlier frames' cameras are only accessible via `world/tape-save`." "Camera values are in world coordinates, not screen coordinates.")
  :drawbacks ("No way to query intermediate frame cameras from Scheme directly; use `world/tape-save` to extract the full history." "If camera was never set during recording, you lose the operator's implicit starting view.")
  :usecases ("Preserving the operator's field of view across a replay: save the camera position and restore it at play-back time." "Headless testing: detect whether a recording was made in a GUI context (camera present) vs. server-side (no camera)." "Choreography validation: confirm that a sequence was recorded with a specific camera framing.")
  :related ("camera-pan" "camera-zoom-to" "camera-snap!" "world/tape-save" "world/tape-frames")
  :learn (:concept "Auxiliary state in motion capture—the tape records not just the world, but the operator's vantage point, enabling full replay fidelity." :prerequisites ("world/tape-record!" "camera-pan" "camera-zoom-to") :progression "Use this to anchor replay to the operator's saved view; then explore `world/tape-save` to inspect frame-by-frame camera history."))

(verb
  :name "world/tape-record!"
  :library "world"
  :kind "mut"
  :signature "(world/tape-record! [cap]) -> true"
  :summary "Arm the motion tape and capture the current world frame; optionally set a rolling-window capacity."
  :explanation "Begin recording the world's motion. Each call to `world/step` appends a new frame to the tape. You can supply an optional capacity `cap` (a positive integer) to limit memory: once the tape reaches `cap` frames, older frames roll off. If `cap` is omitted or non-finite, the tape grows without bound. Always returns `true`. Call `world/tape-stop!` to halt recording (tape is retained), or `world/tape-clear!` to discard it."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(begin\n  (world/tape-record! 100)\n  (world/step)\n  (world/step)\n  (display (world/tape-frames)))" :note "Record with a cap of 100 frames. After two steps, tape holds 3 frames (init + 2 steps). Display shows 3.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(begin\n  (world/tape-record!)\n  (dotimes (i 60)\n    (world/each (lambda (id)\n      (entity/move! id (random-range -2 2) (random-range -2 2))))\n    (world/step))\n  (let ((n (world/tape-stop!)))\n    (display (list 'recorded n 'frames))))" :note "Unbounded recording (no cap): move entities randomly for 60 steps, then stop and report the final frame count.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (record-scene ctx)\n  (world/tape-clear!)\n  (world/tape-record! 5000)\n  (let ((loop-count (ctx-get 'loops ctx)))\n    (if (= loop-count 0)\n      (begin\n        (display 'recording-started)\n        (next 'animate (ctx-set 'loops 1 ctx)))\n      (if (< (world/tape-frames) 4800)\n        (next 'animate (ctx-set 'loops (+ loop-count 1) ctx))\n        (next 'save-checkpoint (ctx-set 'tape (world/tape-save) ctx))))))" :note "Orchestrate a multi-frame recording: arm the tape, loop until near capacity, then save checkpoint. Capacity acts as a guard against runaway memory.")
  )
  :caveats ("Calling `world/tape-record!` again discards the prior tape unconditionally." "The initial capture (frame 0) happens synchronously; do not call during `world/each` or entity mutations." "Capacity is in frames, not bytes; a cap of 1000 may consume significant memory depending on entity count." "If `cap` argument is non-numeric or ≤ 0, capacity defaults to unlimited (0 in internal code, treated as no-limit).")
  :drawbacks ("Memory cost grows linearly with frame count and entity count; unbounded recording can exhaust heap." "No built-in compression or streaming to disk; the tape is always in-memory." "If you want to record multiple independent takes, you must manually save each tape (via `world/tape-save`) before arming a new recording.")
  :usecases ("Motion capture for replay: record a choreography sequence, then play it back deterministically." "Debugging: record a trace of entity motion to replay a failure scenario." "Live demo: arm recording, run a scene, then show the replay to an audience." "Rolling buffer for crash diagnostics: record the last N frames in a production system so you can replay the incident.")
  :related ("world/tape-stop!" "world/tape-clear!" "world/tape-recording?" "world/tape-frames" "world/tape-save" "world/step")
  :learn (:concept "Side-effect management—the tape is a mutable resource that you arm, fill, and query. Understanding this pattern is key to building deterministic replay systems." :prerequisites ("world/step" "world/frame") :progression "Once recording works, learn `world/tape-stop!` to halt, then `world/tape-save` to serialize, then `world/tape-hash` to validate."))

(verb
  :name "world/tape-recording?"
  :library "world"
  :kind "rd"
  :signature "(world/tape-recording?) -> boolean"
  :summary "Check whether the motion tape is currently armed (recording frames on each step)."
  :explanation "The tape can be armed (frames accumulate with each `world/step`) or disarmed (steps do not record). This verb returns `true` if recording is live, `false` otherwise. Use it to guard code paths that should only run during capture, or to decide whether to halt recording."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(begin\n  (display (world/tape-recording?))\n  (world/tape-record! 100)\n  (display (world/tape-recording?))\n  (world/tape-stop!)\n  (display (world/tape-recording?)))" :note "Initially false, becomes true after `tape-record!`, then false after `tape-stop!`.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(begin\n  (world/tape-record! 500)\n  (dotimes (i 50)\n    (if (world/tape-recording?)\n      (begin\n        (world/each (lambda (id) (entity/move! id 1 0)))\n        (world/step))\n      (display 'recording-halted))))" :note "Guard a movement loop: only move and step if recording is still armed.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (capture-until-full ctx)\n  (if (world/tape-recording?)\n    (let ((frames (world/tape-frames))\n          (cap 1000))\n      (world/step)\n      (if (>= frames cap)\n        (begin\n          (world/tape-stop!)\n          (next 'save-tape (ctx-set 'frames frames ctx)))\n        (next 'capture-until-full ctx)))\n    (next 'idle ctx)))" :note "Recursively step and check capacity; when full, stop and transition. The guard `world/tape-recording?` ensures we don't step after stopping.")
  )
  :caveats ("Returns `false` by default (tape is not armed on startup)." "Checking this does not affect the tape; it is a pure read." "Frame count can be > 0 even if recording is false (a stopped tape retains its contents).")
  :drawbacks ("Does not tell you how full the tape is or whether capacity was exceeded; use `world/tape-frames` for that." "No way to pause recording without stopping (stopping disarms but keeps frames; restarting via `tape-record!` clears them).")
  :usecases ("Conditional logic: only record motion during a specific phase or when a condition is met." "Safety check: verify that recording is still active before performing expensive captures." "State machine transitions: decide whether to save the tape or discard it based on whether recording succeeded.")
  :related ("world/tape-record!" "world/tape-stop!" "world/tape-frames" "world/tape-clear!")
  :learn (:concept "State queries—in addition to reading data, you often need to know *whether* a resource is active. This verb answers that question." :prerequisites ("world/tape-record!" "world/step") :progression "Combine with `world/tape-frames` and `world/tape-stop!` to build a full tape management workflow."))

(verb
  :name "world/tape-replay"
  :library "world"
  :kind "rd"
  :signature "(world/tape-replay surface) -> 'empty-tape | 'service-not-yet-wired"
  :summary "Replay the motion tape onto a registered surface (live re-render; not yet wired in the harness)."
  :explanation "After recording a tape, you can re-render it to visualize the motion. This verb accepts a surface argument and attempts to replay each frame onto that surface. Currently, the in-app harness does not wire the render path; the verb returns `'service-not-yet-wired` as a signal that the feature is planned but not yet implemented. If the tape is empty, it returns `'empty-tape`. In a full implementation, each frame would paint its entities onto the surface, frame by frame."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(begin\n  (world/tape-record! 100)\n  (world/step)\n  (let ((result (world/tape-replay 'some-surface)))\n    (display result)))" :note "After recording, call replay. Currently always returns `'service-not-yet-wired`.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(begin\n  (world/tape-clear!)\n  (let ((result (world/tape-replay 'any-surface)))\n    (if (equal? result 'empty-tape)\n      (display 'nothing-to-replay)\n      (display result))))" :note "If tape is empty, `'empty-tape` is returned; otherwise, `'service-not-yet-wired`.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (maybe-replay ctx)\n  (let ((saved-tape (ctx-get 'tape ctx)))\n    (if (null? saved-tape)\n      (escalate 'no-tape-to-replay null)\n      (begin\n        (world/tape-clear!)\n        (world/tape-record! 10000)\n        ;; (populate tape from saved-tape here)\n        (let ((status (world/tape-replay (ctx-get 'surface ctx))))\n          (cond ((equal? status 'empty-tape)\n                 (escalate 'replay-failed 'empty))\n                ((equal? status 'service-not-yet-wired)\n                 (next 'await-render-wire ctx))\n                (else\n                 (next 'replay-active ctx))))))))" :note "Check the return value to branch: if `'empty-tape`, something went wrong; if `'service-not-yet-wired`, the service is not yet bound (expected state).")
  )
  :caveats ("Currently always returns `'service-not-yet-wired`; actual rendering is not yet implemented in Scheme." "The `surface` argument is accepted but not used (no-op in current implementation)." "Returns `'empty-tape` if tape is empty, but this is the only success case that might be meaningful in future versions.")
  :drawbacks ("Feature is not yet wired; you cannot actually replay visual output from Scheme at this time." "No feedback mechanism to know when render is complete or has failed." "The render path is expected to be in the harness; Scheme cannot directly control painting.")
  :usecases ("Future-proofing: call this verb to prepare for the moment when live replay rendering is available." "Placeholder in replay workflows: structure your code to call `tape-replay` even though it is not yet functional, so the integration is ready when the service is wired." "Testing replay mechanics: verify that the tape structure is valid before the render service comes online.")
  :related ("world/tape-save" "world/tape-record!" "world/tape-frames" "surface-paint-dots" "surface-paint-text")
  :learn (:concept "Forward compatibility—sometimes a verb is declared and stubbed before its implementation arrives. This teaches you to code defensively by checking return values and understanding what a deferred service means." :prerequisites ("world/tape-record!" "world/tape-save") :progression "As the harness evolves and `tape-replay` is wired, you will gradually see it return meaningful results instead of `'service-not-yet-wired`. Keep your error checks in place."))

(verb
  :name "world/tape-save"
  :library "world"
  :kind "rd"
  :signature "(world/tape-save) -> (list) | '()"
  :summary "Serialize the entire motion tape into a portable, re-renderable list of frames (each with entities and local viewport camera); empty tape → '()."
  :explanation "The tape is an in-memory buffer. To persist it or pass it between systems, serialize it via this verb. The result is a list of frames, where each frame is a list: `(frame-number cam-x cam-y hash (entity-list) local-camera)`. Each entity record is `(id kind sprite x y state)`. The local camera is `[x y k]` or the symbol `'none`. This is the true recording—the lightweight, replayable form that a host can stash and re-render. Empty tape → `'()` (the empty list, not an error)."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(begin\n  (world/tape-record! 50)\n  (world/step)\n  (world/step)\n  (let ((saved (world/tape-save)))\n    (display (length saved))))" :note "After two steps, tape has 3 frames. Serialized list length is 3.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(begin\n  (world/tape-record! 200)\n  (dotimes (i 10) (world/step))\n  (let ((tape (world/tape-save)))\n    (if (null? tape)\n      (display 'empty)\n      (begin\n        (display (list 'frames (length tape)))\n        (display (list 'hash (world/tape-hash)))))))" :note "Save the tape after recording. Check that it is non-empty and display frame count and hash for later validation.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (checkpoint-scene ctx)\n  (let ((tape (world/tape-save))\n        (camera (world/tape-lcamera)))\n    (if (null? tape)\n      (escalate 'checkpoint-failed 'empty-tape)\n      (let ((checkpoint (list 'version 1 'frames tape 'camera camera 'hash (world/tape-hash))))\n        (begin\n          (display (list 'checkpointed (length tape) 'frames))\n          (next 'await-restore (ctx-set 'checkpoint checkpoint ctx)))))))" :note "Package the tape, camera, and hash into a checkpoint structure. Later, verify the hash matches during replay to detect corruption.")
  )
  :caveats ("Returns the empty list `'()` if tape is empty; this is a valid, honest-null result, not an error." "The serialized format includes frame number, camera, hash, and entity state. Do not edit these by hand; structure is strict." "Local camera may be `'none` if no camera was recorded for a given frame." "Entity state field may be `'none` if an entity had no state object.")
  :drawbacks ("Tape grows unbounded if no capacity was set; serializing a very large tape consumes time and memory." "Format is not compressed; a long recording with many entities will produce a large list." "No built-in versioning; if the tape format changes in a future Sakura version, old saved tapes may not deserialize.")
  :usecases ("Persistence: save a recording to disk or a database so it can be replayed later, even after the program restarts." "Determinism testing: save a tape, run a replay, verify the hash matches to confirm the replay is bit-identical." "Data sharing: export a tape in a portable form so other tools or systems can analyze or visualize it." "Checkpointing: bundle a tape with metadata (version, timestamp, actor info) to preserve a complete simulation snapshot.")
  :related ("world/tape-record!" "world/tape-frames" "world/tape-hash" "world/tape-lcamera" "world/tape-stop!")
  :learn (:concept "Serialization—converting a live, mutable resource (the in-memory tape) into a durable, shareable data structure. This is how you preserve the results of a simulation." :prerequisites ("world/tape-record!" "world/tape-frames" "world/tape-hash") :progression "After saving a tape, learn to validate it via hash and then design replay workflows that use the serialized data."))

(verb
  :name "world/tape-stop!"
  :library "world"
  :kind "mut"
  :signature "(world/tape-stop!) -> number"
  :summary "Stop recording; disarm the motion tape and return the final frame count."
  :explanation "After calling `world/tape-record!`, each `world/step` appends a frame. This verb disarms recording (sets the internal flag to false) so that future steps no longer record. The tape itself is retained, and you can inspect or save it via `world/tape-frames`, `world/tape-save`, or `world/tape-hash`. The return value is the total number of frames captured (including the initial frame from `tape-record!`). Use this to halt recording, report progress, and decide whether to keep or discard the tape."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(begin\n  (world/tape-record! 100)\n  (world/step)\n  (world/step)\n  (let ((count (world/tape-stop!)))\n    (display (list 'frames-recorded count))))" :note "Record two steps (plus initial), stop, and report that 3 frames were captured.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(begin\n  (world/tape-record! 500)\n  (dotimes (i 100)\n    (world/each (lambda (id) (entity/move! id 0.5 0)))\n    (world/step))\n  (let ((final-count (world/tape-stop!)))\n    (if (> final-count 450)\n      (display 'tape-near-full)\n      (display (list 'recorded final-count)))))" :note "Record up to 100 steps (plus init), stop, and check if we're near capacity. Return value tells us how many frames we actually have.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (record-and-checkpoint ctx)\n  (world/tape-record! 10000)\n  (let ((loop (lambda (frame-target)\n         (if (< (world/tape-frames) frame-target)\n           (begin\n             (world/step)\n             (loop frame-target))\n           (let ((count (world/tape-stop!)))\n             (begin\n               (display (list 'checkpointed count))\n               (next 'save (ctx-set 'tape (world/tape-save) ctx))))))))\n    (loop 500)))" :note "Recursively step until we reach a target frame count (500), then stop and capture the tape. Return value confirms the count.")
  )
  :caveats ("Calling `world/tape-stop!` does not clear the tape; frames remain in memory until `world/tape-clear!` is called." "If recording was already halted (via a prior `tape-stop!` call), calling it again still returns the current frame count and succeeds (idempotent with respect to the flag)." "Return value is the frame count at the moment `tape-stop!` is invoked; it does not change afterward unless more frames are added (via a new `tape-record!`).")
  :drawbacks ("No way to resume recording without clearing the tape; `tape-record!` always starts fresh." "If you want to record multiple independent takes, you must manually save each tape (via `world/tape-save`) before calling `tape-record!` again.")
  :usecases ("Ending a recording session and reporting how many frames were captured." "Checking whether the tape reached a size threshold before deciding to save or discard it." "Halting recording when a condition is met (e.g., a scene completes or an error occurs), while preserving the frames for inspection.")
  :related ("world/tape-record!" "world/tape-frames" "world/tape-recording?" "world/tape-clear!" "world/tape-save")
  :learn (:concept "State machine transitions—the tape has two states (armed/disarmed), and `tape-stop!` is the verb that transitions from one to the other while reporting the outcome." :prerequisites ("world/tape-record!" "world/step") :progression "After stopping a recording, use `world/tape-save` to serialize it, `world/tape-hash` to validate it, and `world/tape-clear!` to discard it when ready."))

(verb
  :name "world/wind!"
  :library "world"
  :kind "mut"
  :signature "(world/wind! dvx dvy) -> null"
  :summary "Apply a constant directional force to all physics-enabled entities."
  :explanation "Sets a global wind vector (dvx dvy) that accelerates every entity with physics enabled each frame. This is useful for environmental effects like wind, current, or drift. Pass (0 0) to disable wind. The force is applied uniformly; individual entities can vary their response via entity/gravity-scale! and entity/mass!. Wind does NOT affect pinned or static entities."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice" :code "(world/wind! 0.1 0)  ; constant rightward wind\n(world/step)" :note "Wind is applied every frame; entities accelerate in the wind direction over time.")
    (:tier "intermediate" :code "(define (update-wind strength)\n  (let ((angle (random-range 0 6.28)))\n    (world/wind! (* strength (cos angle))\n                 (* strength (sin angle)))))\n(update-wind 0.05)  ; wind in a random direction" :note "Wind can be updated per frame or on a schedule; here we vary its direction randomly.")
    (:tier "expert" :code "(define (wind-pulse beat-index strength)\n  (let ((phase (/ (modulo beat-index 4) 4)))\n    (world/wind! (* strength (sin (* 6.28 phase))) 0)))\n(on-tick (lambda (ctx)\n  (wind-pulse (audio-beat? (ctx-get 'beat ctx)) 0.15)\n  ctx))" :note "Wind strength synchronized to audio beats; creates a rhythmic drift effect.")
  )
  :caveats ("Wind is global; all physics-enabled entities are affected equally." "Pinned (entity/pin!) and non-physics entities are not affected." "Wind persists until explicitly changed; call (world/wind! 0 0) to stop it." "Wind is NOT included in world/snapshot or world/restore; it is render-only in the tape.")
  :drawbacks ("Global wind cannot be selectively applied to subgroups; use entity/accel! for per-entity forces." "Wind interacts with entity/drag! and entity/friction! in complex ways; test empirically." "Very strong wind can cause stability issues; keep magnitudes ≤ 0.5 for predictable behavior.")
  :usecases ("Simulating weather effects (wind, storms, currents) in a game world." "Creating ambient drift in zero-gravity or space scenes." "Choreographing entities to move together in a wave or swirl pattern." "Testing physics robustness under constant external forces.")
  :related ("entity/accel!" "entity/drag!" "entity/friction!" "entity/gravity-scale!" "world/gravity!" "world/step")
  :learn (:concept "Global forces as a world-state parameter; how external acceleration affects all physics simultaneously." :prerequisites ("world/spawn" "entity/set-vel!" "entity/mass!") :progression "After this, learn world/gravity! (per-entity override), then entity/accel! (per-frame force)."))


; ── CORE LANGUAGE FORMS ──
; Extracted from SAKURA-SCHEME-1.0.REF.md 2026-07-13

(core-form
  :name "and"
  :signature "(and expr1 expr2 ...)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** the last truthy value, or `#f` if any is false. Last\nposition is tail.\n**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/interp.js:354-361`\n**Side effects:** evaluates left-to-right and short-circuits.\n**Wired:** yes\n\nShort-circuit conjunction. Stops at the first `#f`; otherwise returns\nthe value of the final expression. In tail position, the last conjunct\nis itself in tail position.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n;; gate on a precondition\n(and (pair? topics) (not (null? topics)))\n;; → #t when both hold\n```\n*Source: `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/personal/daily-news-brief.sks` (predicate idiom — generated example)*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n;; only proceed if shop is connected AND has listings\n(if (and (ctx-get 'shop-connected ctx)\n         (pair? (ctx-result ctx)))\n    (next 'render ctx)\n    (escalate 'shop-not-connected null))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; compose three gates; the deepest pair? is the determining tail\n(when (and (eq? (ctx-get 'state ctx) 'ready)\n           (not (null? rows))\n           (pair? (assq ':price_ladder_suggestion rows)))\n  (next 'render (ctx-set 'finding rows ctx)))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "begin"
  :signature "(begin expr1 expr2 ... lastExpr)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** the value of the last expression.\n**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/interp.js:298-303`\n**Side effects:** evaluates each expression in order; last is tail.\n**Wired:** yes\n\nSequential composition. Earlier expressions are evaluated for side\neffects; the result of the last is returned. The lint star expects most\nmulti-effect bodies to live inside `(begin …)` or an implicit body\nposition.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n;; two effects, then done\n(begin\n  (table rows '(listing-id title metric value))\n  (done))\n```\n*Source: `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/etsy/age-distribution.sks:36-38`*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n;; in a cart render — emit chip, queue envelope, end\n(begin\n  (card-emit 'engine 'the-living-business-plan-ready (length finding))\n  (envelope-queue (list 'the-living-business-plan ':finding finding))\n  (done))\n```\n*Source: adapted from `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/magic/the-living-business-plan.sks:314-321`*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; tail position — the trailing (done) is the cart's terminal descriptor\n(let ((finding (ctx-get 'finding ctx)))\n  (begin\n    (paint-arrow 'price-ladder-card ':anchors anchors ':glow 'warm-amber)\n    (envelope-queue (list 'pink-price-ladder-suggest ':finding finding))\n    (done)))\n```\n*Source: condensed from `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/pink/pink-price-ladder-suggest.sks:277-289`*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "if"
  :signature "(if test then else)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** `then` if test is not `#f`, else `else` (or undefined).\n**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/interp.js:261-265`\n**Side effects:** evaluates test eagerly; chosen branch in tail position.\n**Wired:** yes\n\nTwo- or three-arm conditional. Anything but `#f` is true (R7RS).\nPrefer `cond` for more than two arms; lint reads bare `if` as fine\nfor binary gates.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(if (null? rows)\n    (escalate 'no-data null)\n    (next 'render ctx))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n;; cache hit shortcuts; miss goes to fetch\n(define (check-today ctx)\n  (let ((cached (ctx-result ctx)))\n    (if (null? cached)\n        (next 'recall-topics ctx)\n        (next 'render-cached (ctx-set 'cached cached ctx)))))\n```\n*Source: adapted from `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/personal/daily-news-brief.sks:82-87`*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; nested if as guard chain (cond is usually clearer — kept here for an honest example)\n(if (eq? (ctx-get 'tier ctx) 'magic)\n    (if (>= (length deltas) 12)\n        (next 'assemble-quarter-memo ctx)\n        (next 'accrue-week ctx))\n    (escalate 'tier-not-permitted null))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "not"
  :signature "(not value)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** `#t` if value is `#f`, else `#f`.\n**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/base.js:42`\n**Side effects:** none.\n**Wired:** yes (base primitive; not actually a special form)\n\nLogical negation. Only `#f` is false; everything else is true.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(not (null? topics))\n;; → #t if topics is non-empty\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(when (not (eq? state 'paused))\n  (next 'fetch ctx))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; closed cond: explicit \"not connected\" arm rather than a negated catch-all\n(cond\n  ((eq? status 'connected)            (next 'fetch ctx))\n  ((not (eq? status 'connected))      (escalate 'service-not-yet-wired null)))\n```\n*Source: `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/personal/daily-news-brief.sks:118-125`*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "or"
  :signature "(or expr1 expr2 ...)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** the first truthy value, or `#f`.\n**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/interp.js:362-369`\n**Side effects:** short-circuits left-to-right.\n**Wired:** yes\n\nShort-circuit disjunction. Returns the first non-`#f` value (which is\nNOT necessarily `#t`). In tail position, the last disjunct is itself\nin tail.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n;; pick the first present field\n(or (assq ':override ctx)\n    'no-override)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n;; fallback chain\n(let ((from (or (ctx-get 'shop-id ctx)\n                (ctx-get 'default-shop ctx)\n                'unknown-shop)))\n  (act 'etsy/listings (list from) 'render))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; guard with side-effect-free fallback\n(if (or (eq? status 'rate-limited)\n        (eq? status 'quota-exhausted))\n    (after 60 'fetch ctx)\n    (next 'check-fetch ctx))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "set!"
  :signature "(set! name value)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** undefined (effect: mutates an existing binding).\n**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/interp.js:279-281`\n**Side effects:** mutates the env binding.\n**Wired:** yes\n\nMutates an EXISTING binding. Throws on an unbound name. Substrate-\nfrozen names (the built-in verb roster) reject `set!` post-freeze —\nthat's the protective wall in `Env.set` interp.js:70-82.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(define counter 0)\n(set! counter (+ counter 1))\n;; → counter is now 1\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n;; close over a counter in a higher-order pass\n(let ((seen 0))\n  (for-each (lambda (r) (set! seen (+ seen 1)))\n            rows)\n  seen)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; mutate-in-closure pattern (rare — prefer pure ctx threading)\n(define (make-counter)\n  (let ((n 0))\n    (lambda ()\n      (set! n (+ n 1))\n      n)))\n(define tick (make-counter))\n(tick) (tick) (tick)\n;; → 3\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "unless"
  :signature "(unless test body...)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** the value of the last body form when test is `#f`, else undefined.\n**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/interp.js:370-377`\n**Side effects:** evaluates body only when test is false.\n**Wired:** yes\n\nInverse of `when`. Body is in tail position.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(unless (null? rows)\n  (table rows '(id title price)))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(unless (eq? (ctx-get 'tier ctx) 'free)\n  (act 'sakura/cloud-reason (list ':context ctx) 'check-finding))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; gate a financial side-effect; tail position is the act descriptor\n(unless (or (eq? state 'vacation) (eq? state 'paused))\n  (act 'etsy/reprice (list listing-id new-price) 'check-reprice))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "when"
  :signature "(when test body...)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** the value of the last body form when test is truthy, else undefined.\n**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/interp.js:346-353`\n**Side effects:** evaluates body only when test is truthy.\n**Wired:** yes\n\nSingle-arm conditional. Body is in tail position. Prefer when the\n\"false\" branch is genuinely a no-op.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(when (null? rows)\n  (escalate 'no-data null))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(when (eq? (ctx-get 'tier ctx) 'magic)\n  (next 'assemble-quarter-memo ctx))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; emit a chip then queue an envelope, only when finding is non-trivial\n(when (and (pair? finding) (> (length finding) 1))\n  (begin\n    (card-emit 'engine 'the-living-business-plan-ready (length finding))\n    (envelope-queue (list 'the-living-business-plan ':finding finding))))\n```\n*Source: condensed from `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/magic/the-living-business-plan.sks:314-321`*\n\n---\n\n## 2. List + sequence primitives\n\nAll §2 entries are bound by `makeBaseEnv` in\n`curator-web/src/scheme/base.js`. They are PURE — no env effects,\nno app state. Higher-order procedures re-enter the evaluator through\n`apply`, sharing the same fuel budget so no escape is possible.\n\n**Wired:** yes (all 20+ shipped + tested).\n**Side effects:** none."
)

(core-form
  :name "append"
  :signature "(append list1 list2 ...)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** a new list — the concatenation, left-to-right.\n**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/base.js:170`\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(append '(a b) '(c d))\n;; → (a b c d)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(append topics (list 'fallback-topic))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; flatten one level\n(reduce append '() rows-of-rows)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "assoc"
  :signature "(assoc key alist)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** the matching `(key value)` pair, or `#f`.\n**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/base.js:293`\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(assoc 'price '((title \"vase\") (price 19.99) (qty 2)))\n;; → (price 19.99)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(let ((entry (assoc ':topic cortex-result)))\n  (if entry (cadr entry) 'no-topic))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; deep-equal key match; nested alist\n(assoc '(:topic news-brief :date today)\n       (cortex/recall-cache))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "car"
  :signature "(car list)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** the first element.\n**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/base.js:46`\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(car '(a b c))\n;; → a\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(let ((first-row (car rows)))\n  (paint-text (assq 'title first-row) '#anchor/center))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; conway/additive-blend style — pulls hex bytes via cadr/caddr (see base.js:50-51)\n(let ((c (car palette)))\n  (list (hex-byte c 1) (hex-byte c 3) (hex-byte c 5)))\n```\n*;; generated example, modelled on `curator-web/src/scheme/conway.js:1205` callers*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "cdr"
  :signature "(cdr list)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** the list minus its first element.\n**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/base.js:47`\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(cdr '(a b c))\n;; → (b c)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n;; drop the head, keep the rest\n(map (lambda (row) (cdr row)) rows)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; tail-recursive walk; uses TCO in interp.js\n(define (count-rest acc lst)\n  (if (null? lst) acc (count-rest (+ acc 1) (cdr lst))))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "cons"
  :signature "(cons head tail)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** a new list with `head` prepended to `tail`.\n**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/base.js:45`\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(cons 'a '(b c))\n;; → (a b c)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n;; prepend a fresh row\n(cons new-row existing-rows)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; build a quoted on-result-symbol payload from a runtime computed kind\n(cons 'finding (cons (ctx-result ctx) '()))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "filter"
  :signature "(filter pred list)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** a new list of elements where `(pred x)` is not `#f`.\n**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/base.js:67`\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(filter (lambda (n) (> n 0)) '(-2 -1 0 1 2))\n;; → (1 2)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n;; keep only published listings\n(filter (lambda (row) (eq? (assq 'state row) 'active))\n        listings)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; chain with sort + take to top-N by score\n(take (sort (filter (lambda (r) (assq 'score r))\n                    rows)\n            (lambda (a b) (> (assq 'score a) (assq 'score b))))\n      3)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "for-each"
  :signature "(for-each fn list)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** undefined.\n**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/base.js:65`\n**Side effects:** invokes `fn` on each element, in order.\n**Wired:** yes\n\nEffectful iteration. Use when you want the side effects and don't need\nthe result list (use `map` for that).\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(for-each (lambda (sprite-id)\n            (sprite sprite-id (rest)))\n          '(blossom rose coral))\n```\n*;; generated example, using real sprite ids from `spriteBehaviors.js:120-136`*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n;; paint a heart at each anchor\n(for-each (lambda (anchor)\n            (paint-heart anchor 'sakura-pink))\n          anchors)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; emit chip per shop, then return ctx\n(for-each (lambda (shop)\n            (card-emit 'engine 'free-shipping-shop-ok shop))\n          (ctx-get 'connected-shops ctx))\n```\n*;; generated example, modelled on `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/scenes/free-shipping-standard.sks:65`*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "length"
  :signature "(length list)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** the number of elements.\n**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/base.js:62`\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(length '(a b c d))\n;; → 4\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(card-emit 'engine 'daily-brief-ready (length rows))\n```\n*Source: `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/personal/daily-news-brief.sks:197`*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; conditional on a per-tier accrual count\n(when (>= (length deltas) 12)\n  (next 'assemble-quarter-memo ctx))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "list"
  :signature "(list elem1 elem2 ...)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** a new list.\n**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/base.js:44`\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(list 'a 'b 'c)\n;; → (a b c)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(act 'etsy/receipts (list 'this-week) 'check-actuals)\n```\n*Source: `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/magic/the-living-business-plan.sks:158-160`*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; build a tools list for a reasoning session\n(act 'lacuna/ask\n     (list \"Reconcile actuals against prior plan.\"\n           ':tools '((etsy/receipts) (etsy/ledger) (cortex/recall))\n           ':budget 'magic)\n     'check-finding)\n```\n*Source: condensed from `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/magic/the-living-business-plan.sks:247-258`*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "map"
  :signature "(map fn list)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** a new list — `fn` applied to each element.\n**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/base.js:66`\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(map (lambda (n) (* n 2)) '(1 2 3))\n;; → (2 4 6)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n;; titles of each row\n(map (lambda (row) (assq 'title row)) rows)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; per-receipt revenue extraction, summed\n(sum (map (lambda (r) (assq 'amount r)) receipts))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "member"
  :signature "(member x list)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** the tail of `list` starting at `x`, or `#f`.\n**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/base.js:292`\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(member 'b '(a b c))\n;; → (b c)\n(member 'z '(a b c))\n;; → #f\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(when (member 'magic supported-tiers)\n  (next 'render-magic ctx))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; deep-equal match against an alist key\n(if (member topic (ctx-get 'followed-topics ctx))\n    (next 'fetch ctx)\n    (escalate 'topic-not-followed null))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "range"
  :signature "(range a b)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** the list `(a a+1 ... b-1)`.\n**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/base.js:63`\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(range 0 5)\n;; → (0 1 2 3 4)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n;; iterate over 7 days for a brief\n(map (lambda (d) (act 'web-search (list 'headline d) 'check-fetch))\n     (range 0 7))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; deterministic-numbered IDs for paint anchors\n(for-each (lambda (i)\n            (paint-heart (list 'anchor i) 'sakura-pink))\n          (range 0 12))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "reduce"
  :signature "(reduce fn init list)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** the accumulated value.\n**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/base.js:68`\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(reduce + 0 '(1 2 3 4))\n;; → 10\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(reduce (lambda (acc r) (+ acc (assq 'amount r)))\n        0\n        receipts)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; fold rows into a tagged structure (price-ladder-style)\n(reduce (lambda (acc r)\n          (let ((p (assq 'price r)))\n            (if p (cons p acc) acc)))\n        '()\n        listings)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "reverse"
  :signature "(reverse list)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** a new list, reversed.\n**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/base.js:171`\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(reverse '(a b c))\n;; → (c b a)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n;; newest-last → newest-first\n(reverse (sort log (lambda (a b) (< (assq 'ts a) (assq 'ts b)))))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; accumulate forward, reverse at the tail (tail-recursive idiom)\n(let loop ((items items) (out '()))\n  (if (null? items)\n      (reverse out)\n      (loop (cdr items) (cons (transform (car items)) out))))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---\n\n## 3. Math + numeric\n\nAll §3 entries are bound by `makeBaseEnv`\n(`curator-web/src/scheme/base.js`). Pure value transforms; no state.\n\n**Wired:** yes — every one shipped.\n**Side effects:** none."
)

(core-form
  :name "abs"
  :signature "(abs x)"
  :doc-body "**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/base.js:35`\n\nAbsolute value.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(abs -7)  ;; → 7\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n;; distance-magnitude per axis\n(abs (- new-price old-price))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; alarm if margin-change magnitude exceeds threshold\n(when (> (abs (pct-change old-margin new-margin)) 5)\n  (escalate 'margin-drift (list ':delta (- new-margin old-margin))))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "clamp"
  :signature "(clamp x lo hi)"
  :doc-body "**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/base.js:192`\n\nBound `x` to `[lo, hi]`.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(clamp 150 0 100)  ;; → 100\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n;; sprite turn — engine clamps 0..360 by spec\n(sprite 'rose (turn (clamp degrees 0 360)))\n```\n*;; generated example, real sprite id from `spriteBehaviors.js:122`*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; coerce a tier float into a discrete percentage\n(round (clamp (* score 100) 0 100))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "expt"
  :signature "(expt b p)"
  :doc-body "**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/base.js:183`\n\nExponentiation, `b^p`.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(expt 2 10)  ;; → 1024\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n;; log-spaced price ladder anchor\n(expt 2 (/ rung 4))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; compound growth over n weeks\n(* start (expt (+ 1 weekly-rate) weeks))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "floor"
  :signature "(floor x)"
  :doc-body "**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/base.js:184`\n\nRound down.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(floor 3.7)  ;; → 3\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n;; integer multiplier\n(floor (/ total seg-count))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; bucket index for a histogram\n(floor (* (- value lo) buckets (/ 1 (- hi lo))))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "lerp"
  :signature "(lerp a b t)"
  :doc-body "**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/base.js:193`\n\nLinear interpolation; `t=0` → `a`, `t=1` → `b`.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(lerp 0 100 0.5)  ;; → 50\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n;; midway colour value\n(lerp red-channel target-red 0.3)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; ease-in-out tween — sample at t=0..1\n(map (lambda (t) (lerp begin end (* t t (- 3 (* 2 t)))))\n     (map (lambda (i) (/ i 9)) (range 0 10)))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "mean"
  :signature "(mean list)"
  :doc-body "**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/base.js:209`\n\nArithmetic mean; empty list → 0.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(mean '(2 4 6))  ;; → 4\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n;; average daily orders\n(mean (map (lambda (r) (assq 'orders r)) day-rows))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; rolling average using sma helper (base.js:221)\n(sma (map (lambda (r) (assq 'price r)) listings) 7)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "modulo"
  :signature "(modulo x y)"
  :doc-body "**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/base.js:30`\n\nPositive remainder (Scheme convention).\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(modulo 10 3)   ;; → 1\n(modulo -1 4)   ;; → 3 (positive!)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n;; every 13th week — quarter-end accrual\n(when (= 0 (modulo week-index 13))\n  (next 'assemble-quarter-memo ctx))\n```\n*;; generated example, real pattern from `the-living-business-plan.sks:65`*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; alternate rows for striped paint\n(for-each (lambda (i)\n            (if (= 0 (modulo i 2))\n                (paint-rect i 0 1 1 'lilac)\n                (paint-rect i 0 1 1 'mint)))\n          (range 0 16))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "sqrt"
  :signature "(sqrt x)"
  :doc-body "**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/base.js:177`\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(sqrt 16)  ;; → 4\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n;; euclidean distance helper (also see `dist`, base.js:237)\n(sqrt (+ (* dx dx) (* dy dy)))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; standard deviation pass\n(let ((m (mean xs)))\n  (sqrt (mean (map (lambda (x) (let ((d (- x m))) (* d d))) xs))))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "sum"
  :signature "(sum list)"
  :doc-body "**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/base.js:208`\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(sum '(1 2 3 4))  ;; → 10\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n;; week revenue total\n(sum (map (lambda (r) (assq 'amount r)) receipts))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; weighted score across category buckets\n(sum (map (lambda (b) (* (assq 'weight b) (assq 'value b)))\n          score-buckets))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---\n\n## 4. Cart spine\n\nThe state-machine spine that every cart runs on. All §4 entries are\ninstalled by `installCartPrelude`\n(`curator-web/src/scheme/cartPrelude.js:42-136`). Each is a PURE\nDESCRIPTOR CONSTRUCTOR: it returns a tagged list the driver\nintercepts. The cart NEVER touches the world directly.\n\n**Wired:** yes (all 7 shipped, lint-validated).\n**Side effects:** none in the verb itself; the driver dispatches."
)

(core-form
  :name "act"
  :signature "(act verb args on-result-symbol)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** `(act <verb> <args> <on-result-symbol>)` — a tool-call descriptor.\n**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/cartPrelude.js:97-102`\n**Lint:** on-result MUST be a quoted symbol (cartLint.js:75-105).\n\nThe cart's only side-effect channel. The driver intercepts, dispatches\nthe real call, threads the response into `ctx` via `'last-result`, and\njumps to the named state.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(define (fetch ctx)\n  (act 'etsy/listings (list 'active) 'render))\n```\n*Source: `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/etsy/age-distribution.sks:28-29`*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(define (recall-topics ctx)\n  (act 'cortex/recall (list '(:topic followed-topics)) 'check-topics))\n```\n*Source: `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/personal/daily-news-brief.sks:94-95`*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n(define (lacuna-ask ctx)\n  (act 'lacuna/ask\n       (list \"Reconcile actuals against prior strategy. Revise projections.\"\n             ':tools '((etsy/receipts) (etsy/ledger) (cortex/recall))\n             ':context (list ':receipts (ctx-get 'receipts ctx)\n                             ':prior    (ctx-get 'prior-plan ctx))\n             ':budget 'magic)\n       'check-finding))\n```\n*Source: condensed from `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/magic/the-living-business-plan.sks:247-258`*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "after"
  :signature "(after seconds state-symbol ctx)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** `(after <seconds> <state> <ctx>)` — sleep descriptor.\n**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/cartPrelude.js:86-87`\n\nSleep, then resume at the named state. Standard back-off after a\n`'rate-limited` result.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(after 30 'fetch ctx)\n```\n*Source: `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/etsy/age-distribution.sks:35`*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(cond\n  ((eq? r 'rate-limited)    (after 60 'fetch ctx))\n  ((eq? r 'quota-exhausted) (escalate 'answers-quota null))\n  (else                     (next 'render ctx)))\n```\n*Source: condensed from `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/personal/daily-news-brief.sks:144-151`*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; exponential back-off via ctx counter\n(let ((tries (or (ctx-get 'tries ctx) 0)))\n  (after (* 30 (expt 2 tries))\n         'fetch\n         (ctx-set 'tries (+ tries 1) ctx)))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "ctx-get"
  :signature "(ctx-get key ctx)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** the value bound to `key`, or `null`.\n**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/cartPrelude.js:108-115`\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(ctx-get 'topics ctx)\n```\n*Source: `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/personal/daily-news-brief.sks:134`*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(let ((anchors    (ctx-get 'anchors ctx))\n      (copy-lines (ctx-get 'copy-lines ctx)))\n  (paint-arrow 'price-ladder-card ':anchors anchors ':labels copy-lines))\n```\n*Source: `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/pink/pink-price-ladder-suggest.sks:277-283`*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; nested ctx threading\n(let ((receipts (ctx-get 'receipts ctx))\n      (ledger   (ctx-get 'ledger ctx))\n      (prior    (ctx-get 'prior-plan ctx))\n      (override (ctx-get 'override ctx)))\n  (act 'lacuna/ask\n       (list \"Reconcile.\"\n             ':context (list ':receipts receipts ':ledger ledger\n                             ':prior prior ':override override))\n       'check-finding))\n```\n*Source: condensed from `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/magic/the-living-business-plan.sks:247-258`*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "ctx-result"
  :signature "(ctx-result ctx)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** the value of `'last-result` in `ctx`, or `null`.\n**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/cartPrelude.js:127-133`\n\nThe driver writes the result of the last `act` here. Most check-states\nread it first.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(define (check-state ctx)\n  (let ((state (ctx-result ctx)))\n    ...))\n```\n*Source: `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/magic/the-living-business-plan.sks:116-117`*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(define (render ctx)\n  (let ((rows (ctx-result ctx)))\n    (cond\n      ((null? rows)              (escalate 'no-data null))\n      ((eq? rows 'rate-limited)  (after 30 'fetch ctx))\n      (else                      (begin (table rows '(id title price))\n                                        (done))))))\n```\n*Source: `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/etsy/age-distribution.sks:31-38`*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n(define (check-finding ctx)\n  (let ((finding (ctx-result ctx)))\n    (cond\n      ((null? finding)                  (escalate 'service-not-yet-wired null))\n      ((eq? finding 'rate-limited)      (after 120 'lacuna-ask ctx))\n      ((eq? finding 'cloud-tier-required) (escalate 'service-not-connected null))\n      ((not (pair? finding))            (escalate 'sakura-garbled null))\n      (else (next 'remember (ctx-set 'finding finding ctx))))))\n```\n*Source: `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/magic/the-living-business-plan.sks:265-283`*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "ctx-set"
  :signature "(ctx-set key value ctx)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** a NEW ctx with `key`→`value`.\n**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/cartPrelude.js:118-122`\n\nImmutable update — returns a new assoc-list. The old `ctx` is\nunchanged.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(ctx-set 'topics topics ctx)\n```\n*Source: `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/personal/daily-news-brief.sks:107`*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(next 'check-cortex-cache\n      (ctx-set 'state state ctx))\n```\n*Source: `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/magic/the-living-business-plan.sks:128`*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; layered ctx updates threaded through one state\n(next 'fetch-ledger\n      (ctx-set 'receipts receipts\n               (ctx-set 'shop-id shop-id ctx)))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "done"
  :signature "(done)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** `(done)` — terminal descriptor.\n**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/cartPrelude.js:77`\n\nCart finished cleanly. The driver releases the worker and records\nsuccess.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(done)\n```\n*Source: `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/etsy/age-distribution.sks:37`*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(define (render ctx)\n  (let ((rows (ctx-result ctx)))\n    (table rows '(listing-id title metric value))\n    (done)))\n```\n*Source: `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/etsy/age-distribution.sks:31-38`*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; emit chip + envelope, then done as the tail of the cart\n(define (render ctx)\n  (let ((finding (ctx-get 'finding ctx)))\n    (card-emit 'engine 'the-living-business-plan-ready (length finding))\n    (envelope-queue (list 'the-living-business-plan ':finding finding))\n    (done)))\n```\n*Source: `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/magic/the-living-business-plan.sks:314-321`*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "escalate"
  :signature "(escalate kind detail)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** `(escalate <kind> <detail>)` — pause descriptor.\n**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/cartPrelude.js:78-79`\n**Lint:** kind MUST be a quoted symbol (cartLint.js:107-119).\n\nThe cart cannot proceed honestly. The driver pauses; the operator\nsurface decides what to do next.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(escalate 'shop-not-connected null)\n```\n*Source: `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/etsy/age-distribution.sks:25`*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(escalate 'state-blocks-spend 'vacation)\n```\n*Source: `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/magic/the-living-business-plan.sks:122`*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n(escalate 'service-not-yet-wired\n          '(:status not-wired :reason \"lacuna-session-returned-null\"))\n```\n*Source: `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/magic/the-living-business-plan.sks:268-270`*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "next"
  :signature "(next state-symbol ctx)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** `(next <state> <ctx>)` — advance descriptor.\n**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/cartPrelude.js:75-76`\n\nMove to the named state with `ctx` as input. The driver looks up the\nmatching `(define (<state> ctx) …)`.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(next 'fetch ctx)\n```\n*Source: `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/etsy/age-distribution.sks:26`*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(next 'check-cortex-cache (ctx-set 'state state ctx))\n```\n*Source: `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/magic/the-living-business-plan.sks:128`*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n(else (next 'remember\n            (ctx-set 'finding finding ctx)))\n```\n*Source: `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/magic/the-living-business-plan.sks:282-283`*\n\n---\n\n## 5. Cortex verbs\n\nCortex verbs are NOT bound as Scheme functions. They are\nACT-DISPATCHED — invoked via `(act 'cortex/recall …)`. The driver\nroutes them to the Cortex memory graph. Card-manifest sources for\nthe verb roster: `curator-web/src/components/cards/cortexManifest.js`\nand the per-tier cart manifests (`carts/<tier>/manifest.js` —\n`cortex/recall`, `cortex/remember`, `cortex/forget`).\n\n**Wired:** partial — `recall`, `remember`, `forget` shipped; deeper\nverbs (`cosine-topk`, `walk`, `multi-store-publish`, `diff-against-shops`)\nare surfaced in cart manifests but resolve to `'service-not-yet-wired`\nor a per-cart lacuna-relay at this writing."
)

(core-form
  :name "etsy/listings"
  :signature "(etsy/listings [state])"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** queued intent `(ok queued (:verb etsy/listings …))`.\n**Backing:** declared `shops.js:19`; runtime-bound at\n`shopVerbsRuntime.js:594-598`.\n**Wired:** yes (read).\n\nList the seller's listings, optionally filtered by state.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(act 'etsy/listings (list 'active) 'render)\n```\n*Source: pattern from `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/etsy/age-distribution.sks:29`*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(define (fetch ctx)\n  (act 'etsy/listings (list 'all) 'check-listings))\n```\n*;; generated example, real verb name from `shops.js:19`*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; chain: list → per-listing inventory pull\n(define (after-listings ctx)\n  (let ((rows (ctx-result ctx)))\n    (act 'etsy/inventory (list (assq 'listing-id (car rows))) 'check-inv)))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "etsy/receipts"
  :signature "(etsy/receipts [state])"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** queued intent.\n**Backing:** `shops.js:37`; bound at `shopVerbsRuntime.js:594`.\n**Wired:** yes (read).\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(act 'etsy/receipts (list 'this-week) 'check-actuals)\n```\n*Source: `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/magic/the-living-business-plan.sks:158-160`*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(act 'etsy/receipts (list 'today) 'count-today)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n(act 'etsy/receipts (list 'this-week)\n     'reconcile-against-cortex-checkpoint)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "paint-arrow"
  :signature "(paint-arrow from to colour)"
  :doc-body "```verb-card paint-arrow\n```\n\n**Returns:** PaintHandle (kind 'arrow).\n**Backing:** `curator-web/src/paint/primitives/arrow.js`; registered via\n`paint/index.js:100`.\n**Wired:** yes.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(paint-arrow '#anchor/center '#anchor/right 'sakura-pink)\n```\n*;; generated example, anchors from `make-character` address grammar*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(paint-arrow 'price-ladder-card\n             ':anchors  anchors\n             ':labels   copy-lines\n             ':glow     'warm-amber)\n```\n*Source: `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/pink/pink-price-ladder-suggest.sks:280-283`*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; arrow per row, colour-mapped by delta sign\n(for-each\n  (lambda (row)\n    (paint-arrow (assq 'from row)\n                 (assq 'to row)\n                 (if (> (assq 'delta row) 0) 'mint 'rose)))\n  rows)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "paint-burst"
  :signature "(paint-burst at colour ms)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** PaintHandle (kind 'burst, animated).\n**Backing:** `paint/primitives/burst.js`; `paint/index.js:112`.\n**Wired:** yes. powerTier 'animate' (skips at quarter/paused).\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(paint-burst '#anchor/center 'sakura-pink 800)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(paint-burst src 'sakura 600)\n```\n*Source: pattern from `carts/scenes/transfer-shop-to-shop.test.js:9`*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; coordinated burst at every connected shop card\n(for-each (lambda (shop-card)\n            (paint-burst shop-card 'sakura-pink 500))\n          (ctx-get 'connected-shop-cards ctx))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "paint-clear"
  :signature "(paint-clear [region])"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** PaintHandle (kind 'clear).\n**Backing:** `paint/primitives/clear.js`; `paint/index.js:91`.\n**Wired:** yes. EVERYWHERE-clear (no region or `'everywhere`) also\nwipes the scene-graph registry (paint/index.js:163-166).\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(paint-clear)\n;; → clears all paints, registry, returns handle\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n;; clear one region\n(paint-clear (list ':bbox 0 0 800 200))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; clean up after a scene exits\n(begin\n  (paint-clear)\n  (surface-restore)\n  (done))\n```\n*Source: pattern from `carts/scenes/transfer-shop-to-shop.test.js:155`*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "paint-emoji"
  :signature "(paint-emoji glyph at)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** PaintHandle (kind 'emoji).\n**Backing:** `paint/primitives/emoji.js`; `paint/index.js:114`.\n**Wired:** yes — uses the dot-matrix emoji atlas.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(paint-emoji '💃 '#anchor/center)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n;; emoji at every flower's address\n(for-each (lambda (a) (paint-emoji '🌸 a))\n          (list '#sprite/blossom '#sprite/rose '#sprite/coral))\n```\n*;; generated example, real sprite ids*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; thought-bubble decoration around a sprite\n(let ((bubble-points (around '#sprite/blossom 32 12)))\n  (for-each (lambda (p) (paint-emoji '💭 p)) bubble-points))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "paint-fireworks"
  :signature "(paint-fireworks at colour-set ms)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** PaintHandle (kind 'fireworks, animated).\n**Backing:** `paint/primitives/fireworks.js`; `paint/index.js:111`.\n**Wired:** yes.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(paint-fireworks '#anchor/center (list 'sakura-pink 'lilac) 1500)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(when (eq? (ctx-result ctx) 'sold)\n  (paint-fireworks '#card/sale-card (list 'mint 'sakura-pink) 1200))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; celebration at every newly-sold listing\n(for-each (lambda (id)\n            (paint-fireworks (list 'card id)\n                             (list 'sakura-pink 'lilac 'mint)\n                             1500))\n          (ctx-get 'newly-sold-ids ctx))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "paint-flow"
  :signature "(paint-flow from to glyph count [colour])"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** PaintHandle (kind 'flow, animated).\n**Backing:** `paint/primitives/flow.js`; `paint/index.js:107`.\n**Wired:** yes. The transfer scene's grayscale-channel verb.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(paint-flow 'card-a 'card-b 'glyph/heart 8 'sakura-pink)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n;; flow from each shop to the central card\n(for-each (lambda (shop-card)\n            (paint-flow shop-card '#card/cortex 'glyph/dot 5 'mint))\n          (ctx-get 'connected-shops ctx))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; transfer-scene-style: dots flowing src → dst with glow at each end\n(begin\n  (paint-glow src 'sakura 600)\n  (paint-glow dst 'sakura 600)\n  (paint-flow src dst 'glyph/box 12 'sakura-pink))\n```\n*Source: pattern from `carts/scenes/transfer-shop-to-shop.sks:132-133`*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "paint-glow"
  :signature "(paint-glow target colour ms)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** PaintHandle (kind 'glow, animated).\n**Backing:** `paint/primitives/glow.js`; `paint/index.js:108`.\n**Wired:** yes. The canonical Sakura signature (8px sakura-magic\nglow per [[feedback_sakura_action_glow]]).\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(paint-glow '#anchor/center 'sakura-pink 1200)\n```\n*Source: `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/scenes/demo/flower-orbit-demo.sks:170`*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(paint-glow '#sprite/blossom 'sakura-pink 1200)\n```\n*Source: `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/scenes/demo/flower-orbit-demo.sks:170`*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; brief glow around every newly-sold listing, sequenced\n(for-each (lambda (id)\n            (paint-glow (list 'card id) 'sakura-pink 800))\n          (ctx-get 'newly-sold-ids ctx))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "paint-heart"
  :signature "(paint-heart at [colour])"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** PaintHandle (kind 'heart).\n**Backing:** `paint/primitives/heart.js`; `paint/index.js:102`.\n**Wired:** yes.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(paint-heart '#anchor/center 'sakura-pink)\n```\n*;; generated example, real anchor address*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n;; one heart per loved listing\n(for-each (lambda (l) (paint-heart (list 'card l) 'sakura-pink))\n          (ctx-get 'loved ctx))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; cascading hearts around a sprite\n(let ((pts (around '#sprite/coral 20 8)))\n  (for-each (lambda (p) (paint-heart p 'sakura-pink)) pts))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "paint-highlight"
  :signature "(paint-highlight card-addr [colour])"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** PaintHandle (kind 'highlight).\n**Backing:** `paint/primitives/highlight.js`; `paint/index.js:104`.\n**Wired:** yes.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(paint-highlight '#card/cortex 'mint)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(paint-highlight (list 'card listing-id) 'warm-amber)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n(for-each (lambda (id)\n            (paint-highlight (list 'card id) 'sakura-pink))\n          (ctx-get 'at-risk ctx))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "paint-grid"
  :signature "(paint-grid surface palette)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** integer (count of cells painted).\n**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/grid.js:695`.\n**Wired:** yes. The Canvas Dreams cellular substrate.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(paint-grid 'desktop (palette 'sakura))\n```\n*;; generated example, palette = `curator-web/src/scheme/palette.js`*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(define (start ctx)\n  (paint-grid 'desktop 'sakura)\n  (next 'await-tap ctx))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; on-canvas-pattern read after grid paint\n(begin\n  (paint-grid 'desktop (palette 'mint))\n  (on-canvas-pattern 'wave (lambda (ev) (paint-burst ev 'lilac 400))))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "paint-marquee"
  :signature "(paint-marquee text band speed)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** PaintHandle (kind 'marquee, animated).\n**Backing:** `paint/primitives/marquee.js`; `paint/index.js:90`.\n**Wired:** yes. The narrating bottom-band per\n[[curator-canvas-is-sakuras-home]].\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(paint-marquee \"Five flowers · slow waltz\" 'bottom 4000)\n```\n*Source: `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/scenes/demo/flower-orbit-demo.sks:162`*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n;; per-state narration\n(paint-marquee (ctx-get 'narration ctx) 'top 3000)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; sequenced marquees per scene beat\n(begin\n  (paint-marquee \"Reading shops...\" 'bottom 2000)\n  (act 'etsy/listings '() 'check)\n  (paint-marquee \"Cross-referencing...\" 'bottom 2000))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "paint-point-at"
  :signature "(paint-point-at card-addr)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** PaintHandle (kind 'point-at).\n**Backing:** `paint/primitives/point-at.js`; `paint/index.js:101`.\n**Wired:** yes.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(paint-point-at '#card/cortex)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(paint-point-at (list 'card (ctx-get 'highlight-id ctx)))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; chained point-at + flow + glow\n(begin\n  (paint-point-at '#card/sale-card)\n  (paint-flow '#card/cortex '#card/sale-card 'glyph/dot 6 'sakura-pink)\n  (paint-glow '#card/sale-card 'sakura-pink 800))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "paint-spiral"
  :signature "(paint-spiral centre radius turns colour)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** PaintHandle.\n**Backing:** `paint/primitives/spiral.js`; `paint/index.js:97`.\n**Wired:** yes.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(paint-spiral '#anchor/center 120 3 'lilac)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(paint-spiral (list 'card listing-id) 80 2 'warm-amber)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; sized by score\n(paint-spiral '#anchor/center\n              (lerp 40 200 (clamp (ctx-get 'score ctx) 0 1))\n              3\n              'sakura-pink)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "paint-text"
  :signature "(paint-text text at [opts...])"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** PaintHandle (kind 'text).\n**Backing:** `paint/primitives/text.js`; `paint/index.js:89`.\n**Wired:** yes. Stroke-mode `'handwriting` paints dot-by-dot per\nSakura's voice (Sakura Magic per [[feedback-sakura-magic-signature]]).\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(paint-text \"Hello Surface\" '#anchor/center\n            ':stroke-mode 'handwriting\n            ':wpm 110)\n```\n*Source: `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/scenes/demo/dot-matrix-greeting.sks:84-86`*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(paint-text \"tap anywhere\" '#anchor/center\n            ':alpha 0.6)\n```\n*Source: `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/scenes/demo/falling-petals-on-tap.sks:81`*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; sakura's spoken-reply pattern — addressable dots, twinkle, motion\n(paint-text reply\n            '#anchor/sakura-mouth\n            ':stroke-mode 'handwriting\n            ':colour 'sakura-pink\n            ':twinkle #t\n            ':wpm 110)\n```\n*Source: pattern from [[project_sakura_reply_dot_matrix]] + dot-matrix-greeting.sks:84*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "sprite"
  :signature "(sprite name atom-or-combinator)"
  :doc-body "```verb-card sprite\n```\n\n**Returns:** `'ok` envelope if the atom lowers to a real verb;\n`'pending-visual` envelope otherwise.\n**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/spriteVerbs.js:393-431`.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(sprite 'blossom (carry \"vase-001\" 50 75))\n```\n*Source: pattern from `spriteVerbs.js:7` — lowers to `move-card`*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(sprite 'rose (in-order (turn 90) (flash \"glow\")))\n```\n*Source: example from `spriteVerbs.js:10`*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; quoted-list form is the ONLY way to reach `when` (collides with the\n;; interpreter special form). spriteVerbs.js:36 documents this.\n(sprite 'lilac '(when (rest) (flash glow)))\n```\n*Source: `curator-web/src/scheme/spriteVerbs.js:36`*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "sprites"
  :signature "(sprites who form...)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** envelope per-resolved-sprite or per-crowd.\n**Backing:** `spriteVerbs.js:436`.\n**Wired:** yes — family addressing through `the-pinks`,\n`the-purples`, `the-neutrals`, `everyone` (spriteVerbs.js:434).\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(sprites '(blossom rose coral) (rest))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(sprites 'the-pinks (gather '#anchor/center))\n```\n*;; generated example, family from spriteVerbs.js:433-434*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; everyone bows in sequence\n(sprites 'everyone\n         (in-order (bow)\n                   (wait-for 400)\n                   (rest)))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "carry"
  :signature "(carry id x y)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** lowers to `(move-card id x y)`.\n**Backing:** `spriteBehaviors.js:98` (atom); `cardVerbs.js:307`\n(move-card backing).\n**Wired:** yes.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(sprite 'blossom (carry \"vase-001\" 50 75))\n```\n*Source: `spriteVerbs.js:7`*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(sprite 'cedar (carry (ctx-get 'item-id ctx)\n                      (ctx-get 'target-x ctx)\n                      (ctx-get 'target-y ctx)))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n(for-each\n  (lambda (item)\n    (sprite 'gray (carry (assq 'id item) (assq 'x item) (assq 'y item))))\n  (ctx-get 'manifest ctx))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "dance"
  :signature "(dance 'clip-name)"
  :doc-body "**Backing:** declared in spriteBehaviors atoms list as a clip atom;\nnot yet wired to a clip player.\n**Wired:** no — `['pending-visual', …]` envelope; honest.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(sprite 'blossom (dance 'waltz))\n;; → pending-visual envelope, never an unannounced no-op\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(sprites 'the-pinks (dance 'flower-conga))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; honest fallback when the clip player isn't wired\n(let ((result (sprite 'rose (dance 'spin-finale))))\n  (cond\n    ((eq? (car result) 'pending-visual)\n       (sprite 'rose (in-order (turn 360) (rest))))\n    (else result)))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---\n\n## 9. Note + music verbs\n\nBound by `installNoteVerbs` (`curator-web/src/scheme/noteVerbs.js:92`).\nAudio is gated by a user gesture (`audioLive()`); first call without\ngesture returns `'pending-audio'` envelope — honest.\n\n**Wired:** yes (all 5 listed)."
)

(core-form
  :name "note"
  :signature "(note pitch [dur] [velocity])"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** `(ok (note … spec …))` or `(pending-audio …)`.\n**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/noteVerbs.js:96-123`.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(note 'c4 'quarter)\n```\n*Source: pattern from `noteVerbs.js:95`*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(note 'e4 'eighth 0.6)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; sequence of notes, audio-gated\n(for-each (lambda (p) (note p 'eighth 0.8))\n          '(c4 d4 e4 f4 g4 a4 b4 c5))\n```\n*Source: pattern from form/scale macro (primitives/macros.js:228-238)*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "note-place"
  :signature "(note-place pitch [stave] [clef])"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** `(ok (note … y … clef …))`.\n**Backing:** `noteVerbs.js:127-146`.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(note-place 'e4 0 'treble)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(note-place 'g4 1 'bass)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; place a sequence at known stave geometry\n(for-each (lambda (p) (note-place p 0 'treble))\n          '(c4 e4 g4))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "note-dots"
  :signature "(note-dots pitch [dur] [stave] [clef])"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** the deterministic `{x,y,fill}` cells of the note glyph.\n**Backing:** `noteVerbs.js:152-168`.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(note-dots 'e4 'quarter)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(let ((cells (note-dots 'f4 'eighth 0 'treble)))\n  (paint-dots cells))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; render the dot-matrix flag of a sixteenth note\n(let ((c (note-dots 'a4 'sixteenth 0 'treble)))\n  (paint-dots (assq 'dots c)))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "staff-lines"
  :signature "(staff-lines [w] [h] [clef])"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** geometry alist (lineCount, lineYs, gap, …).\n**Backing:** `noteVerbs.js:171-188`.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(staff-lines 600 200 'treble)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(let ((g (staff-lines 800 240 'bass)))\n  (paint-line (list 0 (assq 'firstLineY g))\n              (list 800 (assq 'firstLineY g))\n              'gray))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; render every line of the active stave\n(let ((g (staff-lines 800 240 'treble)))\n  (for-each (lambda (s)\n              (for-each (lambda (y)\n                          (paint-line (list 0 y) (list 800 y) 'gray))\n                        (assq 'lineYs s)))\n            (assq 'staves g)))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "tempo"
  :signature "(tempo bpm)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** `(ok (bpm … secondsPerBeat …))`.\n**Backing:** `noteVerbs.js:191-203`.\n**Side effects:** mutates the shared transport singleton.\n**Wired:** yes.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(tempo 96)\n```\n*;; generated example, pattern from noteVerbs.js:191*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(define (start ctx)\n  (tempo 120)\n  (next 'play ctx))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; slow ramp via a sequence of tempo calls\n(for-each (lambda (b) (tempo b))\n          '(120 110 100 90 80))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "card-do"
  :signature "(card-do card-addr verb args)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** `(ok …)` from the card's verb body.\n**Backing:** primitive at `curator-web/src/scheme/primitives/card.js:140 · env.define('card/do', cardDo, …)` and `:146 · env.define('card-do', cardDo, …)` (the slash form + legacy hyphen). Runtime resolution in `cardVerbs.js`.\n<!-- DOC-LIE-FIXED (SRE 2026-06-22): prior citation `coreVerbs.js:158-168` is STALE — `card-do` / `card-emit` / `card-ask` are NOT in `registry/coreVerbs.js` (grep confirms zero hits). They live in `primitives/card.js:140-170`. The same fix applies to the §card-emit and §card-ask entries below. -->\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(card-do shop 'set-free-shipping-threshold cents)\n```\n*Source: `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/scenes/free-shipping-standard.sks:22, 30`*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(card-do '#card/shop-services 'read-gmail-folder folder)\n```\n*Source: `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/scenes/email-inbox.sks:26`*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n(card-do shop 'unpublish-listing listing)\n```\n*Source: `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/scenes/reconcile-sold.sks:18, 29`*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "card-emit"
  :signature "(card-emit card-addr event-name payload)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** EmitHandle.\n**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/primitives/card.js:152 · env.define('card/emit', cardEmit, …)` and `:158 · env.define('card-emit', cardEmit, …)`.\n<!-- STALE-FIXED (SRE 2026-06-22): prior citation `coreVerbs.js:170-180` was wrong (verb is not in coreVerbs.js). -->\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(card-emit 'engine 'daily-brief-ready (length rows))\n```\n*Source: `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/personal/daily-news-brief.sks:197`*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(card-emit 'engine 'free-shipping-shop-ok shop)\n```\n*Source: `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/scenes/free-shipping-standard.sks:65`*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n(card-emit 'engine 'free-shipping-attempted\n           (list 'count (length shops)))\n```\n*Source: `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/scenes/free-shipping-standard.sks:50`*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "card-ask"
  :signature "(card-ask card-addr question)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** AnswerHandle (resolves async).\n**Backing:** `curator-web/src/scheme/primitives/card.js:164 · env.define('card/ask', cardAsk, …)` and `:170 · env.define('card-ask', cardAsk, …)`.\n<!-- STALE-FIXED (SRE 2026-06-22): prior citation `coreVerbs.js:182-192` was wrong. -->\n**Wired:** partial — primitive signature shipped, resolver lane\nin progress.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(card-ask '#card/inventory 'item-count)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(let ((q (card-ask '#card/cortex 'recent-topics)))\n  (next 'render (ctx-set 'topics q ctx)))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; chain ask → act on answer\n(card-ask '#card/shop-services 'connected-platforms)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "transfer"
  :signature "(transfer src-card dst-card item-ids)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** `(ok …)` or `(error …)` envelope.\n**Backing:** `cardVerbs.js:434`. Gated; financial when underlying op is.\n**Wired:** yes (with confirmation gate).\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(transfer src-card dst-card (list \"vase-001\"))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(transfer (ctx-get 'src ctx) (ctx-get 'dst ctx) (ctx-get 'items ctx))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; transfer-shop-to-shop scene pattern\n(begin\n  (paint-glow src 'sakura 600)\n  (paint-flow src dst 'glyph/box 8 'sakura-pink)\n  (transfer src dst items)\n  (paint-glow dst 'sakura 600))\n```\n*Source: pattern from `carts/scenes/transfer-shop-to-shop.sks:132-133`*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "summon"
  :signature "(summon kind)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** newly-summoned card id.\n**Backing:** `cardVerbs.js:684`.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n(summon 'chat)\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n(let ((c (summon 'shop-listing)))\n  (card-do c 'set-title \"rustic ceramic vase\"))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; summon, configure, focus\n(let ((c (summon 'sims)))\n  (begin\n    (card-do c 'load-sim 'pricing-ladder)\n    (card-focus! c)))\n```\n*;; generated example*\n\n---"
)

(core-form
  :name "scene/conveyor"
  :signature "(scene/conveyor src-addr dst-addr listing-count)"
  :doc-body "**Returns:** `{ok:#t, verb:'scene/conveyor, path, n, spawnedIds, staggerMs,\nlegDwellMs}` on success; `['escalate', 'service-not-yet-wired', {verb, reason}]`\nwhen src or dst cards aren't on the surface (`cardCenter` returns null).\n**Backing:** `curator-web/src/surface/scheme-host/sceneVerbs.js:556-675`;\nspawn/move primitives from `curator-web/src/sprites/flowers.js:237-266`.\n**Permission tier:** `paint`.\n**Wired:** yes — bespoke 3-leg arc (src → midpoint → dst), pink-to-green\ncolour transition halfway, source `sparkle + bloom` on launch, target\n`lift + glow` on arrival.\n**Honest-null:** unresolved card center → escalate; src or dst missing →\nescalate with the missing id named in the detail.\n**Cross-refs:** AUTOMATIONS `conveyor-belt` cart; ENGINEERING §AA.\n\n#### Novice\n```scheme\n;; ship 12 listings as flower sprites from one shop to another\n(scene/conveyor 'etsy-shop-1 'ebay-shop-1 12)\n```\n*Source: `curator-web/src/scheme/carts/scenes/conveyor-belt.sks:85`.*\n\n#### Intermediate\n```scheme\n;; resolve kinds to first instance, then run the belt\n(let ((src (car (card-find-by-kind 'etsy-shop)))\n      (dst (car (card-find-by-kind 'ebay-shop))))\n  (scene/conveyor src dst 24))\n```\n*Source: pattern from `conveyor-belt.sks:51-66`*\n\n#### Expert\n```scheme\n;; compose the belt with fade + bring-together so the scene reads as\n;; \"this shop's listings move there\"\n(surface-fade-others (list src dst))\n(surface-bring-together src dst)\n(scene/conveyor src dst 30)\n(surface-restore)\n```\n*Source: `conveyor-belt.sks:75-99`.*\n\n---"
)
